<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     07-23 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nikkei Rises Slightly After Worst Trading Week This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The main market barometer recouped early losses by
the close of half-day trading Saturday, but still finished lower at
the end of its worst trading week so far this year.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a sharp
391.13-point loser Friday, lost nearly 80 points shortly after
trading started, but claimed back lost ground to close the day at
27,301.34 points, up 16.33 points, or 0.059 percent.
   ``The index moved up mainly on profit-taking,'' said Michio
Katsumata, a spokesman for Nomura Securities, Japan's largest
brokerage. ``Hitachi and IC-related companies moved higher up,''
but otherwise ``the market was very quiet,'' the spokesman added.
   Shares from Sony, a leading consumer electronics maker, closed
at a historic high 6,460 yen, up 430 yen, surpassing its previous
record close reached Friday.
   Volume on the first section during the half-day session totaled
600 million shares.
   Despite Saturday's slight gain, the Nikkei index closed the week
down 612.45 points, or 2.19 percent, from a 27,913.79-point close
July 15. It had lost 513.09 points during Tuesday trading alone.
   ``People are anxious about higher interest rates,'' said
Katsumata. Banks in Europe and the United States have all raised
their rates, ``but only Japan is sticking to a lower rate,'' he
added.
   The market next week will just move ``up and down, up and
down,'' the spokesman predicted.
   The foreign exchange market is closed on Saturdays.
</TEXT>
