<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Fires-Prisoners 1stLd-Writethru a0770 07-23 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fires-Prisoners, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0770,0670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inmates Bolster Firefighting Forces</HEAD>
<HEAD>Retransmitting to add writethru designation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 3-4, `Rojas was...', to UPDATE with reward
offered, state of emergency declared, and to put fire acreage at
nearly 11,000, sted more than 12,500, reflecting official change
downward</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Forest Fire Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE GEISSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAIL ROAD FLAT, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They live by a brutal code of each
man for himself in prison, but in the middle of the woods they
learn to stand together against a fiery enemy that is not affected
by their crimes, color or gangs.
   ``We can't bring our problems with us to the fire lines,'' said
Rafael Rojas, 20, of Hollister, who is serving time in the
California Youth Authority for burglary.
   Rojas was among hundreds of state prisoners battling a pair of
arson-linked wildfires in heavy timber and brush near the Calaveras
County town of Rail Road Flat, 150 miles east of San Francisco.
Gov. George Deukmejian on Friday offered a $10,000 reward for the
capture of the arsonist and declared a state of emergency in the
county.
   Nearly 11,000 acres and six homes had been charred by Friday as
firefighters neared containment of the blazes, which have caused an
estimated $3.8 million damage to the drought-parched region since
Tuesday.
   Wielding shovels, saws and other hand tools, state fire Capt.
Bob Segura's strike team of inmates stood guard Thursday when the
fire burned out to a section of the more than 18 miles of
bare-earth control lines that firefighters had carved around the
fires.
   ``Let it burn right to the edge,'' Segura bellowed at the
inmates, clad in orange jumpsuits.
   Some of the inmates had to use ladders off a nearby state pumper
truck to climb up the near-vertical mountain toward the advancing
flames.
   Within minutes, he told his crew from the DeWitt Nelson CYA Camp
in Stockton that it seemed the line would hold for the time being.
   A few of the inmates slid down the slope hand over hand on a
fire hose. Others descended on the ladder. Hours after being dumped
off from a stifling personnel truck, it was finally break time.
   ``This is better than being behind walls,'' Rojas said in an
idle moment.
   Added team member Stevie Wright: ``Every time they ask, `You
want to go on a fire?' everybody stands up and says `Yeah.'''
Wright, 19, of Vallejo, is serving a sentence for possession of
cocaine.
   Inmates in the California Youth Authority or state prison
systems can volunteer to train as firefighters, but candidates are
screened to determine that they are suited and that they are low
security risks. Supervisors are unarmed, but even so there are very
few escape attempts.
   Correctional officer Alex Castillo, supervising state prisoners
in line for food at the Rail Road Flat fire camp after coming off
the lines, said most of the inmate firefighters are proud of what
they do.
   ``They like getting outside and later you hear them say things
like `Hey, we saved a house there,''' Castillo said.
   Added prisoner Myron Bright, with a sincere expression on his
face: ``It's a good way to pay my debt to society.'' Bright, 36,
who is serving time for insurance fraud, works out of the Green
Valley camp near Folsom Prison.
   Castillo said he and other crew supervisors make allowances
because of the nature of the work.
   ``If you're out there for more than a week at a time, they get
antsy. If you're real strict, they won't respond in a good way, and
you don't need tension on a fire,'' he said.
   The inmates said they realize the work is dangerous, but trust
the supervisors to keep them alive.
   One prisoner said the work has changed the direction of his life.
   ``I'd like to become a professional firefighter,'' said Wright.
``The first week I get out, I'm going to put in an application
somewhere.''
</TEXT>
