<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 0303EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BudgetDeficit     07-23 0660</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Budget Deficit,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Outlook Brighter for Reducing Federal Budget Deficit This Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong tax collections from businesses and
individuals are brightening the outlook for reducing the federal
budget deficit in 1988, with red ink for the fiscal year through
June running 2 percent lower than 1987.
   The Treasury Department on Friday reported a rare $9.5 billion
surplus last month, trimming the gap between what the government
has spent and what it has taken in during the first nine months of
the fiscal year to $118 billion, $2.4 billion less than during the
same period last year.
   If the deficit continued building at the same rate, it would
total $147.4 billion when the fiscal year ends Sept. 30, down
slightly from the $150.4 billion budget gap of last year and
substantially below the $221.1 billion record high set in 1986.
   ``Right now it looks like the chances are pretty good that we
can beat last year,'' said Mark Lasky, an economist with Data
Resources Inc., a Lexington, Mass., forecasting firm.
   Michael K. Evans, president of Evans Economics Inc. in
Washington, said higher-than-expected collection of individual
income taxes in both May and June are making projections earlier
this year by private economists of about a $160 billion deficit
look pessimistic.
   Quarterly individual tax payments due in June totaled $46.2
billion, up 14.1 percent from the same month in 1987. In May, tax
payments totaled $18 billion, nearly double the collections in May
1987.
   Corporate tax payments also rose, bolstered by strong profits of
U.S. companies. They totaled $18.3 billion in June, 18.6 percent
more than the same month a year ago.
   ``Nobody's really sure, including the Treasury, how this new tax
reform law works. My view is that the law actually is collecting
taxes that were going into tax shelters, which is what it's
supposed to do. In 1989, we'll see even more of this,'' Evans said.
   The major uncertainty remaining for this year, he said, is how
much the government will have to spend to help drought-stricken
farmers. Higher grain prices caused by drought-induced shortages
could lower government price support payments, but special aid to
farmers with shriveled crops could more than make up for that, he
said.
   The Treasury Department said federal spending last month totaled
$89.9 billion, a 7.7 percent increase over June 1987. However,
revenues surged a greater 19.8 percent above last year's level to
$99.3 billion.
   It was only the third surplus posted since the fiscal year began
in October. There was a surplus in January because Social Security
checks for the month were mailed at the end of December and another
in April as individual income tax payments poured in.
   For the first nine months, revenue totaled $681.1 billion, up
6.9 percent from last year, while spending was $799.1 billion, up
5.5 percent.
   The administration is forecasting a deficit of $146.7 billion,
just slightly above the $144 billion target in the Gramm-Rudman
budget balancing law. Next year's target is $136 billion.
   In June, the largest spending category was interest on the
national debt, followed by the military, Social Security, and other
programs in the Department of Health and Human Services.
   Military spending totaled $24.6 billion last month and $213.3
billion for the fiscal year so far, up 3.9 percent from the same
period a year ago.
   Spending for Social Security totaled $21.3 billion last month
and $160.8 billion for the past nine months, up 5.6 percent from
the same period in the 1987 fiscal year.
   The other programs in the Department of Health and Human
Services, including Medicare and Medicaid, spent $13.7 billion in
June and $118.7 billion so far this budget year, a 6 percent
increase over the first three quarters of fiscal 1987.
   Interest on the $2.5 trillion national debt totaled $31.6
billion last month and $169.1 billion so far this fiscal year, an
increase of 10.2 percent over the same period last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
