<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elizabeth Taylor says she could do without fame, but
since she's got it she will put it to good use.
   ``My life is outside films ... my life is now working for
AIDS,'' Miss Taylor said at a news conference Friday to promote
Franco Zeffirelli's new film, ``The Young Toscanini.''
   ``I don't really like being famous,'' she said. But in raising
money to combat aquired immune deficiency syndrome, she said, ``I
thought that using my fame could do some good.''
   The film, set in 1880s Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, stars American C.
Thomas Howell as the conductor as a young man and Sophie Ward, an
Englishwoman, as his lover. Miss Taylor, 56, has a supporting role
as an aging soprano, Nadina Bulicioff, inspired to return to
singing by an 18-year-old Arturo Toscanini.
