<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Burns-Meese     07-23 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burns-Meese,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Finds No Basis to Investigate Former Deputy Attorney
General Burns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department has found no basis to
investigate former Deputy Attorney General Arnold Burns for
promoting a former law partner for a judgeship, sources say.
   The criminal division's public integrity section reached the
conclusion after reviewing information about the relationship
between Burns and Stuart Summit, who has been nominated to the 2nd
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New York, according to the
sources, who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
   Burns and former criminal division chief William Weld plan to
testify before Congress Tuesday about their March 29 protest
resignations.
   They quit out of concern that the continued tenure of Attorney
General Edwin Meese III was hurting Justice Department operations
and morale.
   The Washington Times disclosed Burns' support for Summit last
month, suggesting the former deputy attorney general might have
violated federal conflict-of-interest law.
   The Washington Times this month disclosed that Weld had been the
focus of an internal Justice Department investigation into whether
he smoked marijuana at a wedding in 1982. Weld has emphatically
denied the allegation, made in an anonymous letter, and the
department's Office of Professional Responsibility closed the
matter.
   Congressional sources and sources close to the Justice
Department have said the leaking of unfavorable information about
Burns and Weld has been an attempt to discourage them from
testifying before the Senate Judiciary Committee.
   Burns was still receiving payments from the law firm and had
investments in limited partnerships with Summit at the time he was
urging Summit's nomination last year.
   When asked Friday about the public integrity section's decision,
Summit said he was ``not surprised, there never was anything to
it'' and said he was pleased about the outcome.
</TEXT>
