<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Jamaica-Violence     07-23 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jamaica-Violence,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Business Groups Call For End To Political Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LLOYD WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eighteen business and professional
organizations urged Jamaica's governing and main opposition parties
to end political violence between their supporters.
   The call to sign a peace agreement came after backers of the
opposition People's National Party stoned a busload of Jamaica
Labor Party supporters in a fishing village Sunday. Pro-government
militants then burned several shacks and chased one opposition
party member into the Caribbean, where he drowned.
   ``In a climate of violence and lawlessness, the entire nation
suffers from a drying up of investment and a decline in tourism and
other economic activity,'' read a joint statement issued Friday by
the 18 private sector groups.
   Several others were injured in separate attacks during the week
between rival bands of the two parties.
   More than 700 people died in political violence during the 1980
general elections.
   ``The signing of a joint declaration by the leaders and the
public commitment of their parties to law and order can no longer
be delayed for whatever reason,'' read the statement, which asked
that the agreement be signed by Aug. 1, Independence Day.
   Elections are expected in December, but Jamaica's Constitution
grants the prime minister a three-month grace period before calling
new elections.
   Prime Minister Edward Seaga was elected for a five-year term in
1983.
   ``We believe we speak for the law-abiding majority of this
country in saying we are sick of....the violence and partisan
point-scoring and are disappointed by our political leaders' delay
in fulfilling their national duty,'' the statement read.
   Michael Manley, a former prime minister and the opposition
leader, said Wednesday his party is ready to sign the agreement.
   ``Jamaica is demanding that both political parties work together
to bring the madness of political violence to an end,'' he said.
   Bruce Golding, chairman of the governing party, said the parties
must have the political will to end the violence before signing a
peace pact.
   Groups signing the statement included the Jamaica Hotel and
Tourist Association, the Medical Association, the Chamber of
Commerce, the Bankers Association, the Employers Federation and the
Exporters Association of Jamaica.
</TEXT>
