<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Libyans     07-23 0582</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Libyans,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bail Denied for Libyan Accused of Illegal Intelligence Gathering</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Libyan man accused of gathering
information about American intelligence operatives and arranging
for the military training of American dissidents in Libya has been
ordered held without bail.
   A U.S. magistrate on Friday granted bail to five other
defendants, including Mousa Hawamda, a travel agency owner accused
of involvement in an alleged Libyan plot to assassinate a ``high
government official in the United States.'' Sources have said the
official was former White House aide Oliver North, who played a key
role in the 1986 U.S. bombing of Libya.
   The prosecution immediately appealed the bail for Hawamda, a
naturalized American described by the FBI as a senior Libyan
intelligence operative, and he was ordered held pending an appeals
hearing early next week.
   The New York Times, in today's editions, quoted Justice
Department officials as saying there is little evidence to support
a federal prosecutor's assertion that Hawamda may have helped in
the alleged plot.
   The Times said Justice officials who asked not to be identified
said they were baffled when U.S. Attorney Henry E. Hudson asserted
in open court earlier this week that Hawamda should be held without
bail because he was a Libyan intelligence officer who may have
assisted in a plot to kill a government official.
   The officials, who asked not to be identified, said that while
there may have been an assassination plot aimed at North, the only
information linking Hawamda to such a conspiracy came from an
informer whose reliabiity is uncertain.
   Hudson had no comment on the assertions that there was little
evidence to support allegations about the assassination plot, the
Times said.
   F. Andrew Carroll, the lawyer representing Hawamda, called the
prosecution's contention of a plot to kill a high government
official ``ludicrous.''
   Hawamda and the five others were among eight men arrested
Wednesday on suspicion of a scheme to illegally use Libyan
government funds to solicit support for Libya among American
dissidents, including Indians and Black Muslims.
   Friday's hearing before magistrate Leonie Brinkema was to
determine whether the six would be freed on bond.
   The bail ranged from $250,000 for Hawamda to $10,000 for Manhal
Ben Mohamed, a Moroccan who worked for Hawamda.
   Two other defendants are being held in Denver, Colo. and
Detroit, Mich.
   Alvin M. Binder, a criminal lawyer from Mississippi who
represented four of the defendants in court, said the case was
``very political.'' Binder, a criminal lawyer who represented
Atlanta child murderer Wayne Williams in 1982, said the prosecution
had made ``allegations with no concrete evidence.''
   Hudson told reporters after the detention hearing that ``the
case involves issues far beyond just a diversion of funds.'' But he
refused to elaborate, saying additional charges would be made when
indictments are returned, possibly late next week.
   Speaking for the prosecution, FBI special agent Donald J.
Bartnik said the defendant held without bail, Saleh Al-Rajhi, was a
Libyan intelligence operative who in June 1987 was ordered to
gather the names and addresses of U.S. intelligence officials
dealing with the Mediterranean region.
   The FBI seized a document handwritten by Al-Rajhi as a cover
letter for a computer list of intelligence operatives, Bartnik
said. The list and letter were sent to the head of Libyan
intelligence, Mohamed Madjoub, he added.
   Al-Rajhi also wrote Madjoub a memo which indicated the Libyans
had promised to fund American dissident groups in the United States
and pay for their military training in Libya, Bartnik said.
</TEXT>
