<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iraqis-Cease-Fire     07-23 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iraqis-Cease-Fire,0680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraqis Wary of Celebrating War's End</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gulf Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Weddings and soccer games still stir
Iraqis' Arab zeal for celebration, and a religious holiday can be a
time of great feasting.
   But Iraqis are showing an uncharacteristic lack of jubilation
over Iran's agreement to halt its 8-year-old war with Iraq. For
people like Suad Mousa, the war will end only when her family is
reunited.
   ``I really want the guns to fall silent and for my dear husband
to come home,'' said the 34-year-old mother of three, whose husband
has been in the army since the war began.
   ``When the Iranians said they would accept the U.N. (cease-fire)
resolution, I really thought the war was finally over, but it seems
now it will take weeks and probably months before he will be
back,'' she said.
   Such war-weary wariness has been common in Iraq after Iran
agreed Monday to accept a truce.
   ``There was nothing. No reaction,'' said a European diplomat who
was in Baghdad on Monday.
   Iraqis seem deeply suspicious of the Iranian decision, and the
government is insisting any truce be tied to a final settlement.
   Parades, celebrations and television specials typically greet
Iraqi victories in battle. None followed the Iranian announcement.
   Official news media and President Saddam Hussein's ruling Baath
Party have encouraged caution and continued vigilance by the
military.
   The army has continued to fight, and it said Thursday night it
had recaptured 33 northern hills lost to Iran in the early days of
the war.
   Iran said Iraqi units penetrated 12 miles into its territory
Friday and claimed Iraq used chemical weapons.
   Exultation is common here over much less than the end of a long
and costly war. Fusillades of tracer bullets lit the night sky over
Baghdad when Iraq defeated rival Syria in the Arab soccer
championship Thursday night.
   Wedding parties toot car horns and bang drums as they move
through the streets of Baghdad.
   Families are buying sheep to slaughter for the Eid al-Adha feast
that marks the end of Islam's season of pilgrimage to Mecca. The
date depends on the moon, but it is expected Sunday or Monday.
   Celebration of the war's end, however, apparently will have to
wait for a final peace.
   Diplomats in Baghdad say distrust of the Iranians, who accepted
a Security Council resolution they had rejected since its passage a
year ago, is rooted in hundreds of years of conflict between Arab
Iraq and Persian Iran.
   Government officials also feel Iran may want a truce only as a
respite in which to rebuild their army, which has lost several
battles this year.
   Some cite Iranian statements that a cease-fire does not mean the
end of the war, which Iran's revolutionary patriarch Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini sees as a crusade for his own vision of Islam.
   Iraq rejected proposals of a cease-fire two years ago when its
own forces were being battered near the southern city of Basra and
many observers felt collapse was near.
   It would ``certainly not'' accept a truce without real peace now
that it has the upper hand militarily, said a Western diplomat who
recently talked with Iraqi officials. He said Iraq insists on
direct peace talks with Iran as a sign ``of serious purpose.''
   A European diplomat said Iraqis are ``still going to be nervous
about the Iranians because the Iranians haven't been beaten'' and
still are ruled by crusading clerics. He said Iran ``could be
militarily quite potent ... within a year or two.''
   Although they are not celebrating, ordinary Iraqis are anxious
for the war to end.
   ``I am an old man,'' said 68-year-old Mahmoud Shaker at the
counter of his auto parts store. ``I have been running the shop for
four years, since my elder son was conscripted. I am very tired and
I want him back to the shop and with the family.''
</TEXT>
