<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CVN--AtlantaImpact Bjt   07-23 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Atlanta Impact, Bjt,0619</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Business Pleased With Atlanta's Image During Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's over, and Atlanta is happy.
   City and business officials praised their city and the publicity
it received during the four-day Democratic National Convention,
which ended Thursday.
   ``The awareness of Atlanta and Georgia is at an all-time high
throughout the world, and that will translate into investment
decisions in future months,'' George Berry, commissioner of the
state Department of Industry and Trade, said Friday.
   Berry said Gov. Joe Frank Harris plans a business-hunting trip
to Australia this fall, ``and we will not have to explain to
anybody we meet with where Atlanta is, and that's the big benefit
of the convention as far as we were concerned.''
   Many Americans are ``still in the mindset (that Atlanta is)
`Gone With the Wind,''' said Denise S. Dwozan, spokeswoman for the
Atlanta Convention and Visitors Bureau, referring to the novel and
film about the South during the Civil War.
   But, she said, ``I think they now have an excellent picture of
Atlanta in 1988 _ a progressive, exciting city.''
   Mayor Andrew Young, also pleased with the city in its role as
host, plugged Atlanta as a site for future major events.
   ``I would hope that we have received the kind of good coverage
around the world that will convince the Olympic Committee that we
really know how to put on a party,'' Young said Friday. The city is
the U.S. nominee to be host of the 1996 Summer Games.
   Live broadcasts during the convention by network morning
television shows, which originated in Atlanta, were particularly
helpful in dispelling myths, Ms. Dwozan said.
   Those programs showed ``Atlanta is a metropolitan city, with a
fabulous skyline, a lot of Fortune 500 companies,'' she said, and
people already have begun calling, wanting more information. The
callers say, ``Gosh, I never had any idea y'all had all that down
there, so can you send me a packet?''
   Pre-convention studies estimated the convention would bring
between $58.7 million and $64.3 million into the city, which spent
$15 million to stage it.
   Berry and Ms. Dwozan estimated that the direct economic impact
was about what had been predicted, but they stressed the short-term
gain was not their goal.
   The city already is a major convention town, Ms. Dwozan said, so
the hope is that tourism will increase and businesses will look
closer at moving to Atlanta or Georgia because of interest
generated by the convention.
   Ms. Dwozan said convention bureau President Ted Sprague
estimates the city received about $1 billion worth of ``media
awareness'' worldwide. ``We could never have afforded an
advertising campaign like that.''
   ``For the most part,'' she said, ``Atlanta was accurately
portrayed. Some of the stories that were negative were accurate.
   ``Atlanta is not perfect. We do have things that need improving
and some of the stories touched on that. All in all, we're
thrilled.''
   The Atlanta Chamber of Commerce had set as a particular goal
keeping the 15,000 reporters in town informed about the city and
trying to make it easy for them to work, hoping the city would look
good.
   ``In that, we overwhelmingly achieved that objective,'' said
chamber spokesman Barry King. ``It was great, it was fantastic
exposure: a little bit of the good, a little bit of the not-so-good.
   ``Nobody really zinged us badly,'' King said. ``The city
performed fantastically. Hospitality was truly gracious in all
respects. Police and security people were outstanding. They looked
good. The demonstrators got their point across.
   ``We couldn't have bought this kind of exposure,'' he said.
</TEXT>
