<1ST_LINE>r w PM-RowanThreat     07-23 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rowan Threat,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Campaign Volunteer Under Investigation For Phone Calls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. attorney's office is investigating
allegations that a former campaign volunteer for Rep. John Miller,
R-Wash., made threatening and harassing telephone calls to
syndicated columnist Carl Rowan from the congressman's home,
according to police.
   The calls were believed to be related to an incident on June 14
in which Rowan, an outspoken gun-control advocate, shot a teen-age
intruder in his back yard, said Walt Ferguson, a spokesman for the
District of Columbia police.
   He said Rowan reported to the security branch of the Chesapeake
and Potomac Telephone Co. and the police that ``a series of
threatening and harassing phone calls'' were made to his home
between July 1 and July 14.
   ``This is such a shock,'' commented Anna Perez, a spokeswoman
for Miller, about the investigation focusing on one-time campaign
helper Michael Brown.
   No charges have been filed against Brown, said Ferguson, but the
case has been handed over to the U.S. attorney's office, where a
decision will be made whether to prosecute.
   Brown worked for Miller during the congressman's 1984 campaign,
Perez said.
   ``He periodically house-sat, and he's been doing it a lot
lately,'' she said. Miller and his wife, June, recently had a baby,
and Miller has been traveling to his home state to visit his
spouse, leaving Brown in the house alone, Perez said.
   Perez said Miller telephoned Rowan Friday to apologize.
   ``He said that he and June are appalled at Mike's action and
that there is absolutely no explanation for it,'' she said, adding
that Brown ``is not now nor ever has been on Congressman Miller's
staff. Never.''
   Rowan, reached at his home Friday, said, ``I have no comment
about anything.''
   Following the shooting incident, Rowan told authorities that he
shot Benjamin N. Smith, 18, with a .22-caliber handgun after
hearing noises in his back yard. Rowan said he called police and
discovered Smith, Laura Bachman, 19, and two other unidentified
youths by his back yard pool.
   The District of Columbia's strict handgun ordinance requires
that all weapons be registered, but Rowan told authorities that the
gun had belonged to his son, Carl Jr., a former FBI agent. Rowan
claimed that his son was told he did not have to register the
weapon after leaving the FBI.
   D.C. officials have not yet decided whether to prosecute Rowan
on weapons charges.
</TEXT>
