<1ST_LINE>r i PM-MeccaPilgrimage     07-23 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecca Pilgrimage,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Trying To Stir Unrest In Holy City, Saudi Arabia Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi Arabia today said thousands of
Moslems were making a calm and peaceful pilgrimage to Mecca and
accused Iran of spreading false reports of violence and unrest to
stir tensions in the holy city.
   Tehran Radio said hundreds of pilgrims demonstrated in Mecca on
Friday against the deaths last year of 402 people in Mecca, and
that police attacked some demonstrators.
   Parts of the report by the government-run Iranian radio,
monitored by the British Broadcasting Corp., were indistinct, but
monitors said they heard no reference to injuries.
   Residents in the Mecca area reached by telephone from Bahrain
said they were not aware of violence. They said pilgrims prayed
early today in preparation for the culmination of the pilgrimage.
   Others reached in Jiddah, 25 miles away, also said they had
heard no reports of violence.
   Iran, which is boycotting this year's pilgrimage, charges that
the Saudi royal family is not fit to supervise the holy shrines at
Mecca and Medina.
   ``Hundreds of Arab, Turk, Afghan, Pakistani and American
pilgrims demonstrated in Mecca today (Friday), chanting slogans ..
. and carrying placards condemning the Al-Saud regime in their
killing of over 400 pilgrims of the holy sanctuary last year in
Mecca,'' Tehran radio said.
   It added: ``According to received reports, the Saudi regime's
police ... subjected the demonstrators to severe control and
surrounded them. In some sections, they attacked the ranks of the
marchers.''
   Government-run Saudi radio quoted an unidentified official
source as saying the report was ``made up'' and one of a series of
``lies and fabrications'' broadcast by Iran to create tension.
   The source was quoted as saying pilgrims in Mecca were
undertaking their rites ``in calm and secure conditions.''
   Tehran radio and television also quoted an Iranian correspondent
in Bonn, West Germany, as reporting that hundreds of non-Saudi
pilgrims demonstrated in Mecca on Friday.
   The report said the demonstrators chanted ``Death to America,''
``Death to Zionism'' and ``Death to the Soviet Union.''
   ``The Saudi police, who had become scared, tried to surround the
attendants,'' the correspondent was quoted as reporting. ``The
rally then stopped moving, and while chanting the slogan `unity,'
the pilgrims asked all the Moslems to condemn the United States.''
   The report made no mention of violence.
   Today, the ninth day of the month of Zhul-Hijja by Islamic
calendar, is earmarked as ``Wukuf,'' or the day of standing, when
pilgrims wake at dawn and travel six miles to Arafat, where they
remain praying, chanting and listening to sermons.
   Saudi Arabia said more than 1 million pilgrims from around the
world gathered Friday in 111-degree temperatures for Sabbath
prayers at the Grand Mosque in Mecca, which houses Islam's holiest
shrine.
   During last year's pilgrimage to Mecca, 402 people were killed
in riots. Saudi Arabia said the pilgrims, 275 of them Iranians,
died in a stampede. Iran claimed Saudi police shot them.
   The Saudis accused the Iranians of defying a ban on protests. In
April, Saudi Arabia broke off diplomatic relations with Tehran,
accusing it of terrorism and subversion.
   Saudi Arabia has been receiving the pilgrims and organizing the
hajj, or pilgrimage, this year with extensive security measures to
prevent a recurrence of violence.
   Saudi authorities earlier announced that the number of pilgrims
would be restricted this year to one for every 1,000 residents of
each Moslem country.
   The Iranians boycotted this year's pilgrimage when Saudi Arabia
sought to reduce the numbers of participants.
   Iran has charged that the Saudi royal family is not fit to
supervise the holy shrines at Mecca and Medina.
</TEXT>
