<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     07-23 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Surgeon General Fears Anti-AIDS `Retribution'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Surgeon General C. Everett Koop says he fears
a wave of ``retribution'' against smokers, drunken drinkers and
others whose actions are seen as a public health threat could
spread to AIDS victims by the next decade,
   ``Such a response would be tragic, but not unexpected to the
health profession,'' Koop said on Friday.
   He cited the recent passing of laws to segregate smokers and
public ``retribution against drunk drivers, teen-agers who become
pregnant, drug addicts and wife beaters.''
   Koop said it is possible that the American people, ``already
traveling the road of retribution,'' will extend that retribution
against AIDS victims in the 1990s, ``when the annual health bill
for the disease reaches $5 billion.''
   The surgeon general commented in a speech after receiving an
honorary fellowship from the American College of Legal Medicine.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mica Shocked That Cubans Revoked Visa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Dan Mica has written a letter to
President Fidel Castro expressing ``shock'' over the Cuban
government's decision to revoke visas which he and several aides
had been given for travel to Cuba.
   The Florida Democrat had planned to visit Cuba to inspect U.S.
diplomatic facilities as part of his duties as chairman of a House
Foreign Affairs subcommittee.
   But Cuba revoked the visas Tuesday evening shortly before Mica
and his companions were scheduled to fly to the island, citing the
presence of Cuban human rights advocates at a reception given by a
U.S. diplomatic official a week ago.
   A dispatch from Cuba's Prensa Latina news agency quoted a Cuban
Foreign Ministry statement as saying the reception ``was organized
to make it possible for American diplomats to instruct their
counterrevolutionary servants and was not a normal diplomatic
activity''
   In his letter to Castro, dated Thursday and released on Friday,
Mica said, ``I am shocked that you should choose to interfere with
a legitimate congressional visit to conduct internal U.S. business
and review the operations of our mission in your country.''
