<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GangSummit     07-23 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gang Summit,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Leaders Bringing Gang Leaders Together For `Truce Summit'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Church leaders plan to hold a ``truce
summit'' next week with gang members in hopes of stopping the
bloody gang strife that claims about one life a day in the Los
Angeles area.
   Organizers say they hope this summer of drive-by killings,
street-corner revenge shootings, and drug deals that explode into
gunfire has persuaded gangs to gather on neutral ground to resolve
their differences.
   ``We're going to see what's on the gangs' minds. We're going to
try to stop the killings,'' the Rev. Charles Mims, pastor of Faith
Baptist Church in Watts, said Friday.
   ``We're seeing members who are macho bad and looking at their
graves. And they're ready,'' added Louis Cater, pastor of the
Antioch Baptist Church, also in Watts, one of the areas that is
hardest-hit by gang violence.
   The summit meetings Tuesday through Thursday will include talks
between representatives of factions of the Bloods and Crips gangs,
the area's two biggest black gangs that police say have expanded
their criminal activities throughout the West and Midwest. A
representative from the NAACP also will participate in the talks.
   The summit comes as highly publicized police sweeps and dragnets
have failed to deter the drive-by shootings and other attacks that
end in hundreds of killings each year.
   Gang membership has grown to 100,000 throughout Los Angeles
County, with youths enticed by a drug business that can net as much
as $1,000 a day, authorities say.
   Gangs accounted for 387 killings last year, and 140 slayings the
first half of this year, police said.
   Local leaders of the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People will try to convince gang members of the importance
of keeping drugs off the streets.
   ``If we can attempt to stop drugs, kids won't have money,'' said
Basil Kimbrew, chairman of community affairs for the Los Angeles
NAACP. ``Then they will have to seek job training or other
employment.''
   Security will be provided by Los Angeles County Supervisor
Kennth Hahn's office. The Los Angeles Police Department and Los
Angeles County Sheriff will send non-uniformed officials to speak
with gang members.
   Los Angeles Police Commander William Booth said he hoped the
ministers could have a ``settling influence'' on gang members.
   The summit, including discussion sessions between gang members,
follows six years of work by church leaders with gang members, who
have pledged to work with the summit organizers, Mims said.
   ``They're going to have to realize that they're worth something,
that they're not all bad, that somebody cares,'' Mims said. ``Then
they got to realize that the killings must stop. I was a prison
chaplain and I haven't seen anyone yet who wants to die. I've seen
a lot people who feign or pretend. But nobody wants to die.''
</TEXT>
