<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Contras     07-23 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contras,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras To Seek New Peace Talks; Bermudez To Give Up Military
Command</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUAN MALTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the Nicaraguan rebels,
struggling to quell internal dissent, say they will seek a new
round of peace talks with the leftist Sandinista government.
   Alfredo Cesar, one of the seven Contra directors, said Friday he
is asking President Oscar Arias of Costa Rica to arrange the talks.
   Cesar also said Col. Enrique Bermudez, a controversial hardliner
who was elected to the rebel political leadership this week, will
step down as military commander of the U.S.-backed rebel forces.
   Cesar told a news conference that Bermudez will be ``the
military supervisor of our military forces, but without any
command.''
   The Sandinistas have said Bermudez's election to the political
directorate of the Nicaraguan Resistance makes ``the possibility of
negotiating peace even more remote.''
   The Contras and the Sandinistas have been trying to negotiate an
end to their seven-year war since March. The talks have been
prompted in large part by the regional peace plan that won Arias
last year's Nobel Peace Prize.
   Cesar is the chief Contra negotiator in the talks.
   The last round of talks ended in a stalemate on June 9, and no
new talks have been scheduled. A temporary truce, however, is still
in place after repeated extensions.
   The Sandinistas accused the CIA of engineering Bermudez's
election to the political directorate of the Nicaraguan Resistance.
They said his election removes the Contra leadership's ``civilian
mask.''
   Bermudez, who publicly resisted peace talks with the
Sandinistas, was a colonel in the National Guard of the rightist,
pro-American Somoza dynasty that ruled Nicaragua for 42 years until
the Sandinistas overthrew it in 1979.
   His background is a source of suspicion for some members of the
resistance who fear the rebel movement is turning to the right.
   The controversy heated up after Bermudez was elected to the
directorate Monday in the Dominican Republic. The seven commanders
of the small Contra organization called the Southern Front, which
has a political base in Costa Rica, resigned in protest.
   Bermudez was the top military commander of the main,
Honduras-based Contra force.
   Cesar publicly appealed to the seven Friday to withdraw their
resignations. He said the new directorate ``will delegate areas of
responsibility and, in this sense, Col. Enrique Bermudez will step
down next week from the general command of the National Liberation
Army.''
   Cesar said the leaders who resigned were frustrated that they
were not getting U.S. aid. He said the Costa Rican government would
not allow delivery through Costa Rica.
   The Contra force led by Bermudez got U.S. aid through Honduras.
   Cesar said the Contras asked Arias two months ago for permission
to deliver humanitarian aid through the Costa Rican Red Cross, but
have received no reply.
   Congress cut off military aid to the Contras in February.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
