<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MsvsMrs     07-23 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ms vs Mrs,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Ms.' Judge Involved In Series Of Confrontations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TARA BRADLEY-STECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge who threatened an attorney
with jail over the use of ``Ms.'' and her maiden name is no
stranger to such threats, say lawyers who practice in his courtroom.
   ``There is no more powerful man than an American judge sitting
in his courtroom. He is a king,'' said Allen Brunwasser, who once
spent 48 hours in jail for missing a hearing before senior U.S.
District Judge Hubert Teitelbaum.
   ``I felt seriously threatened,'' said Leonard Sharon, who was
surrounded by federal marshals when Teitelbaum objected to a
petition he tried to file. ``It's also humiliating because it can
affect the way jurors look at you and your case.''
   Teitelbaum prompted feminists to demand his resignation and the
local bar association to launch an investigation into courtroom
sexism when he recently ordered attorney Barbara Wolvovitz to use
her husband's last name and not use ``Ms.'' during a trial.
   Attorneys who have appeared before Teitelbaum said Friday his
courtroom antics began years ago.
   Teitelbaum, 73, a former U.S. attorney and FBI agent who took
the bench in 1971, could not be reached for comment Friday. There
were no answers at his office or home telephones. He consistently
has refused to talk to reporters.
   Sharon, now practicing law in Auburn, Maine, said Teitelbaum
ordered him arrested and called him a liar in 1984 over a petition
the judge claimed contained errors.
   ``I didn't lie, but if he has facts that say I did, someone else
should'' have decided the issue, Sharon said. ``He can't pitch and
call balls and strikes at the same time.''
   The judge later vacated his order.
   Stanley Preiser, who now practices in Charleston, W.Va., and
Boca Raton, Fla., said Teitelbaum called him a ``dumb Jew'' and
threatened him with jail in 1985 when he asked the judge to
reschedule a case around a Jewish holiday.
   ``He said, `It was the first time I had known you were Jewish,
because I have never met a dumb Jew before,''' recalled George
Mahfood, Preiser's co-counsel in the case.
   ``I was stunned and astounded,'' Preiser said. ``That courtroom
was totally different from any other American courtroom I had been
in before.''
   Teitelbaum stepped down from the case after the two attorneys
filed motions to the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for his
disqualification. Mahfood said the judge was ``enraged'' over the
motions to have him disqualified.
   ``He told us it was improper to investigate him and if we
continued, we'd be put in jail,'' he said.
   In 1973, Teitelbaum dispatched marshals to a local court for
Brunwasser, who was finishing a trial there. Teitelbaum had
Brunwasser jailed for 48 hours for contempt for not attending a
hearing scheduled at the same time.
   Brunwasser served the time, but the 3rd Circuit overruled
Teitelbaum and cleared Brunwasser of contempt.
   ``He's got a Napoleonic complex,'' said Pittsburgh attorney
Harvey Daniels. ``He's very bright. He's very knowledgable in the
law. But he's very domineering. He takes over your case and tries
it for you.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
