<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--WashingtonLetter     07-23 0149</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Washington Letter,0152</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Letter From George Washington Fetches $26,800</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A two-page letter written in 1794 by President
George Washington was sold for $26,800, almost double the estimated
price, Sotheby's auction house said.
   Sotheby's said the letter, which invites John Jay to become U.S.
minister in London, was purchased Friday by a dealer in Sussex,
southern England.
   The letter, marked ``Secret and Confidential,'' was previously
known only by Washington's draft of it, now at the Library of
Congress in Washington, and through a copy. Its whereabouts were
unknown until Friday, Sotheby's said.
   Jay, who had already accepted the post of U.S. envoy
extraordinary to Britain, refused the post of minister, but he
completed negotiations with the British over differences remaining
after the Revolutionary War.
   Also Friday, Sotheby's sold a death mask of the Duke of
Wellington for $24,700.Wellington defeated Napoleon at the 1815
Battle of Waterloo.
</TEXT>
