<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Pee-wee     07-23 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Pee-wee,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A New Pee-wee? He Knows He Is, But What Are You?</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the words of Pee-wee Herman:
``Woooooooooooah.''
   The man-child known for his silly knock-kneed walk, nasal
high-pitched voice and childish taunts like ``I know you are but
what am I?'' is talking these days about advertising and publicity
campaigns, following his instincts and growing as a human being.
   Pee-wee's personality changed a bit after filming the upcoming
movie ``Big Top Pee-wee,'' the sequel to the popular ``Pee-wee's
Big Adventure,'' which cost $6 million to make and grossed $45
million.
   ``I'm confident that this movie will do well, and probably will
do better than the last one,'' Pee-wee said in a recent interview.
``I know it sounds smug to say that, but I've been involved in the
advertising, promotion and publicity campaigns on this movie and I
know that everything is being done to open successfully.''
   ``Big Top Pee-wee'' was co-written and co-produced by Pee-wee's
alter-ego, comedian Paul Reubens, 35, who created the Pee-wee
Herman character in 1979 as part of a skit for an improvisational
group in Los Angeles.
   In ``Big Top Pee-wee,'' Pee-wee discovers lust, greed and
ambition. He even kisses a girl for the first time.
   ``I tried to grow a bit in this movie,'' said Pee-wee, who does
not answer questions directed at Paul Reubens. ``I had to follow my
own instincts and my own feelings about what I want to do and how I
wanted to be portrayed or perceived. I didn't want to be stale and
I didn't want to make the same movie I made before.''
</TEXT>
