<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 0546EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Fiji-Tonga     07-23 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fiji-Tonga,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Island Kingdom Bans Fijian Indians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUVA, Fiji (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The south Pacific kingdom of Tonga has banned
visits by Fijians of Indian extraction, state-owned Radio Fiji
reported today.
   The radio station said the Tongan Immigration Department ordered
Fiji's national airline, Air Pacific, other regional air carriers
and shipping lines not to carry Fijian Indians to Tonga.
   Radio Fiji said Tonga, which is about 500 miles west of Fiji,
did not want to be flooded with Indians, especially businessmen.
   No Tongan government spokesman was immediately available for
comment, but the ban was confirmed by Air Pacific's general
manager, Andrew Drysdale.
   Pilots and cabin crew of the airline, many of whom are of Indian
origin, have threatened to boycott Tongan flights in protest, Radio
Fiji said.
   Relations between ethnic Indians and ethnic Fijians in Fiji have
been tense since May 14, 1987, when Lt. Col. Sitiveni Rabuka, an
ethnic Fijian, led a coup that ousted the Indian-dominated
government of Timoci Bavadra.
   Rabuka said he mounted the coup to protect the political rights
of ethnic Fijians, who are outnumbered by Indians in the 715,000
population. Many native Fijians resent the Indians because they
control much of the local commerce.
   Four months later, Rabuka carried out a second coup against an
interim government. Rabuka since has handed power to the nominally
civilian government and appointed himself head of the army and home
affairs minister in charge of internal security.
   Many Fijians of Indian extraction are seeking to leave the
country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
