<2ND_LINE>PM-Plane Ditches,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Bodies Recovered From Canal Where Plane Crashed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators are looking into
whether the crew of a DC-6 plane that ran out of gas and crashed in
a drainage ditch took on less fuel than normal in order to carry
more cargo from El Salvador.
   Workers on Friday found the bodies of the plane's three crew
members near Golden Meadow, a Lafourche Parish community about 40
miles south of New Orleans.
   Lafourche Parish Sheriff Duffy Breaux identified the crash
victims as George B. Reti, the pilot; Keith LeFever, the co-pilot;
and Stephen Hereros, the engineer. All three were from Miami,
Breaux said.
   The men were believed to be the only ones on the plane.
   Eugene Roth of the National Transportation Safety Board, who is
heading up the investigation of the crash, said there is little
doubt that the plane ran out of fuel.
   He said he is trying to find out if the crew sacrificed some of
its fuel load to carry more cargo. Roth said he has received a
report that the plane's cargo was 22,000 pounds and the fuel load
was only 1,800 gallons.
   The four-engine, propeller driven aircraft belonged to Universal
Air Equipment Leasing Inc. of Miami and was operated by Fiorelli
Crews of Miami, according to a news release from TACA Airlines.
   TACA had chartered the flight to carry a payload of handicrafts,
seafood and other cargo from San Salvador, El Salvador, to New
Orleans.
