<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Rosary-Messages Bjt   07-23 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rosary-Messages, Bjt,0662</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Worshipers Report Messages from Virgin Mary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WENDY E. LANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUBBOCK, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of faithful from across Texas
have been flocking to a cavernous underground church each week to
hear parishioners report what they claim are messages of peace and
hope from the Virgin Mary.
   Crowds have grown from a handful of worshipers into hundreds,
and are expected to swell to 20,000 for a Roman Catholic feast day
next month.
   The largest gathering so far was Monday night, when 800 attended
a Mass and rosary service at St. John Neumann Catholic Church,
parish officials said.
   The worshipers came to see three parishioners who knelt on the
altar scribbling the ``messages'' in notebooks as the congregation
recited the rosary, which is a series of prayers counted off on a
string of beads, also called a rosary.
   After the prayers, the crowd fell silent as the first of the
messengers read from his notebook.
   ``My dear little children, listen to me your mother, I want to
help you,'' read Mike Slate. ``I want you to be in heaven, where we
can pray and serve our father for all eternity. Yes, my dear ones,
you must have signs and you will have these signs ... but it will
be up to you to believe.''
   Messages from Slate, a retired Air Force officer, were followed
by others from Mary Constancio, a former hospital therapist, and
Teresa Werner, a housewife and mother.
   ``My children, do not be sad,'' read Mrs. Constancio softly,
after first delivering the message in Spanish. ``Have joy in your
hearts, have peace. Listen to the prayer that you ask for, the Lord
will give it to you.''
   Worshipers then crowded around the messengers, seeking
blessings. The three laid their hands on those who said they were
seeking help for physical or personal problems.
   Bob Golec, who journeyed to the service from Midlothian, Texas,
in June, said his chronic knee problems disappeared after Mrs.
Werner relayed a message from Mary to him and the church pastor
said a healing prayer for him.
   ``I believe this special healing was a sign to strengthen my
faith,'' he said. Others attending the weekly Monday night rosaries
have also claimed healings, or said they smelled roses or felt
Mary's presence.
   Monsignor Joseph James, pastor of the church built partially
underground during 1972 to save on energy bills, said he and other
parishioners began feeling Mary's presence after a trip in January
to Medjugorje, Yugoslavia. They visited a spot where four
visionaries have been reporting apparitions of the Virgin since
1981.
   ``This has been life-changing for me,'' James said. ``It's much
more life-giving than any of the (theological) stuff I've read.''
   There have been skeptics, but James said it doesn't bother him.
``I can't say somebody has to believe this,'' he said.
   Lubbock Bishop Michael Sheehan is on vacation and has not
commented publicly about the message reports.
   James said he has interpreted many of the messages as indicating
that something miraculous will happen Aug. 15, the day Catholics
celebrate the Assumption of Mary into heaven.
   ``I think we're going to see some beautiful, beautiful thing _
experience her presence,'' said the 56-year-old priest.
   David Garza, the parishioner in charge of planning for the Aug.
15 rosary, said the church is making plans with the city for crowd
and traffic control for the event. Church officials said they are
expecting 20,000 people based on the number of calls they have
received.
   Although James said many people's lives have been touched by the
reported messages and hundreds of people have discovered his
church, he's worried that the messages may stop.
   ``You always have people jumping on the bandwagon,'' James said.
``The question is who will be there in the heat of the day? Who's
going to be praying when there aren't any messages?''
</TEXT>
