<1ST_LINE>u i PM-ShipAttack     07-23 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ship Attack,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Says Ship Attack Was Really Palestinian-Israeli Clash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper reported today that an
attack aboard a Greek cruise ship that left nine people dead
actually was a clash between Palestinian terrorists and the Israeli
secret service.
   The Copenhagen B.T. paper said an Abu Nidal terrorist squad and
agents of Mossad, Israel's secret service, opened fire on each
other on the liner City of Poros on July 11 after Mossad stopped
the terrorists from hijacking the ship.
   Israeli and Greek government officials had no immediate comment.
Abu Nidal's group on Thursday denied accusations it staged the
attack.
   The paper quoted Danish intelligence officers and unidentified
diplomatic sources as saying the Abu Nidal group started shooting
after watching a television news report saying a car bomb detonated
outside the Greek port city of Piraeus.
   Greek police said the car bomb went off prematurely six hours
before the ship was due to dock and killed two people in the car.
   B.T. said the terrorists planned to bring explosives from the
car aboard the cruise ship when the vessel arrived in Piraeus with
471 passengers and that the explosives were to be used in a
hijacking.
   Instead, the explosives were detonated by Mossad to avert the
hijacking, the newspaper said.
   It said two of those killed in the attack on the City of Poros
are believed to be Abu Nidal terrorists. Ninety-eight people were
wounded in the attack.
   B.T. said Danish intelligence is working on the case because
Libyan passport holder Hejab Jaballa, identified by the Greek
government as the likely leader of the terrorist attack, arrived in
Greece on a flight from Copenhagen June 1.
   Jaballa previously has been identified as involved in the
assassination of an Egyptian newspaper editor, for which Abu Nidal
claimed responsibility.
   Anastassios Sehiotis, Greek public order minister, said
Wednesday that Jaballa's real name is Khadar Samir Mohammed.
   On Thursday, Abu Nidal's Fatah-Revolutionary Council said it had
nothing to do with the ship attack and that Mohammed has been dead
since 1985. It did not say where or how he died.
   Abu Nidal, whose real name is Sabry al-Banna, has been blamed
for many terrorist attacks, including those on the Rome and Vienna
airports in December 1985 in which 22 people were killed and more
than 80 wounded.
</TEXT>
