<2ND_LINE>PM-Skyscraper Parachutist,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flamboyant Parachutist Fined $200 For Jumping Off Skyscraper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge fined a flamboyant parachutist $200 for
jumping off a 43-story skyscraper last fall, but suspended a 30-day
jail sentence on condition that he make no more jumps this year.
   But Robin Heid, 34, who defended himself, promised more jumps,
saying if he ``did not go to jail in the next year, I would not be
doing my job as a citizen. And you can quote me on that.''
   Denver County Court Judge Brian Campbell sentenced Heid on
Friday after a six-person jury convicted him of reckless
endangerment, a misdemeanor.
   ``I guess we set a precedent against jumping off buildings,''
said prosecutor Henry Cooper. ``I don't know how much weight a
county jury's decision holds.''
   Heid, whose first trial ended in a hung jury, wore to court the
same navy pinstripe suit he wore last Sept. 18, when he did a
1.5-second freefall from the top of the 1999 Broadway building and
then parachuted to a landing on a sidewalk 530 feet below.
   It was all a part of a publicity stunt to sell his book. Two
dozen of his skydiving buddies were waiting for him at a
book-signing party.
   Cooper told jurors Heid thumbs his nose at the law, as shown in
1979 when he saluted Yosemite National Park rangers while leaping
off the 2,200-foot El Capitan.
   ``I was very polite,'' Heid said. ``I told them, `Have a nice
day.' And then I jumped.''
