<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Unrest     07-23 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Unrest,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike Reported Over In Armenia, Continuing In Nagorno-Karabakh</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some factories in Armenia will work through the
weekend to pay off debts caused by a general strike in a dispute
over an Armenian enclave in neighboring Azerbaijan, Soviet media
said today.
   But public transport and enterprises in the disputed region,
Nagorno-Karabakh, remain idled by a work stoppage, news reports
said.
   State-run Radio Moscow said the situation remains tense in the
regional capital, Stepanakert, where residents have been on strike
since May 23 to demand the annexation of the region by Armenia.
   On Monday, the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, the nation's top
executive body, refused to alter the status of the district, which
has a predominantly Armenian population but no common borders with
the Soviet republic of Armenia.
   The Presidium ordered officials to take steps to restore ``labor
discipline'' and end the strikes in the Nagorno-Karabakh dispute.
But Radio Moscow's report indicated little had changed in the small
mountain region.
   ``The situation remains tense in the capital of
Nagorno-Karabakh, Stepanakert,'' the radio said. ``Many enterprises
are idle and public transport is at a standstill. However, farmers
of the region have already harvested more than one-half of this
year's bumper crop.''
   Friday night's television news program ``Vremya'' showed
deserted streets in Stepanakert and said only two buses were in
service in the city.
   The republic of Azerbaijan is mostly Moslem, while Armenia is
predominantly Christian. In February, 32 peole were killed in
ethnic riots in Sumgait, Azerbaijan, 26 of them Armenians.
   Activists in Yerevan, Armenia's capital, called a general strike
on July 4 to increase pressure for the incorporation of
Nagorno-Karabakh into their Caucasus Mountain republic.
   One Yerevan Communist Party official estimated that the work
stoppage, which ended Monday, cost the republic $111 million in
lost industrial production.
   ``As was reported in the Yerevan city party committee, it has
been decided to work Saturday and Sunday to compensate for the debt
that has formed,'' the Communist Party daily Pravda reported from
Yerevan.
   On Wednesday, Armenian activists called for a resumption of the
general work stoppage to protest the Presidium's decision. Reports
from Yerevan residents and the state-run media indicated the latest
strike call was largely ignored.
   A correspondent for Armenpress, the Armenian republic's official
news agency, said only about 7 percent of Yerevan's industrial
workers failed to show up at the job Friday.
   ``From the beginning of the work week, practically all
enterprises are working, although in some places there have been
occurrences of `pro-strike' feelings,'' Pravda said.
</TEXT>
