<HEAD>Rain From New England to Florida</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms stretched from southern New England to
Florida and westward to Ohio today, and strong winds blew smoke
from forest fires into sections of Wyoming.
   Occasionally heavy rain fell Thursday evening. More than 2
inches of rain fell in Asheville, N.C. Heavier rainfall in six
hours overnight included nearly an inch in Atlanta, and half an
inch in Providence, R.I., and Columbus, Ohio.
   Strong, gusty winds Thursday blew smoke from forest fires into
north central and northwest Wyoming, reducing visibility in many
places.
   It was a cool night in Kentucky. In Paducah, the temperature
just before midnight was 65 degrees, tying the low-temperature
record for July 22 set in 1980.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
southern New England and much of New York to Florida, southern
Alabama and southern Mississippi, and widely scattered showers and
thunderstorms in Nevada.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 70s and 80s from New
England to Georgia, from the Great Lakes region to the Tennessee
Valley, the central Mississippi Valley, and the upper Missouri
Valley, along the northern Pacific Coast and scattered along the
lower two-thirds of the California coast; near 100 degrees in North
Dakota, northwest Texas and Nevada; 100 to 115 degrees in the
desert Southwest and inland California; and in the 90s or near 90
degrees in the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 51
degrees at Arcata, Calif., to 98 degrees at Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 67 cloudy; Boston 62 foggy; Buffalo 66 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 77 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 68 partly cloudy;
Cleveland 67 showery; Detroit 69 fair; Miami 79 partly cloudy; New
York 71 cloudy; Philadelphia 73 foggy; Portland, Maine 59 foggy;
Washington 74 foggy.
   _Central: Bismarck 77 fair; Chicago 68 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
76 fair; Denver 75 fair; Des Moines 68 fair; Indianapolis 65 fair;
Kansas City 66 fair; Minnepolis-St. Paul 69 fair; Nashville 73
partly cloudy; New Orleans 74 foggy; St. Louis 70 fair.
