<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PlaneCrash     07-23 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plane Crash,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Killed When Plane Crashes Into Building</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) _ Workers in a building hit by a small
plane say they tried to save a man screaming for help in the
wreckage, but the aircraft exploded before they could reach him.
All four people aboard died in the crash.
   ``The flames were shooting 10 to 15 feet into the air,'' B.G.
Melton, a machinist at the manufacturing plant, said Friday night.
``I ran back and alerted my co-workers by intercom.''
   None of the 23 people in the Jepson Burns Corp. plant were
injured in the accident, which happened about 9:30 p.m. shortly
after the single-engine Cherokee 180 took off from Smith Reynolds
Airport.
   A Greensboro pilot, who declined to give his name, said he
watched the crash from the air.
   ``We were on our final approach when we saw a big fireball. I
heard an airplane on the ground radio the tower and ask if they saw
the crash,'' he said. The pilot said the plane appeared to stall
during takeoff.
   Officials at the airport did not confirm the deaths, but a
firefighter, who refused to identify himself, told the Greensboro
News & Record that everyone on the plane was killed.
   A spokeswoman for the National Transportation Safety Board in
Atlanta said a team of investigators would be on the scene today.
   A flight plan for such an aircraft is not required and no plan
was filed, said Jack Barker, a Federal Aviation Administration
official in Atlanta.
   The plane had just fueled and reportedly was taking off for
Myrtle Beach, S.C., when it crashed through the roof of the plant,
a three-building complex that manufactures airplane seat covers,
officials said.
   The workers inside the one-story building escaped safely, said
Mike Kingsbury, an employee of Jepson Burns.
   ``The plane went through the roof into the sewing department,''
said Kingsbury, who saw the accident from a guard's post about 200
yards away.
   The fire at the plant was extinguished within 20 minutes, fire
officials said. Five people were working inside the building the
plane smashed into, said Billie Melton, a Jepson Burns employee.
   ``They all went out the back door,'' Melton said.
   ``There's a fire wall between where they were working and where
the plane went down at. Smoke drove them out the other door,'' he
said.
   ``It sounded like a big boom. Me and a co-worker went out the
back door. We didn't see anything at first,'' Melton said.
``Everything looked normal. But when we went back in and came out
the other door, we saw the flames shooting out of the roof.''
</TEXT>
