<DOCNO> AP880723-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 0622EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ConfidentialityVerdict     07-23 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Confidentiality Verdict,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Rules Against Newspapers in Confidentiality Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLAYTON HASWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury verdict awarding $700,000 in damages
to a confidential source whose name was revealed by two newspapers
could open the door to scores of similar lawsuits, a First
Amendment expert says.
   The St. Paul Pioneer Press Dispatch and the Star Tribune were
ordered Friday to pay $200,000 in actual damages and $250,000 each
in punitive damages to Dan Cohen for a 1982 story that named him as
the source of information about a political candidate's shoplifting
conviction years earlier.
   Cohen said reporters had promised him anonymity.
   The jury decided that a promise of confidentiality was an oral
contract.
   ``It's very important to keep your word,'' a tearful Cohen said
after the verdict. ``That's the hard currency of journalism. That's
the hard currency of politics. When that currency is devalued, we
all suffer.''
   The verdict distressed journalists, who have faced contempt
charges and jail for not revealing sources, and now could face
damages if they do.
   ``I believe this is absolutely unprecedented,'' said Floyd
Abrams, a New York City-based attorney who has represented The New
York Times, NBC and other media organizations.
   ``If not reversed, this decision opens the door for an enormous
range of real or imagined sources to claim that, in one way or
another, they've been victimized by the press,'' Abrams said.
   John Finnegan, senior vice president-assistant publisher for the
St. Paul Pioneer Press Dispatch, and Tim McGuire, managing editor
of the Star Tribune, said an appeal is likely of the Hennepin
County jury's 5-1 verdict.
   ``What we've been saying is disclosure of an 11th-hour dirty
trick was at least as important as the 12-year-old shoplifting
record which Cohen was revealing,'' McGuire said.
   Finnegan said the punitive damages, associated with a finding of
fraud and misrepresentation, ``ignores the fact that the editors
involved handled the story honestly, fairly and accurately.''
   ``In no way did we misrepresent. Nor were we guilty of fraud in
our dealings with Mr. Cohen,'' Finnegan said.
   Gary Pruitt, counsel for McClatchy Newspapers Inc. in
California, said the verdict was understandable because the judge
did not instruct the jury on First Amendment issues.
   Making a reporter-source relationship a simple contract gives
those who want to sue the press a new way to circumvent
constitutional protections, Pruitt said.
   The suit centered on a decision by editors at both newspapers to
overrule their reporters and use Cohen's name. At the time, Cohen
was a spokesman for Wheelock Whitney, an Independent-Republican
candidate for governor.
   Six days before the election, Cohen gave reporters documents
showing that Marlene Johnson, a Democratic-Farmer-Labor candidate
for lieutenant governor, admitted shoplifting $6 in merchandise.
The documents were given on condition Cohen's identity not be
revealed.
   The day the stories appeared, Cohen was fired from his
$35,000-a-year job as a public relations executive with an
advertising agency, said his attorney, Elliott Rothenberg. Cohen
claimed he lost $725,000 in wages and pension.
   Cohen now has his own public relations firm and made $93,000
last year, according to testimony.
   In a related development, the Star Tribune began recalling all
640,000 copies of this weekend's Sunday Magazine after a person
quoted by name in the magazine said she had been promised anonymity.
   Executive editor Joel Kramer told the Pioneer Press Dispatch
that the Cohen case ``figured in our thinking, but I'm not saying
that's our only reason.'' He said publisher Roger Parkinson made
the decision after editors concluded they weren't sure whether a
pledge of anonymity had been given by the free-lancer who wrote the
article.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
