<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 0627EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea-Corruption     07-23 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Corruption,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Assembly Passes Bills To Question Former President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The opposition-controlled National
Assembly today passed bills aimed at forcing former President Chun
Doo-hwan and his family to testify before the assembly on
corruption charges.
   The bills passed unanimously, with controversial provisions
rewritten in a compromise between the governing and opposition
parties.
   President Roh Tae-woo vetoed earlier opposition-sponsored bills
and urged the assembly to revise provisions empowering it to summon
witnesses with writs of arraignment issued by courts.
   Under the new bills, lawmakers can subpoena witnesses with
non-binding writs of summons issued by the assembly.
   It was not immediately known if the writs would be effective in
bringing Chun before the assembly. The opposition accuses Roh's
government of trying to protect Chun, but the government also is
sensitive to public opinion.
   The opposition controls 166 seats in the 299-member assembly but
lacks the two-thirds majority required to override a presidential
veto.
   Opposition lawmakers sought the bills to question the former
president and his family, who have come under public criticism for
alleged involvement in financial scandals.
   Chun's younger brother, Chun Kyung-hwan, has been on trial on
charges of embezzeling millions of dollars in funds while head of
the semi-official Saemaul Undong development organization.
   The opposition also accuses the former president brutality in
ordering the military to quell a 1980 uprising in the southern city
of Kwangju in which about 200 people died.
   Despite continued government denials, dissidents charge Chun and
his military followers with provoking armed clahes in Kwangju as an
excuse to seize power.
   Roh is one of former generals who helped Chun seize power in
1980. He has tried to distance himself from Chun by carrying out
substantial reforms since the former president left office in
February.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
