<2ND_LINE>PM-Elderly Victim,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Assailant Kills Man, Steals Money He Saved For Burial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 103-year-old man was stabbed to death and robbed
of more than $1,000 he'd saved to pay for his burial expenses, a
longtime friend said.
   ``Now we don't have enough money to bury him,'' said Andy
Clewis, 34, who found Adam Owens and said the old man had raised
him as his son.
   The Dallas County medical examiner ruled Owens' death a homicide
after he was found stabbed and bleeding Thursday in the ransacked
living room of the apartment he'd lived in for 14 years.
   Ada Thomas, Clewis' mother, said she'd been Owens' companion for
more than 40 years.
   ``He walked crippled, but he was strong as an ox,'' Ms. Thomas
said.
   Daisy Hamilton, 98, said Owens moved slowly, carrying the
memories of 103 years, which he often shared with her and other
neighbors sitting on his porch.
   ``I would scold him a lot because he wouldn't do like I told him
and take better care of himself,'' Mrs. Hamilton said.
   According to The Dallas Morning News, neighbors said Owens
admitted an unknown woman to his apartment early Thursday evening.
   A ``tall, thin, dark-skinned woman'' came to the apartment on
foot, said ``good evening,'' and went inside with Owens, said one
neighbor. Others said they saw or heard nothing out of the ordinary
until Clewis arrived some time later and found Owens.
   Owens was described as a former Alabama coal miner who came to
Dallas in the 1940s. He was a construction worker and a gardener
until he stopped working in his 80s, Ms. Thomas said.
   Dallas police Lt. T.J. Barnes declined to comment Friday on how
Owens died or whether authorities had a suspect.
</TEXT>
