<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AgentOrange     07-23 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Agent Orange,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Gives Settlement Money to Australia and New Zealand</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of Australia and New Zealand
were given checks totaling $5 million to be distributed to those
who were exposed to the herbicide Agent Orange during the Vietnam
War.
   On hand to accept the checks Friday were Australian General
Consul Christopher Hurford and New Zealand General Consul Paul
Cotton.
   The checks were made out to the New Zealand Agent Orange Trust
and the Australian Vietnam War Veterans Trust and were part of a
$240 million settlement of suits against the chemical's makers.
   According to figures contained in 1985 court papers, 48,400
troops from Australia and 3,842 troops from New Zealand served with
the United States during the war in Vietnam.
   The checks, $4.5 million for Australian veterans and $500,000
for New Zealand, were presented by U.S. District Judge Jack B.
Weinstein of Brooklyn, who oversees the Agent Orange litigation.
   Hurford thanked Weinstein on behalf of the Australian people
``that you have not forgotten the Australian veterans.''
   Cotton also expressed his ``deepest appreciation'' and said that
``New Zealand and the United States are happy to be together in
peace.''
   ``Please express to your veterans our appreciation for the help
they gave us and our desire to help them as much as possible, our
comrades in arms,'' Weinstein said during the ceremony in his
chambers.
   The class-action suit, which was filed in 1978, was settled in
1984 when the chemical companies agreed to pay $180 million.
Interest gained during a lengthy appeal process upped the fund to
$240 million.
   The companies sued were Monsanto, Dow, Uniroyal, Hercules, T.H.
Agriculture and Nutrition, Diamond Shamrock and Thompson.
   Agent Orange was sprayed over Southeast Asia during the 1960s by
the U.S. military, which hoped to deprive communist troops of crops
and cover.
   The herbicide contains the highly toxic dioxin, and veterans
contend that exposure to the defoliant causes cancer and other
illnesses.
   Under a distribution plan, $170 million of the fund will be used
for cash payments to American veterans, $52 million will finance
social service projects to help Vietnam veterans and their families
and $17 million will pay for attorneys' fees and administrative
costs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
