<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Newborn-Airliner     07-23 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Newborn-Airliner,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Juvenile Court Commissioner Awards Temporary Custody To Paternal
Grandparents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELMONT, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Temporary custody of a baby girl who was
abandoned in a jetliner bathroom after her secret birth has been
awarded to her paternal grandparents.
   San Mateo County Juvenile Court Commissioner Patricia Bresee
said her decision Friday was based on a finding that 9-day-old
Alyssa Frances LoCasto might be in ``substantial danger'' if turned
over to her mother, Christina LoCasto, 24.
   Following a closed hearing, Bresee decided the home of John and
Frances LoCasto of New York City was adequate for their
granddaughter, said Gerry Hilliard, the infant's court-appointed
lawyer.
   ``The court has decided it would be better for the child to be
with relatives,'' Hilliard said.
   Christina LoCasto pleaded innocent last week to a felony charge
of child endangerment and is free on bail. Louis LoCasto, 26, asked
earlier that the baby be placed in his custody.
   The furor over Alyssa began July 13, when she was found under a
bathroom sink on a United Airlines jet shortly after it arrived at
San Francisco International Airport from Newark, N.J., and all
passengers had left.
   Christina LoCasto, traced through the passenger list, turned
herself in to San Mateo County Sheriff's detectives the next
morning.
   Her husband, who owns a limousine service, did not know his wife
had been pregnant or had given birth just before the flight,
detectives and lawyers said.
   The elder LoCastos, who attended Friday's hearing, posed for
photographers but declined to talk to reporters. They were whisked
away as attorneys spoke at a brief news conference.
   The baby's parents, Christina and Louis LoCasto, also of New
York City, did not attend the hearing.
   However, their attorneys, said the couple would be pleased by
the decision.
   ``This could be the beginning of a happy ending,'' said Vicki
Yeley, an attorney for Louis Locasto. ``The only disappointment is
that the child cannot be moved (immediately),'' she said.
   The brown-haired, blue-eyed girl will remain in a foster home
until Aug. 5 because legal proceedings involving New York state
officials must be completed, Hilliard said.
   The elder LoCastos will have custody of Alyssa at least until
Aug. 26, when another hearing will be held to determine if the
arrangement will continue. Until then, the baby's parents will be
able to visit her once a week under the supervision of child
welfare officials, lawyers said.
   John LoCasto, who works for a hospital insurance company, and
his wife, a civilian Army employee, live in a quiet, affluent
neighborhood less than two miles from their son and daughter-in-law.
   The younger couple have two other daughters, a 6-year-old and an
18-month-old
   The couple's decision to remain together was one reason Bresee
rejected Louis LoCasto's request for custody, Yeley said Monday.
  
</TEXT>
