<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--SovietTrain     07-23 0146</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Soviet Train,0149</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Train Hits Derailed Cars In Soviet, No Deaths Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A passenger train in Soviet Central Asia crashed
into eight derailed freight cars, causing its locomotive, mail van
and two passenger cars to shoot off the tracks, the official Tass
news agency reported today.
   No one was killed in the accident Thursday night, but 400 yards
of track were damaged, Tass said. It did not say whether anyone was
injured.
   The train wreck occurred in the republic of Kazakhstan between
the cities of Badam and Kalash, 1,700 miles southeast of Moscow,
Tass said, quoting from an account in the railway worker's daily
Whistle.
   According to the report, freight apparently broke up in one of
the freight cars, causing eight cars to derail and obstruct another
track. The passenger train then ran into them.
   An investigation was under way, Tass said.
</TEXT>
