<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Mandela     07-23 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Mandela,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mandela Receives Belated Birthday Visits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Imprisoned black leader Nelson
Mandela today accepted a government offer to visit with his wife
and family.
   Mandela rejected a similar offer earlier this week to protest a
government ban on celebrations of his birthday.
   Winnie Mandela, who flew to Cape Town for the visit at Pollsmoor
Prison, said the prison service had the best intentions in offering
her husband a special meeting with nine of his relatives on his
70th birthday Monday.
   But she said the African National Congress leader had decided to
protest the government's ban on celebrations of his birthday and
the detention of pro-Mandela activists by rejecting the privilege
offered him.
   Mandela has been imprisoned since 1962.
   During today's 80-minute visit, Mandela and his wife were joined
by their daughter, two grandchildren and an American businessman
who represents the Mandela family's interests.
   The attorney, Robert J. Brown, of High Point, N.C., said Mandela
agreed to grant power of attorney to him to protect the use of the
Mandela family name and its interests worldwide. Brown, who
announced a similar agreement with Mrs. Mandela earlier this week,
said the agreement requires that he consult with ANC president
Oliver Tambo in Lusaka, Zambia on all matters relating to the
family.
   Mandela is serving a life sentence for sabotage and plotting the
overthrow of the South African government as a leader of the ANC,
which is the main guerrilla group fighting the white-led government.
   Before the family visit, Mandela met with Yusuf and Amina
Cachalia, activists who in the 1950s waged with him a campaign
against South Africa's policy of apartheid, which establishes a
racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no
vote in national affairs.
   The Cachalias last saw Mandela in 1962, and had been applying
for 15 years for permission to meet him again.
</TEXT>
