<HEAD>Pope Urges Couples to Study Encyclical on Birth Control</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II, marking the 20th
anniversary of the encyclical Humanae Vitae, today urged young
married couples to study the document which affirms the church's
ban on contraception.
   ``I would like to remind you of the encyclical Humanae Vitae
that Paul VI published 20 years ago, July 25 1968, and to exhort
you to read and meditate upon this important document of the
church,'' the pope said during his general audience.
   He said the encyclical ``traces, with enlightened doctrinal
certainty and with profound human sensibility, the necessary
directives for achieving responsible parenthood.''
   The pope also stressed the values of ``love, unity, the
indissolubility of marriage and chastity.''
   After the audience, the pope flew by helicopter to his summer
retreat in Castel Gandolfo, in the Alban hills south of Rome. He
returned Friday from a 10-day vacation in the Dolomite Alps.
   The pope is expected to stay in Castel Gandolfo through August,
returning to the Vatican for his weekly audiences.
