<1ST_LINE>r a PM-YoungViolinist 1stLd-Writethru a0479 07-23 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Young Violinist, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0479,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Young Violinist Makes Successful Debut</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to include time element; SUBS last graf to
CORRECT spelling of Sassmannshaus</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 14-year-old violinist made her debut with
the Cincinnati Symphony Orchestra in a performance one music critic
hailed as inspiring.
   Under the direction of Jesus Lopez-Cobos, Alyssa Park performed
Wieniawski's Concerto No. 1 before 4,000 people Friday at the
outdoor Riverbend Music Center.
   ``Her performance transcended this concerto's often commonplace
materiels. Park is an inspiring performer with bright prospects
indeed,'' wrote Ray Cooklis, music critic for The Cincinnati
Enquirer.
   Miss Park, of Lexington, Ky., shrugs off her early musical
achievement as just another activity for a busy teen-ager, but she
already has decided that the concert life is for her.
   ``I'm the type of person who tries to fit in everything I can,''
she said. ``I hate to miss anything, especially something with my
friends.''
   Miss Park said the greatest influences on her life are ``my
family and friends. They give me enough love, strength, advice and
encouragement.''
   She began studying the violin at age 5, started taking lessons
at the University of Cincinnati's College Conservatory of Music at
age 9 and made her professional debut at age 11 with the Cincinnati
Chamber Orchestra.
   She has been making the hourlong commute with her family from
Lexington to Cincinnati since 1982 to study under a scholarship
with College Conservatory of Music instructor Kurt Sassmannshaus.
   She has played at the Aspen Music Festival in Colorado for six
summers, and has performed with the Louisville Orchestra, Lexington
Philharmonic, CCM Philharmonia and several city orchestras.
   ``She's extremely intelligent,'' Sassmannshaus said. ``She picks
up technical skills on the violin incredibly fast. I feel myself
more guiding her musical instincts rather than telling her what to
do.''
</TEXT>
