<DOCNO> AP880723-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 0935EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Burma-Glance 1stLd-Writethru a0503 07-23 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma-Glance, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0503,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burma at a Glance</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to ADD details on history, people and economy.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Burma-Ne Win</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some facts and figures on Burma:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE LAND _ Burma is about the size of Texas and shares frontiers
with India, China, Thailand and Laos. Resources include fertile
soil, timber, oil and other minerals. Rangoon, with a population of
3.5 million, is the capital and largest city. Mandalay, in the
heart of the country, is the second largest and the center of
traditional culture.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE PEOPLE _ Most of the 38 million people are Burmans.
Important minorities include Chinese, Indians, Karens, Shans, Chins
and Kachins. About 85 percent of the people practice Buddhism, with
minorities adhering to Islam and Christianity. Education is
widespread.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE ECONOMY _ Per capita income is less than $200 a year, making
Burma one of the world's poorest nations. It once was the world's
leading rice exporter, but experienced food shortages in 1987.
Burma's debt has climbed to more than $3 billion.
   The black market _ fueled by smuggled goods from Thailand and
China _ overshadows the official economy.
   Burma's economic failure is generally attributed to poor
government management and a crippling war against several ethnic
minorities seeking autonomy. Japan and West Germany are major aid
donors and the United States has a modest assistance program,
mainly in the anti-drug area.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   HISTORY _ Burma's golden age was the 12th century, when its
kings built the spectacular temples of Pagan. Britain ruled it from
1886 to 1948. After a post-independence experiment with democracy,
a military coup in 1962 brought Gen. Ne Win to power. He has
imposed isolationism, military control and socialist economics. Ne
Win held the presidency until 1981, when he resigned.
   Burma seeks to maintain a strictly neutralist policy and keep
out most foreign influences, including joint ventures with foreign
companies. It has been nicknamed ``Asia's hermit.'' Tourists are
allowed to stay only one week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880723-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 1008EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BusCrash     07-23 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bus Crash,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorney Says Driver Will Carry Burden Rest of Life</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE EMBRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pickup truck driver indicted in a
fiery bus crash that killed 27 people is relieved that the charges
do not carry a possible death sentence, his lawyer said.
   ``He couldn't sleep the night before wondering if he would live
or be put to death,'' said William L. Summers, attorney for Larry
W. Mahoney. ``He's had that answered.''
   Larry W. Mahoney, 35, pleaded innocent on 27 murder counts and
58 other charges filed by a Carroll County grand jury Friday.
Prosecutors had said after the May 14 crash they would seek capital
murder charges that could have led to a death penalty.
   But state Attorney General Fred Cowan said, ``After
investigating into the law and evidence, we concluded it would not
be appropriate to make this a death-penalty case.''
   Cowan indicated authorities did not feel the crime was
premeditated.
   Mahoney's bond was set at $270,000 cash. The non-murder counts
include 44 counts of wanton endangerment, 13 counts of assault and
one count of driving under the influence of alcohol.
   If Mahoney had been indicted and convicted of capital murder, he
could have been sent to the electric chair. The lesser murder
charge carries a possible prison sentence of 20 years to life.
   Referring to the lesser charge, Summers said: ``This has taken a
burden off him. The burden of what happened that night will never
be off him.''
   Cowan said if Mahoney were sentenced to life on one murder
count, he would have to serve at least 12 years before being
eligible for parole.
   Also Friday, the state medical examiner announced in Louisville
that the 24 children and three adults killed in the crash died of
smoke inhalation after the bus and the truck, which was going the
wrong way, collided on Interstate 71 near Carrollton. The bus,
owned by the Radcliff First Assembly of God church, was returning
from an outing to an amusement park in Ohio.
   The examiner, Dr. George Nichols, said that alcohol was found in
the bodies of four children, but he attributed this to a natural
process and not drinking.
   ``I believe the alcohol showed up because of the post-mortem
fermentation of blood sugar,'' Nichols said, adding that the
children probably had not drunk alcoholic beverages.
   The recommendation for capital murder had been made by Carroll
County Commonwealth Attorney John Ackman Jr., who suffered a heart
attack shortly after the accident, prompting the attorney general's
office to take over the case.
   Paul Richwalsky, the case's chief prosecutor, said he met with
more than 40 relatives of the victims Thursday night to explain the
less serious charge.
   Asked if any of the families were disappointed with the
decision, Richwalsky said, ``I can't say that. We had a frank and
candid discussion. If anyone was disappointed or disagreed, they
didn't verbalize it to me.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880723-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 1019EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-ShipCollision 1stLd-Writethru a0512 07-23 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Ship Collision, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0512,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Submarine Collides With Fishing Boat, 29 Missing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE number of missing, other details.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A submarine collided today with a fishing boat off
the port of Yokosuka, and police said 29 people were missing.
   The 2,200-ton Nadashio, a Maritime Self-Defense Force submarine,
collided with the fishing boat, the 150-ton No. 1 Fujimaru, two
miles off Yokosuka in the mouth of Tokyo Bay, Yokosuka police said.
   Police said 48 people, including 39 sport fishermen, were on
board the fishing boat, which sank less than two minutes after the
collision.
   Police officials said 19 fishermen and crewmen were rescued from
the boat, including a 38-year-old man who was hospitalized in
serious condition, and that the remaining 29 people aboard the boat
were missing.
   Previous police reports had said about 20 people were missing.
   There were no reports of injuries among the 75 men aboard the
submarine or on the extent of damage to the vessel, Maritime
Self-Defense Force officials said.
   Nineteen vessels and six helicopters from the Maritime
Self-Defense Force, Japan's navy, and the Maritime Safety Agency,
Japan's coast guard, were searching for the missing people, police
said.
   The cause of the accident was under investigation.
   At the time of the collision, the submarine was cruising on the
surface of the water on its way back to Yokosuka after a training
exercise, while the fishing boat was leaving Tokyo Bay, the
officials said.
   The submarine, built by Mitsubishi Heavy Industries, was
commissioned in March 1984. It has two diesel engines and is
equipped with six torpedo tubes.
   Defense Agency officials said the collision was the worst
involving Maritime Self-Defense Force vessels and civilian boats
since World War II.
   It was the first collision in Japan between a submarine and a
Japanese civilian ship since 1981, when a U.S. nuclear submarine
hit a freighter, killing two people, Kyodo News Service reported.
</TEXT>
