<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--Hartsfield-O'Hare     07-23 0162</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Hartsfield-O'Hare,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hartsfield Losing `World's Busiest Airport' Claim</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hartsfield Atlanta International Airport is in
danger of losing the title of world's busiest which it won last
year from Chicago's O'Hare International Airport.
   O'Hare was leading the race through the first half of the year,
according to Federal Aviation Administration figures reported
Friday. Through June, O'Hare had handled 397,033 takeoffs and
landings to Hartsfield's 396,722.
   That was a narrower margin, however, than the first quarter
figures, which put O'Hare at 196,589 and Hartsfield at 192,211.
   Last year, Hartsfield for the first time was the world's busiest
airport, handling 797,037 flights to O'Hare's 791,907.
   Cutbacks by Eastern Airlines, Hartsfield's No. 2 carrier, are
the biggest reason for the airport's decrease, said John Braden,
spokesman for the city's Aviation Department.
   Eastern has cut its schedule from an average 338 flights a day
at Hartsfield in February to 272 in June.
   Delta Air Lines, Hartsfield's top carrier, has 397 daily flights
there.
</TEXT>
