<DOCNO> AP880723-0080 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 1112EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-ConventionOverview Bjt   07-23 0818</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Convention Overview, Bjt,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>What Began With A Question Mark Ended With An Exclamation Point</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats, who began their quadrennial convention
with the threat of discord, headed home in dramatic unity to fight
the fall battle for the White House.
   ``This has been a great convention and it sets the stage for a
great Democratic win in November,'' the star attraction, Michael
Dukakis, told weary delegates gathered for one last party early
Friday.
   His nomination was a given coming into Atlanta, but the
atmosphere in which he would accept it was uncertain.
   Jesse Jackson's bus caravan rolled in Saturday with the
runner-up in the primaries unsure whether he ``had a place at the
table.''
   Dukakis arrived Sunday but refused to meet with the edgy Jackson
until he sat down with his trusted advisers to assess preliminary
talks between the two camps.
   Republicans had a ``truth squad'' in town and took advantage of
the apparent rift to boast of divided Democrats and a nominee-to-be
powerless to control his convention. But a show of unity just hours
before Democratic Chairman Paul Kirk gaveled the party's 40th
convention to order on Monday night ended most talk of discord,
although Republicans continued to assert Jackson was stealing the
show.
   After a nearly three-hour meeting Monday, Dukakis and Jackson
declared their differences resolved, with Dukakis promising Jackson
a role in the fall campaign and Jackson in turn promising his
support.
   ``We did not come here for fireworks; we came here for noble
works,'' Jackson said.
   With that, the convention opened _ to verbal fireworks, all
aimed at the Republicans.
   Keynote speaker Ann Richards pumped up the more than 4,000
delegates with fiery rhetoric that lampooned George Bush's claim of
Texas as his home state and portrayed the vice president as a
do-nothing member of a disgraced administration.
   ``I want to announce to the nation that in a little more than
100 days the
Reagan-Meese-Deaver-Nofziger-Poindexter-North-Weinberger-Watt-Gorsuch-Lavelle-Stockman-Haig-Bork-Noriega-George
Bush era will be over,'' the Texas treasurer said to thunderous
applause.
   The redeemed Jimmy Carter made a prime-time appearance, too,
adding his call for moral government to a convention with a
deliberate Southern flavor.
   Jackson had his night Tuesday, declaring himself qualified for
the presidency and predicting he would occupy the White House in
the future while urging his backers to support Dukakis in the fall.
   In a show of respect, many Dukakis delegates gave up their hall
passes to Jackson alternates and supporters and Dukakis placards
were kept low while a sea of red proclaimed ``Jesse!''
   Despite that gesture, not all of Jackson's backers got into the
Omni convention hall. Thousands were kept out after Atlanta's fire
marshal decided too many people had already been let in, a problem
that continued throughout the four-day gathering.
   Monday's detente had removed the potential for acrimony
Wednesday, when Dukakis won the party's blessing to take on Bush.
   All that was left was to crown the nominee, and after the
rousing speeches of Richards and Jackson, there was some worry the
star of the show might be upstaged.
   But actress cousin Olympia Dukakis, in a supporting role once
again, warmed the audience with an introduction of Dukakis the
frugal family man, and when the standard-bearer entered the hall he
was filled with emotion that carried over into the speech of his
lifetime.
   His eyes welled and his voice cracked when he talked of the
American dream of his late father _ a Greek immigrant who arrived
at Ellis Island with $25 and rose to become a wealthy doctor. His
smile was broad as he waved to his 84-year-old mother, herself an
immigrant, and his wife and children gathered in a skybox above the
made-for-TV rostrum at a made-for-TV convention.
   ``I'm a product of that dream,'' Dukakis said on his dream
night. ``My friends, we're going to forge a new era of greatness
for America.''
   Dukakis spoke forcefully about his themes of jobs and day care
and health care and competence, and sternly about his commitment to
public service and his perceived lack of such in the Reagan
administration.
   No stranger to television or teleprompters, Dukakis' delivery
was as carefully choreographed as the swirling lights and patriotic
music that had entertained the delegates before him.
   He ended with an Athenian pledge to strength, honesty and
integrity, but not before allowing screaming delegates to interrupt
repeatedly with a chant Democrats will surely take into the fall
campaign: ``Where was George? Where was George?'' _ a reference to
Bush's professed ignorance of administration blunders.
   In the end, Dukakis was joined by his family, then Bentsen and
his family, Jackson and his family, the Carters and other
contenders in what began as a crowded race for the nomination and
ended with the crowning of the man who likens the race to a
marathon.
   The confetti fell, the balloons followed and the Democrats went
home happy.
</TEXT>
