<HEAD>Former Policeman Sentenced For Sexual Torture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former policeman was sentenced
Saturday to five years in prison for molesting a woman he was
questioning about anti-government demonstrations.
   Moon Kwi-dong, 42, was found guilty of sexually harassing a
female student in July, 1986, to force her to give him information
about the unrest.
   The victim accused Moon of trying to rape her. The allegation
triggered widespread public criticism of the police.
   Prosecutors dropped the case for unknown reasons, but the
government dismissed Moon and several other police officers after
protests by dissident and human rights groups.
   The activists contended the case represented violations of human
rights under the government of former President Chun Doo-hwan.
   The charges were reinstated after Chun left office in February.
