<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0473 07-23 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0473,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Fire Tear Gas, Order Shops to Close</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with today's developments. TRIMS
outdated material. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police in the Holy City fired tear gas and shut
down Arab shops today after protesters hurled rocks and bottles at
them during a tense weekend of both Jewish and Moslem holidays.
   One Palestinian was hit in the head by a bottle, and an Israeli
was struck by a rock and taken to a hospital, Israel radio said.
Police said four Palestinians were arrested.
   In another development, Foreign Minister Shimon Peres' closest
aide sharply criticized Israeli policymakers for refusing to talk
to moderate Palestinian nationalists in the occupied territories.
   The aide, outgoing Foreign Ministry director-general Yossi
Beilin, singled out Shmuel Goren, a Defense Ministry official in
charge of the occupied territories, for conducting a ``too
simplistic carrot-and-stick policy'' in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip.
   Hundreds of police reinforcements were deployed today in
Jerusalem to prevent disturbances as Jews and Moslems both prepared
to mark holy days associated with the Temple Mount, a site sacred
to their faiths.
   In the walled Old City, an Associated Press photographer saw
police fire large quantities of tear gas to disperse protesters who
threw rocks at them from the roofs of buildings in the city's
Christian Quarter.
   Hundreds of shoppers and tourists, some holding handkerchiefs to
their noses, streamed out of the city's Damascus Gate as the white
tear gas floated over the streets.
   The trouble started after 60 mourners marched in a memorial
procession for 15-year-old Nidal Fuad Rabadi, who was killed by
Israeli troops Tuesday on the northern outskirts of Jerusalem.
   Rabadi's death caused several days of rioting throughout Arab
east Jerusalem, which Israel annexed after capturing it from Jordan
in 1967.
   After the procession, police ordered the storekeepers to close
their shops and fired tear gas to disperse the crowds.
   Merchants also accused police of overturning open air stalls
lining the sidewalk near the Damascus Gate, where the ground was
strewn with vegetables and boxes of goods.
   The U.S. State Department voiced concern Friday over resurgent
violence in the occupied lands. Over the past week, nine Arabs have
died, including the first Israeli Arab fatality since the
Palestinian rebellion began Dec. 8.
   According to U.N. figures, 231 Arabs have been killed in the
uprising. Four Israelis have also died.
   Israeli officials have said Jerusalem is becoming a center of
the violence after months of relative calm in the city.
   Today's incident took place while the Old City was teeming with
shoppers preparing for the four-day Moslem Eid al-Adha holiday,
which starts Sunday. The holiday marks Abraham's sacrifice of his
son Isaac at the Temple Mount.
   At sundown today, Jews start observing the Tisha B'Av fast day,
which marks the destruction of the Jewish Temple by the Romans
2,000 years ago.
</TEXT>
