<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 1146EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MustardPickpockets     07-23 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mustard Pickpockets,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Nab Two Alleged Pickpockets Using Mustard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two groups of pickpockets armed with mustard
have been arrested at Kennedy International Airport, where they had
been preying on foreign tourists, a Port Authority spokesman said.
   The arrests were made Friday night by an undercover team
fighting a rash of incidents over the past six weeks involving
mainly Japanese tourists, said Mark Marchese, a spokesman for the
Port Authority of New York and New Jersey.
   A technique becoming common among pickpockets is to discreetly
squirt the intended victim with mustard or ketchup, then point it
out and pretend to help him clean up. While the person is
distracted, his pocket is picked or his bags stolen.
   The first group was arrested about 7:45 p.m. when undercover
Port Authority police saw three men and a woman crowd a Japanese
woman in the Pan American Worldport Terminal, Marchese said. The
woman had just gotten off a plane from Japan and had her luggage
with her.
   Two of the men engaged her in conversation while a third was
feeling her luggage, according to the report filed by PA Detective
Evan Goodstein. Police moved in to arrest the four, all from
Queens, when the woman pickpocket took out a jar of mustard and
opened it, Marchese said.
   Five minutes later, police saw three men approach a man who had
just disembarked from the same plane.
   ``One man squirted mustard on his sleeve, the second began
wiping it off,'' Marchese said. Police moved in as the third man
went for the victim's bag. Thre three ran out of the terminal but
their car was stopped as it was trying to leave the airport.
   The seven were all charged with jostling, a Class A misdemeanor
punishable by up to one year in jail upon conviction, he said. The
undercover operation at Kennedy will continue, Marchese said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
