<DOCNO> AP880723-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 1213EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-MoslemPilgrimage     07-23 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Moslem Pilgrimage,0684</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Annual Moslem Pilgrimage Comes to Climax</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MECCA, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of thousands of white-robed
Moslems prayed, chanted and listened to sermons on Mount Arafat in
108-degree heat Saturday during the climax of the annual pilgrimage
to Mecca.
   Iran said there were protests in the holy city, but a Saudi
official denied the report.
   For the second time since Wednesday, Tehran radio said there
were political demonstrations against the ruling Saudi family and
against the United States, Soviet Union and Israel.
   The Iranian government-run radio also claimed police
``attacked'' some demonstrators. Saudi authorities, however, said
the pilgrimage, or hajj, proceeded in ``peace and security.''
   The pilgrims on Saturday ascended to Nimra Mosque on Mount
Arafat after trekking from Mecca, nine miles away.
   Smiling men and women draped in their seamless white pieces of
cloth brandished copies of the Koran, Moslems' holy book, during
the ceremony inside the mosque. The ceremony was broadcast live on
Saudi television and via satellite.
   In their midst were Saudi security men, dressed in green
fatigues and caps. Authorities said 20,000 of them guarded the
pilgrimage. The pilgrimage season officially began July 15 with the
sighting of the crescent moon, marking the start of the Moslem holy
month of Eid al-Adha.
   The ``Wukuf,'' or standing at Arafat, represents the culmination
of the annual hajj, which all of the world's 850 million Moslems
are expected to make at least once if they can afford it.
   The culmination includes the stoning of the devil, in
commemoration of the prophet Abraham's refusal to be tempted into
disobeying God's order that he sacrifice his son.
   On Sunday, after slaughtering sheep to represent the sacrifice
of a sheep instead of Abraham's son, the pilgrims begin a four-day
feast.
   Prayer leader Sheik Abdel-Aziz Al-Sheikh called upon Moslems to
respect and maintain the sanctity of Mecca's Grand Mosque as
``Allah has made it a place of refuge and security.''
   Outside Nimra Mosque, waves of black and colored umbrellas
shaded pilgrims from the sun as loudspeakers broadcast the ceremony.
   The temperature was about five degrees cooler than average for
this time of year, but many cases of heat exhaustion and sunstroke
were reported.
   On Friday, the pilgrims gathered for prayers at the Grand Mosque
in Mecca, which harbors the Kaaba, Islam's holiest shrine.
   It was after those prayers, according to Tehran radio, that
hundreds of pilgrims demonstrated in Mecca against the deaths last
year of 402 people, mostly Iranian pilgrims, in the holy city.
   Saudi authorities said many of those killed last year were
trampled in a stampede, and they denied Iranian claims that police
opened fire on the march.
   Parts of the latest report by the Tehran radio, monitored by the
British Broadcasting Corp., were indistinct, but monitors said they
heard no reference to injuries.
   ``Hundreds of Arab, Turk, Afghan, Pakistani and American
pilgrims demonstrated in Mecca today (Friday), chanting slogans ..
. and carrying placards condemning the Al-Saud regime in their
killing of over 400 pilgrims of the holy sanctuary last year in
Mecca,'' Tehran radio said.
   It added: ``According to received reports, the Saudi regime's
police ... subjected the demonstrators to severe control and
surrounded them. In some sections they attacked the ranks of the
marchers.''
   Government-run Saudi radio quoted an unidentified official
source as saying the report was ``made up'' and one of a series of
``lies and fabrications'' broadcast by Iran to create tension.
   Gen. Abdullah Abdel-Rahman Al-Sheikh, director general of Saudi
security, said there were no incidents.
   Prince Majed, governor of Mecca, issued a statement to the radio
hailing the ``success'' of the hajj rituals.
   By Saudi count, there are 762,755 pilgrims from more than 130
Moslem nations who converged on the kingdom this year, joining an
estimated half million from within Saudi Arabia.
   There were about 1,000 American pilgrims, according to estimates
by the U.S. Consulate in Jiddah, a Red Sea port city about 40 miles
from Mecca.
   Non-Moslems are barred from Mecca.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
