<HEAD>People In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billionaire philanthropist H. Ross Perot isn't
happy with developments at a local arboretum and botanical garden,
and he wants the park to give back his multimillion dollar donation.
   Perot donated $2 million and pledged $6 million in October 1986
for expansion and development of the park, which is run by the
Dallas Arboretum and Botanical Society.
   Voters approved $7.5 million in bonds to improve the 66-acre
park, but only $2.5 million has been issued and Perot said because
of the downturn in the economy he doubts enough public and private
money will be available to develop the arboretum into a world-class
facility.
   ``We can't afford to spend money on things like this now,''
Perot said. ``There are no villains. It's the economic period we're
going through now. We had a plan when we started. It went from
world-class to a scaled-back, nice arboretum.''
   Robert Hoffman, chairman of the society, said Perot's $2 million
had not been spent and that the society's board will meet Thursday
to decide on a response.
   If the arboretum board returns his money, Perot said he will
give the funds to people who need it.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors for Gov. Bill Clements, who
suffered a mild stroke last week, postponed his hospital release
Saturday after detecting a heart rhythm irregularity, the
governor's spokesman said.
   Dr. David Morris at Seton Medical Center described Clements as
``very stable overall,'' and he is listed in good condition at the
hospital, said Reggie Bashur, the governor's press secretary.
   Morris, a heart specialist, and Dr. Jerry Tindel, a neurologist,
earlier said tests indicated Clements' heartbeat irregularity could
have caused a tiny blood clot to form in his heart before passing
through his bloodstream and into his brain, causing the stroke
Monday night.
   The governor admitted himself to the hospital Tuesday evening.
He suffered some vision problems in his right eye, doctors said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WARWICK, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country singer Willie Nelson's support of
an American Indian convicted of killing two FBI agents has drawn
the ire of police, who are threatening to picket his concerts next
weekend.
   Owners of a theater where Nelson is scheduled to perform tried
to block the picketing, but Superior Court Judge Antonio S. Almeida
on Friday refused. The judge said he will consider a request by the
Warwick Musical Theater for stringent protest guidelines.
   Police from Rhode Island and other states are planning to picket
Nelson's concert to protest his support of Leonard Peltier.
   Peltier, 43, was convicted in 1977 and sentenced to two
consecutive life terms for killing the FBI agents during a gunfight
on a South Dakota reservation. He is currently serving his sentence
at a federal penitentiary in Kansas.
   Nelson held a concert last October to raise money for Peltier's
defense.
   Rodney Patterson, president of the Providence Fraternal Order of
Police and a picket organizer, said police have no intention of
protesting on private property. ``We're planning on acting like
professionals,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 14-year-old violinist shrugged off her debut
with the Cincinnati Symphony Orchestra as just another activity for
a busy teen-ager, but she's already decided to pursue a musical
career.
   ``I'm the type of person who tries to fit in everything I can,''
said Alyssa Park. ``I hate to miss anything, especially something
with my friends.''
   Under the direction of Jesus Lopez-Cobos, Miss Park performed
Wieniawski's Concerto No. 1 before 4,000 people Friday at the
outdoor Riverbend Music Center.
   ``Park is an inspiring performer with bright prospects indeed,''
wrote Ray Cooklis, music critic for The Cincinnati Enquirer.
   Miss Park, of Lexington, Ky., began studying the violin at age
5. She made her professional debut at age 11 with the Cincinnati
Chamber Orchestra.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Cagney & Lacey'' may have been canceled
recently by CBS, but the television show received high marks again
from members of Viewers for Quality Television.
   The show was voted Best Quality Drama for the fourth straight
year in a recent poll conducted by the group. ``Cagney & Lacey''
received 29 percent of the vote from the 1,500 members who
participated in the poll, said director Dorothy Swanson of Fairfax
Station, Va.
   The citizens lobbying group, first organized several years ago
in a successful effort to keep ``St. Elsewhere'' on the air, voted
its Best Quality Comedy award to CBS' ``Designing Women.''
