<2ND_LINE>PM-Ponytail Lawsuit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0406,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hair-Pulling Lawsuit Settled For $65,000</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 10th (next-to-last) graf, ``Emeis' attorney xxx, to
CORRECT that Beam is Kovel's attorney, NOT Emeis'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nurse who says she suffered
excruciating pain and emotional distress after a doctor yanked her
ponytail has been awarded $65,000 in an out-of-court settlement.
   Jean Kovel said she was sitting at the nurse's station in
Memorial Hospital on Sept. 25, 1984, making notes in a patient's
chart, when someone pulled hard on her ponytail and said, ``Hey,
babe, what's going on?''
   ``My head jerked back so hard that the chair came up resting on
the back two wheels,'' she said. ``The pain was excruciating.''
   She said she turned around to find William Emeis, an
obstetrician-gynecologist, smiling at her.
   Emeis denies pulling Kovel's hair, but this week his insurance
company paid $65,000 to settle her lawsuit charging assault,
negligence and emotional distress.
   Kovel, 31, said this week that the pain in her neck, back and
shoulder never went away and has affected her life.
   ``I was off work for five weeks, lying in bed or undergoing
therapy every day. I had to wear a cervical collar, take pain
medication and muscle relaxants,'' she said.
   She said she had to hire a maid because she couldn't perform
some household chores, and had to give up her daily jog because of
her injury.
   ``I can't even bend down to hug my two children before they go
to sleep,'' she said.
   Kovel's attorney, Jack Beam, said Kovel didn't recall the
incident when he gave a deposition. A pre-trial statement filed on
the doctor's behavior suggested it was horseplay.
   Said Kovel: ``I don't know whether it was his way of greeting me
or if he wanted to rip my hair out. We hadn't had any
disagreement.''
</TEXT>
