<1ST_LINE>r a AM-VanderbiltSuicide     07-23 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vanderbilt Suicide,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gloria Vanderbilt Under Doctor's Care Following Son's Suicide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heiress and designer Gloria Vanderbilt was under
a doctor's care Saturday following the suicide of her son, who
jumped to his death from a 14th-floor penthouse terrace,
authorities said.
   Carter V. Cooper, 23, left no note before jumping from his
mother's apartment Friday night, said police spokesman Officer
Peter O'Donnell.
   Ms. Vanderbilt, the ``poor little rich girl'' who became the
focus of a heated custody battle in the 1930s, was put under a
physician's care after witnessing the suicide, police said.
   Cooper's father was writer Wyatt Emory Cooper, Ms. Vanderbilt's
fourth husband. She hasn't remarried since Cooper died in 1978
during surgery for a heart ailment.
   Ms. Vanderbilt, 64, is the great-great-granddaughter of railroad
and shipping financier Cornelius Vanderbilt.
   Beneficiary of a $5 million trust fund, Ms. Vanderbilt became
famous at age 10 as the ``poor little rich girl'' _ the object of a
sensational custody fight between her globe-trotting mother and
matriarchal aunt.
   After growing up with her aunt, Gertrude Whitney, she went to
Hollywood and dated celebrities such as actor Errol Flynn and
billionaire Howard Hughes.
   She married four times _ the first when she was only 17,
prompting her aunt to disinherit her. She and Wyatt Cooper, who wed
in 1963, had another son, Anderson.
</TEXT>
