<DOCNO> AP880723-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 1338EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN-Democrats-Cubans     07-23 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN-Democrats-Cubans,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats See Cuban Opportunity</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-CVN-Convention Overview Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats think they can lure more votes this
year out of the Cuban-American Republican stronghold, as some Miami
Cubans try to increase their conservative ethnic group's
involvement in a national Hispanic coalition.
   ``We see the Cuban community as an area of opportunity,' said
Jorge Haynes, a Mexican-American who has been an aide to Florida
House Speaker Jon Mills, D-Gainesville, and was spokesman here for
the National Hispanic Caucus.
   Haynes said efforts to increase Hispanics' political clout by
having Mexicans, Puerto Ricans, Cubans and other Latins working
together foundered with election of Ronald Reagan in 1980.
   But the group held daily, well-attended meetings last week
during the Democratic National Convention, Haynes said.
   Coral Gables banker Luis Lauredo, a Cuban-American who was a
Carter administration aide, was selected as a co-chairman of the
group.
   Simon Ferro, the 34-year-old Cuban-born attorney who heads the
Dade County Democratic Party, said Cubans traditionally haven't
been active in national Hispanic groups.
   Their immigration story is different than those of the Puerto
Ricans and Mexicans. The Cubans fled a homeland, where they had a
comfortable standard of living, because of Communist takeover and
have made anti-Communist stands a major part of their politics.
   Ferro noted that in Dade, 97,000 Cubans are registered as
Republicans, compared to 23,000 Democrats. He said the figures
don't include second-generation Cuban-Americans who were born in
this country, and the younger Cubans are more likely to join the
Democrats and identify with other Hispanic groups.
   ``It's been frustrating, but it's getting better,'' Ferro said.
   He said Cubans have seen that despite tough rhetoric, President
Reagan's Cuba policies weren't particularly strong.
   Ferro said he would emphasize that the Democrats are closer to
the Cubans' true best interests.
   ``Every time that something good happened to us _ the doors were
opened, the air bridge from Cuba, the social programs that helped
us _ the Democrats were in office,'' Ferro said.
   ``Cuba remains a priority, but there are other issues that bind
us together,'' Ferro added.
   He said the Cubans, with their strong anti-Communist interests,
can still fit into the Democratic Party just as do Jews with their
strong stands on Israel and blacks with their anti-South Africa
interest.
   ``I think other Hispanic groups should defer to us on Cuba. I
see no contradiction with the Democratic Party condemning Cuba
within the framework of human rights, just as it condemns South
Africa,'' Ferro said.
   Campaign planners in the state for Democratic presidential
nominee Michael Dukakis say they won't concede the Cuban vote to
Vice President George Bush and probably will have Dukakis and vice
presidential nominee Lloyd Bentsen campaign among them. Both
nominees speak Spanish.
   Haynes, from Texas, said Bentsen's popularity with Hispanics in
Texas and his conservative stands might play well with Cubans.
   Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., said he received 25 present to 35
percent of the Cuban vote in his 1986 election, after 1984
presidential nominee Walter Mondale got about 5 percent.
   ``I think there is the legitimate basis for a transition. I
don't think it's going to happen overnight,'' Graham said.
   Tommy Thomas, a Southern co-chairman for the Bush campaign and
former Florida Republican Party chairman, said there's little
chance Dukakis will pick up Cuban votes. Republicans will be
emphasizing his liberal positions and opposition to aiding
Nicaraguan Contra rebels.
   ``Our Cubans are going to be wholeheartedly for George Bush,''
Thomas said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
