<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 1409EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ReformedKid     07-23 0672</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reformed Kid,0690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Girl Who Met Pope, Then Became Addict And Hooker, Returns To
Writing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Dollars Canadian</NOTE>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In 1984, at age 13, Evelyn
Lau was one of 12 winners in an essay contest who got to meet Pope
John Paul II. At 16, she had become a runaway supporting herself
and her drug habit with prostitution.
   ``I told myself this wasn't prostitution, it's just give and
take,'' Lau said. ``It was there, and I had about 25 cents in my
pocket, and I had an amazing capacity at first to just block it
out.''
   Then she realized that her writing was taking a back seat to
drugs.
   ``That totally destroyed me,'' said Lau.
   After an unsuccessful suicide attempt, she wound up in a
hospital a year ago. She decided to stop doing drugs and resume
writing.
   Now, at 17, she has a Canada Council grant for $13,000 (more
than $10,700 U.S.) for her writing and a contract with a Toronto
publisher for her first book, to be called ``Small Lives: The Diary
of a Street Kid.''
   She also has more dubious signs of success _ legal problems and
lawyer's fees, over which she has little control because she is now
a ward of the state.
   She left home because of friction with her parents, possibly the
reason social caseworkers decided not to return her to her parents.
And since she was a juvenile not with her family, Canadian law
required that she be made a ward of the state.
   She said officials in the Social Services Ministry have told her
they are not sure she can handle the grant, which comes out to
about $1,100 (more than $900 U.S.) a month. She is negotiating with
public trustee Steven Rumsey and the ministry superintendent over
how her grant should be paid.
   ``It's hard enough being a writer and not getting a paycheck
every two weeks, and the rewards are few and far between,'' Lau
said after she learned of the award last week. ``Then when you get
rewarded, they take it away from you.
   ``I felt like I was more of a human out there (on the street)
than I am now. At least I had some control.''
   ``I'm supposed to be jumping up and down, but I feel like every
time I do something that everybody should be happy about they have
an anxiety attack,'' she said. ``They're afraid I'm going to take
the money and blow it, which isn't even feasible.''
   ``If I went out and got a job that paid $1,100 a month, they
wouldn't come after me and say, `You're making too much money,' so
how is this different? Isn't this work?'' she said.
   ``We want to make sure the monies are used for the purposes
intended by the grant,'' Rumsey said Wednesday. ``We would be
responsible in looking after the funds as trustees.''
   Lau also receives $480 a month in social assistance. She pays
$300 for rent and uses the rest for writing expenses.
   ``When I get my check I buy my supplies first _ paper, ribbons,
stamps. I'm constantly submitting my short stories and poems to
magazines, and I'm not going to give that up, but it's amazing how
much it costs,'' Lau said.
   Her first encounter with the problems of being a ward of the
state came when the public trustee hired lawyer Bruce McColl to
review her contract with literary agent Denise Bukowski, her book
contract with Collins Publishers and her manuscript for any
potential libel.
   McColl's $175-an-hour fee is to be paid from Lau's advance on
royalties from Collins, although the size of the advance was not
known.
   Bukowski said the lawyer is unnecessary because the publisher
has its own lawyers to check the manuscript, butMcColl said he
redrafted the agent's contract, approved the publisher's contract.
   ``We have a responsibility to protect the child,'' Rumsey said.
``The publisher may well have counsel, but that doesn't necessarily
mean the best advice is going to go to the infant.''
</TEXT>
