<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Monsoon     07-23 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Monsoon,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Monsoon Toll Rises to 255</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rains and landslides were reported
across India on Saturday, and the death toll from the annual
monsoon rains rose to 255, reports said.
   The hill resort of Simla in the northern state of Himachal
Pradesh was cut off for the third day, the Press Trust of India
reported. Rail and road traffic to Simla, the state capital, has
been disrupted because of landslides and heavy rains.
   At least 20 more deaths were reported as a result of the rain,
which began last month. The rain, eagerly awaited by Indians after
three years of drought, has caused widespread flooding.
   In New Delhi, officials began evacuating people living in
low-lying areas near the Yamuna river.
   Warnings were issued to villagers living on the outskirts of the
capital because of the rising water levels of the river, the Press
Trust of India said.
   Five people died in Himachal Pradesh state in floods or
landslides, the United News of India reported.
   Eight more people were killed when heavy rains caused a mudslide
in northeastern Bombay, the news agency said.
   Three people died in Jammu district in Kashmir state when their
hut collapsed, and four people died in Uttar Pradesh state, UNI
said. Most of the deaths occurred in the past 24 hours.
</TEXT>
