<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 1416EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Reagan-Hungary Bjt   07-23 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Hungary, Bjt,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hungarian Leader, Seeking Closer Ties to West, Visits Washington</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungarian leader Karoly Grosz, eager to
strengthen ties to the West as part of an ambitious reform program,
comes to Washington this week on the first visit by a Hungarian of
his rank since the country came under communist rule 40 years ago.
   Since becoming premier in June 1987, Grosz has moved decisively
to pursue economic and political openings to the West, where the
image of Hungary for years had been largely shaped by the Soviet
Army's smashing of an anti-Moscow uprising in 1956.
   Grosz's 11-day, U.S. visit, which began last week and took him
to Illinois, California and New York, has its high point Wednesday
when has a luncheon with President Reagan during a White House
visit.
   He also will meet with Secretary of State George Shultz,
congressional leaders and Democratic presidential nominee Michael
Dukakis.
   Grosz, who became Communist Party general secretary last May in
addition to premier, is the first Warsaw Pact leader to make an
official visit to Washington since 1978 when President Carter
received Romanian leader Nicolai Ceaucescu.
   Grosz, 57, is from the same generation as Mikhail Gorbachev and,
like the Soviet leader, he has called for a new era of openness and
economic restructuring.
   U.S. officials, insisting on anonymity, said that Grosz will be
encouraged during his talks here to continue his announced policy
of seeking increased trade with and investment from Western
countries.
   To improve efficiency, Grosz has been pushing market-oriented
approaches but this and other measures have increased unemployment
levels in Hungary. Another problem area for Grosz is Hungary's $11
billion foreign debt.
   Among economic goals approved by the party since Grosz'
accession are more foreign investment, fewer restrictions on the
ownership of foreign capital, an expansion of private initiatives,
and a greater voice for consumers.
   In Chicago last Wednesday, Grosz witnessed the signing of a $115
million joint venture between a Hungarian entity and Guardian
Industries Corp., an Illinois-based glass manufacturer.
   ``We have seen science and technology tear down borders between
countries and even continents ... and those who come to recognize
this will be in an advantageous position,'' said Grosz.
   Grosz also met with officials of MacDonald's Corp. to discuss a
larger presence in Hungary for the fast food giant. The firm
already has a thriving operation in Budapest.
   Grosz has been courting West European leaders as well. He was
received warmly on visits to Bonn and London and three weeks ago,
Hungary became the first communist country to reach an agreement
with the European Community.
   The accord will gradually allow expanded Hungarian exports to
Western Europe by removing present tariffs and quotas between now
and 1995.
   Still, Hungary is intent on maintaining its traditional role as
a member of the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact. More than three decades
after the Soviet invasion of Hungary, an estimated 65,000 Soviet
troops are deployed there.
   U.S. intelligence officials recently received indications that
the Soviets were planning to withdraw these forces but thus far
there has been no announcement.
</TEXT>
