<1ST_LINE>d a AM-PacificQuake     07-23 0149</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pacific Quake,0152</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Large Quake In Pacific Ocean</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MENLO PARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A large earthquake struck Saturday in
the southwest Pacific Ocean on Saturday, but there were no reports
of damage, officials said.
   The temblor struck at 1:17 a.m. Sunday local time (11:17 a.m.
EDT Saturday) and registered 6.8 on the Richter scale, said Pat
Jorgenson, of the U.S. Geological Survey in Menlo Park.
   The quake was located about 150 miles northeast of Rabaul, New
Britain, off the northeast coast of New Guinea. No damage was
reported and no tidal wave warning was issued, Jorgenson said.
   The quake was reported by the National Earthquake Information
Center in Golden, Colo., she said.
   The Richter scale measures ground motion and energy released by
a quake. The devastating 1906 quake in San Francisco, which took
place before the scale was devised, has been estimated at 8.3. on
the Richter scale.
</TEXT>
