<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Guatemala-Kidnapping     07-23 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Guatemala-Kidnapping,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kidnapped Guatemalan Judge Set Free; Friend Murdered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A criminal court judge kidnapped last week
was freed unharmed, but a friend abducted with him was tortured and
shot to death, police said Saturday.
   The abduction of the two men sparked a strike by Guatemala's
judges, clerks, lawyers and prosecutors.
   A National Police communique said Judge Sergio Anibal Trejo
Duque of the 7th Penal Court was kidnapped in Guatemala City along
with his friend, Carlos Moran Amaya, on Wednesday.
   Trejo Duque, 48, was set free Friday night, but his friend was
found dead earlier Friday, the communique said. It said Moran Amaya
was shot and his body showed signs of torture.
   When interviewed by reporters Saturday, Trejo Duque only said,
``They (the kidnappers) treated me well.'' He refused to say more
about his captivity.
   Members of the judiciary throughout the country stopped handling
cases in protest Friday morning. They called an end to the strike
Saturday after the National Police issued its communique.
   Trejo Duque's court has been handling a number of cases
involving members of the Treasury Police accused of robberies,
kidnappings and assassinations.
</TEXT>
