<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0515,0690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heavy Fighting Reported As U.N. Peace Mission Nears</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to CORRECT Iraqi minister's surname to
Jassem thruout. Pickup 7th graf pvs, ``Iran's official...
^By NEIL MACFARQUHAR</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said Iraqi forces today moved across
huge sections of Iranian territory and bombed targets with chemical
weapons.
   The fighting, reported by both countries, came as a U.N. team
prepared to travel to both nations to arrange a truce.
   Tehran radio urged all able-bodied Iranians to rush to the
front, saying troops were needed to ``thwart Iraq's new round of
mischiefs.''
   ``The General Command staff seriously wants all the trained
forces that are ready to go to the fronts to apply immediately to
resistance bases for rapid dispatch,'' the radio said in a report
monitored in Nicosia.
   In Baghdad, Iraqi Minister of Information Latif Nusayyib Jassem
reacted to the Iranian statement by saying Iraq had no desire to
occupy Iranian territory.
   ``All we want is to liberate our occupied areas... We have no
aggressive intentions against Iran,'' Jassem was quoted as saying
by the official Iraqi News Agency.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency said Iraqi troops
had pushed across the border in the southern front and advanced to
within 24 miles of Ahwaz, capital of the Khuzestan province and 54
miles from the nearest border. It said hand-to-hand fighting was
continuing in the area.
   Iraqi troops were pushed back in the nearby Salamcheh region,
IRNA said, with the bodies of ``hundreds of Iraqi soldiers
scattered on the battlefield.''
   In the central sector, IRNA said that Iraqi warplanes dropped
chemical weapons on two villages between Sar-e Pol Zahab and
Gilan-e Gharb to the south, ``wounding a large number of
villagers.''
   In an earlier report, IRNA said Iranian forces repelled an Iraqi
attack at a southern border area west of the Iranian town of
Khorramshahron.
   ``The battle now continues between Iran's Moslem soldiers and
the invading Iraqis,'' IRNA said, adding that the Iraqis suffered
heavy casualties.
   IRNA said the Iranians used long-range artillery to bomb a
housing complex in Iraq's northern Sulimaniyeh province. The report
said three civilians were killed and four were wounded in the
attack Friday night.
   The news agency denied an Iranian report that Iran had shot down
an Iraqi jet fighter over the southern front.
   Both Iran and Iraw rarely let foreign observers near the
warfront and reports of fighting cannot be independently confirmed.
   On Friday, Iran's revolutionary patriarch, Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini, said the war with Iran was not over despite Iran's
acceptance Monday of a U.N. cease-fire resolution.
   ``My revolutionary children, you should not think that the war
has come to an end. Arm yourselves with the weapons of faith and
holy war,'' he said on Tehran Radio.
   Iraq said it regained on Friday the last remaining territory the
Iranians had captured in the eight-year war. Iran accused the
Iraqis of using chemical weapons.
   Both countries accepted an invitation by Javier Perez de
Cuellar, the U.N. secretary-general, to send their foreign
ministers to New York next week for meetings on implementing
Resolution 598, which the Security Council passed unanimously July
20, 1987.
   Iraq wants direct negotiations with Iran, and the Iranians
indicated Friday they may accept such talks if Perez de Cuellar
requests it.
   The Iraqis also said they would welcome a team Perez de Cuellar
is sending to arrange the details of a cease-fire. The nine
military officers and one civilian are due in Tehran on Sunday and
expect to be in the region about a week.
   A military communique read on Iraqi television Friday said: ``We
retook whatever was left of our land from the Iranians'' in an
offensive named ``In God We Trust 4.'' It said the victory ``will
acelerate the achievement of peace through the signing of a genuine
peace treaty via direct talks.''
   In the past few months Iraq has regained large areas that had
been captured by Iran, including the Faw Peninsula and marshlands
east of Basra, the Iraqi port.
</TEXT>
