<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SecondDeath Bjt   07-23 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Second Death, Bjt,0675</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Charged In Death of Another Honeywell Co-worker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who was rehired by Honeywell Inc. after
serving four years in prison for strangling a co-worker has been
charged with killing another co-worker, a woman he allegedly
stalked and threatened for weeks.
   Randy Don Landin, who surrendered after the first slaying in
1979, turned himself in again Friday in the shotgun slaying of
Kathleen Nesser, saying ``he'd heard we'd been looking for him,''
said Sgt. Jeff McFarlane of suburban New Hope.
   Police had launched a search for Landin after Nesser, 25, was
slain early Tuesday outside her New Hope home, where she lived with
her 18-month-old daughter.
   Honeywell spokesman Tim Morin said he didn't know the specifics
of Landin's rehiring, but ``the philosophy we have is that we don't
discriminate when it comes to hiring practices.''
   Police had been trying to get the victim to file a complaint
about threats allegedly made by Landin. `If I knew then what I know
now, I guess we probably would have tried to move heaven and Earth
to prevent what happened,'' said McFarlane.
   Landin, 31, was charged with murder and jailed on $1 million
bail.
   In 1980, he pleaded guilty to murdering his girlfriend, Nancy
Miller. He was released from prison in 1984 after serving 4{ years
of an eight-year sentence reduced for good behavior and a year
spent in jail awaiting trial.
   Landin, who worked for Honeywell from 1977 to 1979, when he was
indicted in Miller's death, was rehired a few weeks after his
release.
   Police said Nesser befriended Landin at Honeywell's facility in
the suburb of St. Louis Park, where they were maintenance workers.
Landin told Nesser that Miller's death was an accident, police said.
   But Landin began stalking Nesser after she rebuffed his romantic
advances, harassing her with phone calls, police said. A death
threat note found on her locker about a month ago read ``One more
day dead,'' McFarlane said.
   St. Louis Park police found only Nesser's fingerprints on the
locker door, McFarlane said Saturday.
   Some residents of New Hope said Nesser ``was scared to death of
the man,'' who frequently visited her home. Neighbors said they
heard her phone ring unanswered for hours.
   On June 30, Nesser complained to her supervisor that she was
being harassed by another worker. On July 1, Honeywell officials
went to police with Nesser's concerns and six days later she was
reassigned to the company's Plymouth plant, McFarlane said.
   Nesser also changed her telephone number.
   Landin telephoned his supervisor on July 7 and resigned,
McFarlane said.
   McFarlane said police asked Nesser to make a statement about the
incidents so they could arrest Landin on charges of making
terroristic threats. She was scheduled to make the statement 10
days before she was killed but failed to show, he said.
   McFarlane, who talked to Nesser the Friday before her death,
said she ``was getting kind of complacent because there hadn't been
any threats for almost a week since she changed her phone number.''
   ``She got some breathing space after her transfer to Plymouth
and she felt that, if she charged him, it would make things worse
and she was feeling better,'' he said.
   On Monday, McFarlane said, St. Louis Park police told him they
had not heard from Nesser and had not been able to contact her
because her number had been changed.
   ``If you want to assess real blame, we're all guilty,'' he said.
``He was convicted, he got a sweet deal for no reason. He got out.
... Honeywell hired him back. This is just a whole series of errors
that culminated in a tragedy.''
   In a statement issued Friday through Honeywell, Nesser's mother,
Patricia Nesser, said: ``We are relieved that a suspect in Kathy's
murder is now in custody. I have no hate for him; it is not in me
to feel malice for him, at least not now.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880723-0120 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 1538EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SpanielDefense     07-23 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spaniel Defense,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wife Freed Cleared In Shooting Prompted By Attack On Her and
Spaniel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No charges will be filed against a
woman who killed her husband after he threatened to shot the
couple's cocker spaniel, then started beating her when she
protested, police said.
   According to police, Ralph Hess Jr. said he was fed up with the
family's ``useless'' cocker spaniel and asked his wife, Katherine
Elaine Hess, ``Where's the gun?'' She refused to get it for him and
Hess turned on her.
   ``He then physically attacked her and knocked her to the floor,
kicking her and digging his fingernails into her arm as he was
kicking her,'' said George Pinckney, a police spokesman said.
   During the struggle late Thursday in a motel room, Mrs. Hess
reached under a nightstand, grabbed a small-caliber handgun and
shot her husband in the shoulder. Hess, 35, died a short time
later, police said.
   On Friday, the Pasco-Pinellas State Attorney's Office ruled that
Mrs. Hess acted in self-defense, said William Doniel, another
police spokesman.
   Pinckney said police closed the investigation and released Mrs.
Hess, 34.
   Police said the couple had come to Florida from Tennessee four
days before the shooting to open a business with another couple,
whom police would not identify.
   Motel manager Bob Carpenter said the Hesses were not guests at
the motel, but were visiting another couple who were staying there.
   ``After the shooting, I saw a cream-colored cocker spaniel
running around,'' he said.
</TEXT>
