<2ND_LINE>AM-Welcome Wagon Suit,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Welcome Wagon Sues Over Movie Joke</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Welcome Wagon International says an
off-color joke in the motion picture ``Big'' infringes on its
trademark and casts aspersions on its hostesses.
   The company, founded and based in Memphis, filed the federal
suit Friday against the producers and distributors of the film,
seeking an injunction against release of the movie for television
or videotape distribution.
   The action also seeks removal of the reference to Welcome Wagon
and payment of unspecified damages to the company.
   The film, which has already been released, stars Tom Hanks and
tells the story of a boy who gets his wish to become an adult.
   ``During (Hanks' character's) first day at work, one of his
co-workers points to a voluptuous woman who is dressed in red,''
the lawsuit says. The co-worker comments on the woman's sexual
prowess, saying, ``She is what we call the company `Welcome Wagon.'
''
   Welcome Wagon says in the lawsuit that its name is a trademark
and that the organization offers advertising to business sponsors
via gifts distributed by paid hostesses who visit people in their
homes.
   The reference in the movie conveys a false impression that a
typical Welcome Wagon hostess is promiscuous, the lawsuit says.
   Among the defendants are 20th Century Fox Film Corp.; American
Entertainment Partnership II, L.P.; Gracie Films and James L.
Brooks.
   Telephone messages for comment left Saturday at the offices of
20th Century Fox, Gracie Films and Brooks were not immediately
retuirned.
</TEXT>
