<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 1550EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GuardianshipConference     07-23 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Guardianship Conference,0604</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bar Conference Recommends Sweeping Change In Gardianship Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RACINE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national conference sponsored by the
American Bar Association called Saturday for major changes in the
nation's guardianship system, including expanded legal rights and
representation for the old and disabled.
   Forty-four experts, including attorneys, psychiatrists, judges,
researchers and government officials, also cautioned that judges
and lawyers were often ``quantitatively and qualitatively
inadequate'' in performing their guardianship duties and
recommended greater awareness of flaws in the system.
   ABA officials attending the National Guardianship Symposium: A
Response to The Associated Press Inquiry said the meeting was a
result of growing concerns about the nation's guardianship system,
including the findings of the AP's 50-state investigation of abuses
in court-ordered guardianships.
   ``It's the perception of many professionals that the
guardianship system is not meeting the needs of some people and may
be abusing the rights of others, as demonstrated by the information
in the AP report,'' said Nancy Nevelowf Dubler, a commissioner with
that ABA's Commission on the Legal Problems of the Elderly.
   Last year's AP series found many of the 300,000 to 400,000
elderly under guardianship in this country are stripped of their
rights and placed under the power of a guardian without the same
court protections given those facing criminal charges.
   An AP review of 2,200 case files also found the courts often
failed to do their job monitoring guardianships, leaving elderly
wards prey to financial and physical abuse at the hands of their
guardians.
   The three-day conference issued 36 recommendations for change in
the system. Among them:
   _ Legal representation for all those facing guardianship. The
group said attorneys should represent the wishes of clients. The AP
investigation found lawyers often dismiss the rights of their
clients facing guardianship.
   _ The elimination of age, economic status, medical diagnosis or
``eccentricity'' as sole reasons for placing someone under
guardianship. While many state laws permit guardianships for
reasons of age alone, the conference stressed that guardianship be
used only when the person can no longer care of themselves.
   _ Greater efforts by judges, lawyers and court personnel to
understand the problems of the elderly. The courts were urged to
tailor proceedings for those with poor eyesight or hard of hearing.
   _ Attempts to find alternatives to guardianship in cases where
it does not serve the interests of the proposed ward. The AP study
found people are often placed under guardianship to assure payments
to nursing homes or limit liability to hospitals.
   David Wexler, a University of Arizona law professor and chairman
of the ABA's Commission on the Mentally Disabled said the
recommendations come at a time when the guardianship system is
coming under greater scrutiny.
   ``As the population ages and a larger number of people has
experience with this system it has to grow in importance,'' he said
   John Perry, commission director, said the recommendations would
go on to various ABA groups for review with hopes that state
legislatures and individual courts would amend laws and practices.
   ``It's one of the first volleys being fired in this issue,'' he
said.
   Since the AP's series last fall, some 20 states have either
passed or considered legislation to reform guardianship systems in
their courts.
   Rep. Claude Pepper, D-Fla., has drafted legislation setting
federal guardianship standards for the courts. Rep. Don Bonker,
D-Wash., also has drafted recommended standards for the system.
   The conference was sponsored by the ABA's Commission on the
Mentally Disabled and Commission on Legal Problems of the Elderly
and was hosted by the Johnson Foundation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880723-0125 </DOCNO>
