<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vatican-Lefebvre     07-23 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vatican-Lefebvre,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Traditionalists Forming Group Loyal To Rome</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of traditionalist priests and seminarians
have broken with renegade Archbishop Marcel Lefebvre and are
setting up their own organization loyal to the papacy, according to
a Roman Catholic magazine.
   In an interview with the monthly 30 Giorni, Abbe Joseph Bisig
said 16 priests and 20 seminarians have joined the group and ``many
others'' are expected.
   The interview, to appear in the magazine's August issue, was
released to the media Saturday.
   Bisig, a former official in Lefebvre's St. Pius X Fraternity in
Switzerland, said the new organization, called the Priestly
Fraternity of St. Peter, was being set up in Hauterive, Switzerland.
   Lefebvre, an 82-year-old Frenchman who heads an
ultra-traditionalist movement opposed to modernizing the Roman
Catholic Church, was excommunicated after he consecrated four
bishops without papal approval on June 30. The consecration led to
the first schism in the church in more than a century.
   The Vatican warned Lefebvre's followers that they also will be
excommunicated if they adhere to his movement. But Pope John Paul
II promised to meet their traditionalist needs, including wider use
of the 16th century Latin Mass, if they remained loyal to the
papacy.
   ``We want to be tied to the spiritual and liturgical tradition
in the church, thus with Peter,'' Bisig was quoted as saying. ``We
want to show our brothers that have created the rupture (with Rome)
that they can remain traditionalist Catholics within the church.''
   Bisig said he met with the pope and other Vatican officials in
Rome in early July to discuss the new traditionalist fraternity. He
said he was promised by Cardinal Joseph Ratzinger, the pope's
guardian of orthodoxy, that the group would receive official
Vatican recognition ``by September at the latest.''
   ``It is absolutely not our intention to fight with the St. Pius
X Fraternity,'' Bisig was quoted as saying. ``We are actually very
grateful for everything (Lefebvre) has done, apart from the schism.
He fought against progressivism and modernisn. That is also our
objective, but we want to do it within the church.''
</TEXT>
