<1ST_LINE>u i AM-NeWin-Profile 1stLd-Writethru a0528 07-23 0714</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ne Win-Profile, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0528,0731</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burma Leader Wielded Power For More Than a Quarter-Century</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to ADD that rioting cited as reason for
resignation and CLARIFY that advancing age, sted poor health
another reason. Pickup 4th graf pvs ``Born Shu...''; SUBS last graf
``He cited...'' to CONFORM</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Burma, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ne Win, a one-time military hero and
Burma's undisputed ruler for 26 years, relinquished his grip on
power in a country shaken by mounting political unrest and economic
decline.
   Citing anti-government rioting and advancing age, Ne Win
announced Saturday he was resigning as chairman of the country's
sole political party, the Burma Socialist Program Party.
   Ne Win, whose name means ``Brilliant as the Sun'' in Burmese,
called for a referendum on ending one-party rule that could shake
the very political foundations he established after seizing power
in a 1962 military coup.
   Born Shu Maung on May 14, 1911 in the central Burmese town of
Paungbe, he took the name Ne Win after entering revolutionary
politics in what was then a British colony.
   Ne Win worked briefly as a postal clerk after failing in medical
studies. He joined the anti-British movement and became one of
Burma's ``Thirty Comrades,'' who traveled secretly to Japan for
military training in the early days of World War II.
   Returning to Burma, Ne Win and his comrades fought first
alongside the Japanese against the British, but then turned against
their teachers after realizing that Japan would also colonize
rather than liberate the Burmese.
   Ne Win rose quickly in the military and became chief of staff of
the Burmese armed forces in 1949, the year after Burma gained
independence.
   He came to the political forefront in 1958 when the military
pushed aside an ineffective prime minister and established a
caretaker government in a country wracked by poverty and ethnic
division.
   As promised, elections were held in 1960. Nu, soon to become Ne
Win's archrival, won the post of prime minister. Ne Win, who had
the makings of a popular leader, staged a coup in 1962, jailed Nu
and vowed to lead his country on a neutralist, egalitarian and
moralistic ``Burmese Road to Socialism.''
   Once known as a playboy and gambler, Ne Win banned gambling,
closed nightclubs and preached strict, traditional morality. This
did not stop him from enjoying horse racing or from marrying six
times.
   He moved quickly toward socialism. Private businesses were
nationalized, generally with little or no compensation, and the
central government attempted to run everything from the vital rice
trade to light manufacturing.
   Foreign private investment ceased, and foreigners were carefully
screened before being allowed into the country. Some charged that
Burmese leaders, including Ne Win, could not shake a post-colonial
syndrome that included xenophobia.
   Ne Win became president under a constitution written in 1974.
   Although he retired from the military in 1972, Ne Win maintained
effective control of the capable, well-organized armed forces that
served as his chief instrument of control.
   When anti-government riots erupted from time to time, Ne Win
moved ruthlessly to suppress them. Thousands of dissenters were
jailed. Although most were later releaed, there have been
persistent allegations of human rights violations.
   Fearing assassination, Ne Win rarely appeared in public,
traveled under tight security and never gave a press conference. He
became a recluse and spent much of his time in a heavily-guarded
lakeside villa on the edge of Rangoon.
   About the only time Rangoon residents could catch a glimpse of
their leader was inside his heavily guarded limousine on the way to
play golf.
   He also kept potential rivals at bay, by firing or jailing
up-and-coming leaders and demanding loyalty from subordinates.
   Burmese say Ne Win is both a shrewd, calculating political
tactician and a personality given to sudden outbursts of anger.
   His moves were rarely foreshadowed.
   His resignation from the presidency in 1981 was unexpected, as
was Saturday's announcement that he would step down from his one
remaining post, the chairmanship of the party.
   He cited poor health on the first occasion and advancing age on
Saturday. There have been unconfirmed reports of heart, kidney and
stomach problems. But after 1981, Ne Win gave no indication that
declining health had lessened his grip on power.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880723-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 1611EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Tourism     07-23 0681</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Tourism,0701</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fewer Americans Willing To Pay The Price To See Italy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Travel Abroad, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American tourists grumble about prices in Italy even
as they pitch coins into the Trevi Fountain. The symbolic gesture
is supposed to guarantee a return to Rome, but that is something
fewer Americans can afford to do.
   ``We've been traveling for a month and this is the most
expensive place we've been,'' said Caroline Faris of Wilson, N.C.
``Paris and Nice were cheaper, and that's surprising.''
   Italian tour operators aren't surprised. They say Italy is
pricing itself out of the market with exorbitant rates and inferior
service. The government predicts that compared to last year, U.S.
tourism will drop by more than 6 percent, or 112,000 people.
   Tourism from other countries is on the rise, and students and
backpackers from the United States still jam the streets of
Florence and the ferries in the Venice lagoon. The drop-off is
among the big spenders.
   ``We are one of the most expensive countries in the world for
hotels and restaurants. And this comes with a very low level of
service quality,'' said Isabella di Montezemolo, a spokeswoman for
American Express Travel Services here.
   ``Our country is very rich in natural and historical beauty, but
people are getting a bit tired of the services,'' she said. ``They
feel they are being taken for a ride.''
   ``Our tourist services are 30 years old. They are too old, too
small and not competitive anymore,'' said Enzo Poli, the president
of a federation of 2,700 Italian travel agents and tour operators.
   Giovanni Colombo, the president of the Federation of Italian
Hotels, said that compared to last year, the number of foreign
tourists in Italian hotels has increased by 5 percent. Ms. di
Montezmolo cited a 47 percent increase this year in Japanese
tourism due to a favorable exchange rate.
   But industry officials are concerned about the drop in the
number of Americans, who traditionally are among the biggest
spenders.
   ``This year Americans won't be the big spenders and they will
shorten their vacations in Italy,'' said Franco Cesaretti of the
Aviatur travel agency in Rome.
   Franco Paloscia, spokesman for the Italian National Tourist
Office, said his government spent about $9.2 million over the past
two years to promote Italy's image.
   His office predicts Americans will account for 6 percent of
foreign tourism this year and at least 10 percent of the revenue.
In 1985, Americans made up about 7 percent of the tourists and 17
percent of the revenue.
   That was before the rise of Middle East terrorism in Europe and
the fallout from the Chernobyl nuclear plant accident in the Soviet
Union sent vacationing Americans elsewhere.
   The Italian tourism industry discounts the theory that recent
acts of terrorism in Europe, such as the killing of a U.S. diplomat
in Greece and an attack on a tourist ship there, are factors in the
declining number of U.S. tourists.
   ``Terrorism is not scaring American tourists anymore,'' said
Paloscia. ``Terrorism, pollution, strikes are problems which
tourists learn to live with.''
   Ms. di Montemezelo agreed, blaming instead the weak position of
the dollar.
   ``This is not connected to terrorism,'' she said. ``The decrease
is due mainly to the dollar. Bookings are done mainly in November,
and November was the lowest point reached by the dollar.''
   The dollar has rebounded from a value of 1,208 lire in November
to about 1,365 lire. But officials say that is not enough for
people to change their plans.
   ``Italy is extremely expensive, it is one of the most expensive
countries in the world,'' said Cesaretti of the Aviatur travel
agency. He said that in Rome, the average price of a night in a
first-class hotel is $184 to $220, while in Madrid it is $95 to
$110.
   An American Express spokeswoman in London, who asked not to be
identified, said a 14-day holiday in Spain at a three-star hotel
with breakfasts, some dinners and sightseeing tours would cost $965
while a comparable tour in Italy would cost $1,495.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
