<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson     07-23 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Leaves Atlanta, Says Convention Was `Tremendous Moment'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson headed home to Chicago
Saturday, leaving town in a decidedly more low-key manner than he
entered and maintaining that his failed presidential campaign made
history at the Democratic National Convention.
   The civil rights leader refused to speculate on whether he would
seek public office again, saying that his priority now is to work
for the Democratic ticket in the fall presidential race.
   ``My focus now is on the fall campaign,'' he told reporters as
he left a downtown Atlanta hotel. ``We'll be spending a lot of time
organizing for voter registration, issue interpretation, involving
people _ many for the first time _ and a big turnout for the fall
campaign.''
   Of his post-election plans, Jackson said, ``We'll have to
determine what will happen, based on the outcome of the campaign.
But we take this journey one phase at a time.''
   Jackson took members of his family, campaign staffers and
journalists who covered his bid for the Democratic presidential
nomination to Paschal's, a well-known, black-owned hotel and
restaurant for lunch.
   The entourage then headed for Fulton County Airport, west of
Atlanta, where a chartered jet took off shortly after 2 p.m.
   Jackson, dressed in cuffed blue jeans, sandals and a red, white
and blue shirt, appeared at ease, accepting well-wishers and posing
for photographers. A few reporters and photographers covered his
departure and about 10 people gathered at the airport to bid
Jackson farewell.
   The casual scene contrasted sharply with the thunderous entrance
to Atlanta made by Jackson one week earlier.
   A motorcade of buses brought the Jackson campaign to Atlanta
July 16, two days before the start of the Democratic convention. He
addressed thousands of cheering supporters in Piedmont Park,
asserting that Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, then assured of
the nomination, must give Jackson a stronger voice in the party.
   Dukakis, Jackson and vice presidential nominee Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen of Texas met on Monday and peace was made. Though Jackson's
name was placed in nomination at the convention, he later pledged
support for the Dukakis-Bentsen ticket.
   Jackson said Saturday his campaign made great gains in Atlanta.
   He said blacks and others previously outside the party
mainstream will have unprecedented involvement in the fall
campaign. And he noted that several Jackson platform positions were
adopted.
   ``We can leave Atlanta with a real sense of inspiration because
of the expansion of the Democratic Party, more inclusion,
involvement in the campaign at all levels, vertically and
horizontally. And also helping to determine the course, the
priorities _ being in the room where poilicy is debated and
priorities are set.
   ``This is a trmemendous moment for us,'' he said.
</TEXT>
