<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites Subs a0612 07-23 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites, Subs, a0612,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS to Charles sted Chales in 1st graf, Petzold sted
Rankin in 3rd graf of ist item. Corrects spelling of dinosaurs in
1st graf of 3rd item.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>STUART, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired naval architect Charles Petzold and
a ship he helped design 44 years ago will soon be neighbors.
   A Navy demolition team will send the U.S.S. Rankin to the sea
floor off the coast of Martin County on Sunday to serve as an
artificial reef. The site is just a few miles from Petzold's home.
   ``It's crazy. It really is crazy. I can't believe how that thing
is following me,'' Petzold said.
   Petzold, a Stuart resident for 10 years, designed the ship with
colleagues at Gibbs and Cox Naval Architects in 1944 and followed
its career through World War II, when he was a civilian in charge
of monitoring ship performance during battle.
   After the war, his decision to keep the ship in the Navy fleet
enabled the vessel to build up a military record that includes
service in the Korean conflict and during the Cuban missile crisis.
   ``Here in the twilight of my life, that baby doll is going to be
right out there,'' he said.
   To add to the coincidence, his father-in-law, William McDonald,
was the Rankin's first full-time captain.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 6-year-old boy has his own theory on
the extinction of dinosaurs. ``My theory is that God killed off all
the dinosaurs so there would be room for all the other animals,''
says Andrew Shuster.
   Andrew, of Fremont, Neb., shared his theory with millions of
television viewers during an appearance Friday on the ``Tonight
Show with Johnny Carson.''
   ``That's not a bad theory,'' Carson said. ``It's as good as any
other.''
   Andrew was invited to appear on the show after its producers
heard of his 35-minute lecture on dinosaurs to second-grade
students in Fremont.
   Carson, a native of Norfolk, Neb., asked Andrew if he knew
Carson hailed from the Cornhusker State ``about 150 miles'' from
Fremont.
   ``Everybody who knows I'm going here tells me that,'' Andrew
said, seemingly unimpressed.
   The young dinosaur expert said he normally is not allowed to
stay up late enough to watch the show, but was given special
permission when he found out he would be a guest.
   Andrew said he likes the Tyrannosaurus Rex best of all dinosaurs
``because he was the king of the reptiles. He ate meat. He was
29-feet long.''
</TEXT>
