<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Italy-F-16s     07-23 0140</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Italy-F-16s,0143</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>At Least 1,000 Protest Transfer of U.S. Planes to Italy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISOLA CAPO RIZZUTO, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 1,000 demonstrators
protested Saturday outside the airport where 72 U.S. F-16 fighter
planes are to be transferred from Spain, police said.
   About a dozen people were arrested on charges of fighting,
according to a police official speaking on condition of anonymity.
No injuries were reported.
   The demonstration in Isola Capo Rizzuto on Italy's southern
coast was sponsored by more than a dozen leftist, ecological and
peace groups. Pacifist organizations from Spain, Belgium and other
European countries also sent representatives.
   The Italian government agreed in June to accept the jets, now
based at Torrejon air base near Madrid. Washington wanted to keep
them in Spain, but after lengthy talks the Spanish government said
they must be withdrawn within three years.
</TEXT>
