<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PigChase 1stLd-Writethru a0518 07-23 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pig Chase, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0518,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Piglet Leads Police On Two-Hour Chase</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf to CORRECT time element to Thursday night</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pet piglet that led police on a three-hour
chase was finally nabbed by a farm agent who got down on the ground
and lured the animal with a handful of horse feed.
   ``It's easy _ you just have to be faster than the pig,'' said
Deputy Jack ``Hi-Ho'' Hrabovsky, a member of the Hillsborough
County Sheriff's Office Agricultural Unit.
   Blackie, an 8-month-old, 40-pound pig, spent the night behind
bars at the city's impoundment lot before being sent to the
sheriff's farm for ``wayward'' animals in Plant City.
   The pig's brush with the law began as owner David A. Brown
carried him along a city street late Thursday night. Officer Gary
Yost stopped to chat, and soon learned through a computer check
that Brown was wanted for violating probation on a charge of
driving under the influence of alcohol.
   As Brown was arrested, Blackie took off.
   For three hours, Yost and another Tampa officer pursued the
porker, at times catching a glimpse of the elusive swine in the
glare of police spotlights. About 2 a.m. Friday, they called
Hrabovsky.
   ``I was asleep when they called and asked if I could come catch
a pig,'' said Hrabovsky, who arrived to find police and the pig in
a standoff.
   ``I got down on the ground with him and took a handful of horse
feed and waited for him,'' he said.
   When the pig came to Hrabovsky, officers nabbed it.
   ``I tried to take Blackie with me, but the officers said they
had to take him so I just put him in the back seat of their car,''
Hrabovsky said. ``I guess they didn't know the procedure ... being
their first time and all that.''
   Brown remained in the Hillsborough County Jail late Friday, and
no hearing date or bail had been set.
   Meanwhile, Hrabovsky took Blackie to Plant City. The pig will be
auctioned off if Brown doesn't claim him in 40 days, but Hrabovsky
said he'd try to place Blackie with Brown's family.
   ``This is one gentle pig,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
