<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Unrest     07-23 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armenia Making Up for Time Lost in Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Businesses in Armenia tried to make up for lost
time Saturday after a crippling strike, but a walkout continues in
a disputed Armenian region of a neighboring republic, Soviet news
reports said.
   State-run television reported Saturday in its evening news
program ``Vremya'' that 54,000 businesses in the Armenian capital,
Yerevan, that normally stay closed on weekends had opened.
   The extra hours were aimed at catching up after a strike that
began July 4 and tapered off last week, the program said.
   But the broadcast said a strike continued in the
Nagorno-Karabakh region of Azerbaijan Saturday despite a televised
appeal by the local Communist Party chief for Armenians to return
to work.
   State-run Radio Moscow said the situation remains tense in
Stepanakert, capital of Nagorno-Karabakh, where residents have been
on strike since May 23 as they demand the incorporation of their
district into Armenia.
   On Monday the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, the nation's top
executive body, refused to alter the status of the district, which
has a predominantly Armenian population but no common borders with
the Armenian republic.
   In another development, the wife of Paruyr Ayrikyan, a jailed
Armenian activist the Presidium ordered expelled Wednesday, said
she had learned he was taken from Yerevan to Moscow. Lena Ayrikyan,
in a telephone interview, said it was not clear whether her husband
would be sent out of the Soviet Union via Moscow.
   A KGB agent reported the activist's transfer in a meeting Friday
with a sister of Ayrikyan, Mrs. Ayrikyan said.
   Ayrikyan, a leader of an Armenian nationalist group, was
arrested March 25 on a charge of defaming the state and imprisoned
in Yerevan. In ordering him exiled, the Presidium stripped Ayrikyan
of his Soviet citizenship and pardoned him.
   The U.S. Embassy has said Soviet officials have contacted them
about resettling Ayrikyan in the United States, where he has
relatives. Mrs. Ayrikyan said she had not been allowed to speak to
her husband and didn't know whether he might be headed for the
United States.
   The government newspaper Izvestia claimed Saturday that Ayrikyan
appealed to the Presidium June 1 to drop the criminal charges
against him and allow him to emigrate to the West. It accused
Ayrikyan of advocating more serious changes than annexing
Nagorno-Karabakh to Armenia.
   On Wednesday, Armenian activists called for a resumption of the
general work stoppage to protest the Presidium's rejection of their
annexation demand. But Yerevan residents and the state-run media
have indicated people were generally ignoring the strike call.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
