<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel     07-23 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Put Down Protest and Stand by as Jews Worship in Jerusalem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Jews gathered at the Wailing Wall
Saturday to pray amid tight security after Palestinians battled
police in Jerusalem.
   Police fired rubber bullets and arrested 14 Palestinians during
clashes in which one Israeli and a Palestinian were injured,
according to broadcast reports. They said police used tear gas to
break up an anti-Arab demonstration by Jewish militants.
   The fighting came as Jews and Moslems were beginning religious
celebrations this weekend centering on the same site in Jerusalem's
walled Old City.
   Such skirmishes have made this disputed city a part of the
seven-month-old Palestinian uprising against Israeli rule in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. The Israelis seized control of
Arab east Jerusalem, the West Bank and Gaza Strip in the 1967
Middle East War.
   Israeli television reported that many rabbis throughout the
country urged worshipers to attend prayer services at the Wailing
Wall and not be frightened away by Palestinian violence.
   Hundreds of riot police patrolled east Jerusalem as Jews began
observing Tisha B`Av, which marks the destruction of the Holy
Temple by the Romans 2,000 years ago.
   Services were conducted at the Wailing Wall, a retaining wall of
the Temple Mount and the only remnant of the ancient Jewish temple.
   Later this weekend Moslems begin celebrating the four-day Eid
al-Adha festival that commemorates the story of Abraham's planned
sacrifice of his son on the Temple Mount, which they call Haram
al-Sharif. Abraham instead sacrificed a sheep.
   With its importance to both faiths, the Temple Mount area has
become one of the flashpoints of the Israeli-Arab conflict.
   Some people who have prayed at the Wailing Wall in previous
years said there were fewer worshipers this year.
   Debbie Albert, a tourist from Philadelphia, said she would not
``let a little rock-throwing keep me from the holiest place in
Judaism. I am here because if we don't come, they'll win.''
   Israel radio said a Palestinian and an Israeli suffered head
injuries during a battle involving Arabs, police and Jewish
students from a seminary in the Old City's Moslem quarter.
   It said the violence began after a memorial procession attended
by hundreds of Palestinians for 15-year-old Nidal Fuad Rabadi who
was fatally shot Tuesday on the northern outskirts of Jerusalem.
   Fighting spread to the Damascus Gate, one of the main entrances
to the Old City. Police ordered shopkeepers there to close stores
and fired tear gas to disperse a large crowd of Arabs stocking up
for the Moslem holiday.
   Hundreds of Arabs and tourists rushed out of the area to escape
the gas.
   Israel television reported police also used tear gas to disperse
demonstrators belonging to the militantly anti-Arab Kach movement,
headed by U.S.-born Rabbi Meir Kahane.
   According to U.N. figures, 231 Palestinians and four Israelis
have been killed since the uprising began Dec. 8.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
