<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Democrats-Text     07-23 0873</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democrats-Text,850</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of the Democratic response to
President Reagan's weekly radio address, given this week by Rep.
Beryl Anthony of Arkansas:
   Good afternoon. This is Congressman Beryl Anthony, Jr., from the
Fourth Congressional District in Arkansas.
   As chairman of the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee,
I'd like to visit with you about the renewed spirit within the
Democratic party. As Democrats leave Atlanta where we held our
national convention this week and scatter from one corner of our
nation to the other, the enthusiasm for the Democratic party is
spreading like wildfire across the prairie.
   It's a spirit we haven't felt since John Kennedy and Lyndon
Johnson filled us with hope and provided opportunities to all
working men and women. In 1988, we have another Massachusetts-Texas
team just as dedicated and just as capable of getting the country
back on the right track.
   In Atlanta, we nominated a presidential ticket of Massachusetts
Governor Michael Dukakis and Senator Lloyd Bentsen of Texas. Today,
the Dukakis-Bentsen team will carry its message of hope and
opportunity to the valley of Central California, and then, move on
to the plains of North Dakota.
   In Atlanta, Democrats recaptured a sense of party unity that has
been missing for too long, and while we celebrated solidarity, we
also debated.
   Democrats in 1988 can debate without becoming divided for a
simple reason _ we share a deep commitment to fulfilling the needs
and challenges of all Americans, not just our closest friends.
   After eight years of a Republican administration, fueled by
selfish and sometimes unlawful motives, the American people are
looking for a return to the basic values of common respect,
compassion, and concern for all. And as Michael Dukakis promised,
we are determined to forge a new era of greatness.
   This fall, the Republicans will brag about low unemployment, low
inflation and sustained growth. But you and I know, we've paid a
big price for their bragging rights. Ohio and Michigan have paid
dearly with plant shutdowns. In our heartland, it's a daily
struggle for farmers to keep their farms. And if you brag about
sustained growth in Oklahoma and Louisiana, the folks there would
laugh, or maybe cry.
   George Bush was right eight years ago when he called Ronald
Reagan's policies ``voodoo economics.'' He seems to have forgotten
that, and forgotten the needs of the working men and women of this
country. Soon, Mr. Bush may begin to feel like a voodoo doll, when
he is stuck with explaining his administration's legacy of debts
and deficits.
   Voters who supported Reagan and Bush are now disillusioned
because this administration couldn't keep its promises. George Bush
will pay the price as many of these supporters return home where
they belong _ to the Democratic party. We're already hearing from
these folks. From Desha County, Arkansas, a farmer friend called me
recently.
   He said: ``Beryl, I'm sorry I voted for Reagan and Bush. I'll do
it again. Now, I need your help.'' My reply was simple: ``There's
no need to apologize. Just remember how empty those promises were
and that George Bush will try to hoodwink the public again.''
   Throughout most of the 1980s, Democrats in the Congress were the
safety net for the American people. We fought to protect your basic
rights. It was difficult at times, but our efforts have paid off.
It was Democrats in Congress who crusaded far and fast for
catastrophic health insurance.
   It was Democrats in Congress who initiated in fast trade
legislation to protect American jobs for opening more world
markets. It was Democrats who said it's only fair and decent to
give workers 60 days notice when they lose their jobs. And
Democrats even cooperated with the President in strengthening our
national defense.
   But Reagan and Bush took it too far to the point where crime
corruption and greed set in. Clearly, the priorities of the last
eight years served the interest of ambitious Reagan appointees and
the elite of our society.
   This administration favors missile systems over school systems
and supports payments to international drug-traffickers, but
doesn't fund programs to stop drugs at our borders. I think you'll
agree, it's time to straighten out our priorities.
   National security is no longer simply a debate over missiles and
troops _ it's a concern for the American family. It's a renewal of
the dream that our children will have greater opportunities. Every
American deserves the right to share the same hopes and dreams _
the hope that all of our children will receive quality education,
that adequate health is available for all, that all our children
will be able to afford to buy a house, and that all our children's
children will have a better quality of life.
   These hopes will remain just dreams if you, my fellow Americans,
don't get involved in the political process. The 1988 election will
be one of the most important ones in our lifetime. It's the
Democratic commitment to invest in our most precious natural
resource _ the American people _ that will propel this nation into
the next century.
   Don't ever forget _ your vote is important. In November, vote
Democratic. Our future depends on it. Thank you for listening.
</TEXT>
