<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BigBend-Parkland     07-23 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Big Bend-Parkland,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Land Purchase Nearly Doubles State Parkland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas' largest parkland acquisition in
history, the massive Big Bend Ranch, is putting the state Parks and
Wildlife Department into high gear. The $8.8 million purchase
nearly doubles the state parks system.
   ``It's a bargain,'' said Chuck Nash, chairman of the state Parks
and Wildlife Commission. ``This great property will provide a new
and exciting opportunity for the citizens of Texas to enjoy one of
the state's wildest and most beautiful places.''
   The purchase of the 215,000-acre ranch in Brewster and Presidio
counties in western Texas ends a 15-year struggle by former state
Land Commissioner Bob Armstrong to acquire the property.
   The parks system now has about 220,000 acres of land.
   ``It's really a unique area and we plan to keep it that way,''
said Armstrong, now a commission member. ``It's unreal how many
outstanding geological features the ranch has.''
   The ranch includes the Solitario, an extinct volcano with an
8-mile diameter, and is known to provide habitats for at least 11
endangered species of plants and animals.
   The purchase, approved by the commission Thursday, is expected
to be completed within three weeks. Title to the ranch is held by
Humble Oil and Gas Co., owned by Robert O. Anderson of New Mexico
and Walter Mischer of Houston.
   As land commissioner in the late 1970s, Armstrong negotiated a
trade of state lands for the ranch. But the swap was opposed by
several legislators and never completed.
   Armstrong described the ranch as one of the Southwest's most
significant natural resources. Covering about 336 square miles, it
is about one-third the size of nearby Big Bend National Park. The
ranch is about 350 miles southeast of El Paso.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
