<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Police     07-23 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Police,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Three Drunk Policemen Disrupt Mass</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three drunk policemen entered a church
linked to the outlawed Solidarity union and disrupted a Mass before
being evicted by worshipers, a Solidarity spokeswoman said Saturday.
   A scuffle broke out during the service Friday night at St.
Brygida's Church in Gdansk, said Joanna Wojciechowicz, speaking
from her home in the Baltic port city.
   She said one officer threw a knife and another used his
truncheon to ward off angry worshipers but the policemen, all in
uniform, were subdued and removed from the building.
   Police summoned by the parish priest, the Rev. Henryk Jankowski,
later located the three officers and detained them, according to
the spokeswoman.
   A duty officer at Gdansk police headquarters declined to comment
about the incident.
   The church is a few blocks from the Lenin shipyard where
Solidarity was founded in the fall of 1980 to become the only free
union federation in the Soviet bloc. Solidarity was suspended by
the communist government in December 1981 and subsequently
outlawed. There have been frequent pro-Solidarity demonstrations at
the church.
