<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 1838EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BloodSuit     07-23 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Blood Suit,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Cheered by Reinstatement of Lawsuit over Products Derived from
His Blood</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A soft-drink distributor who maintains he should
get some of the profits from commercial products derived from his
blood and body tissues says he is pleased by a court ruling that
may lead to that.
   ``To me, this (ruling) is the ultimate vindication of the
rightness of what we're trying to do,'' John Moore said Friday
after learning the California 2nd District Court of Appeals
reinstated his suit against the University of California-Los
Angeles.
   Moore, 43, claims Dr. David Golde of UCLA never informed him of
the value of his blood while using it to develop a product that
scientists say offers considerable hope for treating cancer and
AIDS.
   His attorney in Los Angeles, Jonathan Zackey, said the ruling
was unprecedented.
   ``This is the first time an appellate court has ruled that a
patient has an interest in the unique properties of his genetic
material and that commercial exploitation without the patient's
consent entitles the patient to sue for damages,'' Zackey said.
   Private research companies paid UCLA $500,000 for exclusive
access to Moore's cells, Zackey said. Golde received benefits worth
about $1.5 million, and trade sources have indicated the full line
of treatments that could be developed from the cells might be worth
more than $3 billion, the lawyer added.
   An attorney for UCLA, Allen Wagner, said he might seek
reconsideration of the ruling or seek an appeal.
   Twelve years ago, Moore learned he had a rare blood disease
called hairy-cell leukemia, and in a relatively common treatment,
Golde removed his spleen.
   From that organ, Golde discovered Moore's blood possessed a
previously unknown capacity for fighting disease, and for the next
seven years he had the Seattle man frequently return to Los Angeles
to draw more blood.
   Moore said he never was told that researchers used his blood and
tissues to patent what they called the ``Mo-cell.''
   The product was developed by copying a unique characteristic
found in Moore's cells, a property that boosts production of
certain white blood cells which, in turn, stimulate the body's
first line of defense against some diseases.
   When patients consent to the removal of organs, they also
consent to disposal of the organs, including their use in research,
so Moore ``had abandoned any interests in the therapeutically
removed tissue,'' Wagner said.
   Since his spleen was removed, Moore has undergone no further
treatment and says the disease appears to be in remission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880723-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 1842EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-VietnamMines     07-23 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam Mines,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vets Returning to Vietnam to Clear Mine Fields</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spurred by reports that land mines are maiming and
killing Vietnamese children, five veterans intend to return to
Southeast Asia to help clear mine fields they laid 20 years ago.
   ``I don't consider myself a Rambo type, and I don't consider
myself a Jane Fonda,'' former Cpl. Frank Noe said Saturday. ``I did
what I had to do, what I was told to do, during the war.
   ``And I'm doing what I feel is right to do now.''
   Noe, a 39-year-old firefighter in Stoughton, Mass., and four
fellow veterans of the 11th Marine Combat Engineering Battalion
have received the Vietnamese government's approval for a two-week
humanitarian mission in January.
   They plan to point out the perimeters of the fields they laid,
provide technical expertise on mines and, if necessary, comb the
jungle with metal detectors and probe the dirt with knives.
   Noe said they realize their actions may be dangerous and have
asked the Marine Corps to reduce the risk by turning over maps of
the fields.
   But a Marine Corps spokesman said the maps either never reached
the Pentagon or were tossed out long ago.
   ``If we kept everything back that far, this city would be buried
under paper,'' said Lt. Col. Frederick C. Peck of the Marine Corps
public affairs office in Washington.
   If that means the veterans have to rely on memories two decades
old, so be it, said former Lance Cpl. Nathaniel Genna, 40, of
Boston.
   ``I won't remember all the fields, but I'll remember the ones I
worked on,'' Genna said. ``You'd be surprised how well you recall
when you had ears on the back of your head and eyes on your rear
end.''
   Plans for the trip emerged from a September 1987 reunion in
Chicago, where Genna showed his companions a newspaper article in
which the Vietnamese government estimated 3,000 people _ many of
them children _ died from grenades, bombs and land mines between
1975 and 1985.
   Former Sgt. Eugene T. Spanos of Rosemont, Ill., who organized
the reunion, said the news hit him hard.
   ``I turned to one former battalion commander and said, `Sir, did
you take the mine fields out?,' and he said, `No.'
   ``So I turned to the other battalion commander who relieved him
and I said, `Did you?' And he said, `No.' So I said, `My God, all
these years have gone by, and we're still killing people over
there,'' recalled Spanos.
   After the reunion, Spanos, 40, contacted the Vietnamese mission
to the United Nations, wrote to other veterans and found an
anonymous donor willing to support the mine-clearing expedition,
which the veterans estimate will cost $30,000.
   Besides Spanos, Noe and Genna, the veterans who have volunteered
are William Johnson of Manchester, Conn., and Michael Wallace of
Langdon, Kan. All five served in Vietnam between 1967 and 1970.
   The group's translator and guide will be retired Marine Lt. Col.
Robert J. Dalton, who went to Hanoi last fall to help plan the
mission.
   ``I'm supporting them because it's a humanitarian effort I agree
with,'' Dalton said. ``I see this as an act of a reconciliation
between two governments that have been at odds for a long time _
and who better to do it than the young men who were sent to fight
the war in the first place.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880723-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 1846EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-NorthernIreland 4thLd-Writethru   07-23 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northern Ireland, 4th Ld-Writethru,a0618,0705</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Kills Family Headed Home From Vacation; IRA Says It Was a
Mistake</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS two grafs for 16th pvs, Police described ... with police
correcting surviving daughter's age to 19 sted 18 and updating with
family statement. Pickup 17th graf pvs, British security ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEWRY, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb blew up Saturday on a road
near the Irish border and killed three members of a family headed
home after a vacation in the United States, police said.
   The outlawed Irish Republican Army, fighting to end British rule
in Northern Ireland, admitted it was their bomb but that it
detonated prematurely and was meant for British soldiers, not
civilians.
   The blast blew a crater in the road and left bodies and luggage
scattered on the main road between Dublin and Belfast, witnesses
said.
   Killed in the explosion were Robert James Hanna and Maureen
Patricia Hanna, both 44, and their son David, 6.
   They were driving to their home in Hillsborough, 12 miles south
of Belfast, when the explosion occurred at about 10 a.m. near
Newry, about a mile from the Irish border, police said. It was not
immediately known where they vacationed in the United States.
   Three people in nearby cars were slightly injured.
   The explosion brought to 21 the number of people killed in
explosions in Northern Ireland this year, police said.
   The IRA is fighting to drive the British out of the
predominantly Protestant province and unite it with the Roman
Catholic Irish Republic.
   The IRA issued conflicting statements explaining the bombing.
   In a statement issued to journalists in Northern Ireland, the
South Armagh Brigade of the IRA said the Hannas were the
``unfortunate victims of mistaken identity.'' It said the attack
was a carefully planned military operation that ended in ``tragic
and unfortunate circumstances.''
   A later IRA statement said British scanning devices may have set
off the device, which was planned for British soldiers.
   ``This bomb which was to be detonated by remote control exploded
prematurely, tragically killing three civilians,'' it said.
   ``We are in a position to state that all volunteers in command
of the explosives did not detonate the device. Without shirking
responsibility for this tragedy, we are investigating the
possibility that the explosion could have occurred as a result of
British forces who were in the vicinity using electronic scanning
devices,'' the IRA said.
   Officials speculated the IRA mistook the family's jeep for a
Land Rover used by British security forces. Security forces
regularly patrol the area.
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary denounced the IRA statement.
   Police described Hanna as a company director. They said the
couple had a 17-year-old son and an 19-year-old daughter who were
not traveling with them.
   The Hanna family, in a statement later Saturday, said they were
``stunned and hurt'' and wished to mourn in private.
   British security forces sealed off the area.
   ``When I came out from getting petrol, I saw parts of bodies
lying all over the road,'' a witness said. ``A (jeep) was blown
into a field and two other cars were damaged,'' another witness
said.
   ``From what I could see there were a couple of cars lying in the
crater. There was debris everywhere,'' said another witness. All
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   A nearby abandoned house was demolished in the explosion.
   The blast occurred near the spot where a Northern Ireland judge
and his wife were killed by an IRA bomb 15 months ago. Three years
ago, four Royal Ulster Constabulary officers were killed by a bomb
at almost the same spot.
   Jim Nicholson, a former legislator in the Protestant Unionist
Party, said the IRA ``would react with another sickening apology
for the deaths of three innocent people.''
   On July 8, the IRA apologized for killing two civilians, who
died along with a British soldier and an IRA guerrilla during two
bombings and two mortar attacks. An IRA statement said the
operation went ``tragically wrong.''
   Gordon Mawhinney of the non-sectarian Alliance Party described
the bombers Saturday as savages and said they could only be
defeated ``if the community act against terrorism.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
