<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-23 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Locally Heavy Rain Over Parts Of East Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rain fell along parts of the East Coast on Saturday, with
rain also scattered across the northern Plains and Midwest, and
temperatures cooled to record lows over the south-central states.
   Showers and thunderstorms, some producing locally heavy rain,
were scattered ahead of a stationary front from Florida through the
lower and middle Atlantic Coast states to Maryland.
   Thunderstorms dumped heavy rain on eastern North Carolina during
the morning, including more than 2 inches at Wilmington, where the
ground was already saturated from nearly 7 inches that caused
street flooding on Friday.
   Showers and thunderstorms also were scattered over West
Virginia, Ohio, Lower Michigan and parts of western Pennsylvania.
Toledo, Ohio, got 1-inch diameter hail.
   Isolated thunderstorms developed ahead of a cold front over
northeastern South Dakota.
   Isolated thunderstorms also broke out over northeastern New
Mexico, western Kansas, the Front Range of the Rockies and the
Texas Panhandle.
   Record lows Saturday were 63 at Monroe, La., and 61 at Paducah,
Ky. Calico Rock, Ark., tied its record low of 55 and San Antonio,
Texas, tied its record of 68.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 62
degrees at Crescent City, Calif., to 106 at Twentynine Palms,
Calif. Saturday morning's low was 36 at Gunnison, Colo.
   For Sunday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from Florida and the eastern Gulf Coast region through the Atlantic
Coast states to Maine. Scattered showers and thunderstorms also
were forecast ahead of a cold front over northwestern Wisconsin,
western Iowa, southeastern Nebraska and northwestern Missouri, and
over eastern Colorado.
   Highs only in the 50s and 60s were predicted across Maine; in
the 70s over the rest of New England and New York state; in the 70s
and 80s over sections of the California coast and western
Washington state; in the 80s from the northern Plains and eastern
Colorado through the upper Mississippi Valley and the Great Lakes
states to the middle Atlantic Coast states and the Carolinas; from
100 to 110 in the desert Southwest and the valleys of California;
and in the 90s in most of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
