<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 1929EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LoogooteeBomb 2ndLd-Writethru a0557 07-23 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Loogootee Bomb, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0557,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Damages Entrance To Loogootee High School</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs the last 3 grafs with 9 grafs to expand on other bombs,
update with more comment from police chief.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOOGOOTEE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police were looking Saturday for a
cream-colored pickup truck that may be linked to an explosion that
damaged the east entrance to Loogootee High School.
   The Friday night blast created enough force to destroy a metal
door and hurl pieces of the bomb up to 100 yards away, police said.
No injuries were reported in the 9:45 p.m. explosion, which was
heard over the entire town.
   Damage was estimated by police at $500.
   An older model pickup truck, which had a darker-colored stripe
along the side, was seen near the school at the time of the
explosion, state police dispatcher Richard Weintraut said.
   ``We're waiting on an Indiana State Police bomb investigator to
come up this morning for further investigation,'' said Loogootee
Chief of Police John Hunt.
   On July 5, 13 improperly wired time bombs were found in Salem,
about 50 miles east of Loogootee in southern Indiana. There was no
evidence the two incidents were related, Hunt said.
   The Salem incident involved dynamite improperly wired to timed
fuses. None of those bombs exploded. The Loogootee bomb was a fused
pipe bomb that was lit by someone shortly before it went off, Hunt
said.
   The only similarities were that neither bomber knew how to wire
a bomb correctly, Hunt said.
   ``Whoever made these bombs here didn't know what they were
doing,'' he said. ``The state investigator said whoever made the
bomb was real lucky it didn't explode while they were making it.''
   Earlier this month, police discovered an unfinished pipe bomb in
the center of an intersection about a block from the school.
   ``It looked like someone had made it and it fell out of a
vehicle or something,'' Hunt said. ``It looked like someone had
been experimenting, trying to make something like a homemade bomb,
but didn't get it finished. It didn't have any powder, wasn't
fused.''
   ``The school teachers are starting to get worried,'' Hunt said.
``They don't know if they want to go back to school or not.''
   Police talked to several teachers and neighbors Saturday, but
none reported receiving any threats, he said.
   Said one local officer who spoke on condition he not be
identified: ``What we are afraid of is that whoever is doing this
is practicing and the bombs might get bigger and bigger. We hope it
stops right now before someone gets hurt.''
</TEXT>
