<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-Cardinal     07-23 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Cardinal,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cardinal Calls For Regional Peace Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CEBU, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the country's two Roman Catholic
cardinals called Saturday for peace negotiations at the regional
level to end the 19-year-old communist insurgency.
   Cardinal Ricardo Vidal of Cebu released a statement urging the
government and rebels to ``sit down and face each other once more.''
   He added ``this cannot be done if others stand up and fight. A
dialogue demands an atmosphere of sincerity and of course safety.
Firing has to cease in the meantime.''
   In proposing regional talks, the cardinal said: ``Such dialogues
are better held within a locality. The more familiar the
personalities involved, the better the issues are identified and
easier settled.''
   President Corazon Aquino's government reached a two-month
cease-fire agreement with the rebels in December 1986 and tried to
negotiate a political solution.
   But the talks broke down in January and fighting resumed after
the end of the cease-fire period the following month. Attempts to
revive the talks have failed.
   In the fighting, communist guerillas attacked a power station in
a southern town and raided a hospital in the northern Philippines,
military and news reports said Saturday. They gave these accounts:
   About 40 rebels of the New People's Army attacked the power
station in the town of Tudela Thursday night with rifle fire,
destroying four transformers and 45 voltage regulators. Another
power station had been attacked Wednesday and the two assaults
blacked out seven towns in Misamis Occidental province.
   In northern Cagayan province some 100 rebels raided a hospital
in the town of Tuao a week ago and fled with the medical supplies.
   No casualties were reported in the attacks.
   An estimated 3,000 members of anti-communist groups held a
``prayer rally'' Saturday in a downtown Manila park. The rally was
organized by the ``Philippines, Return to God'' movement that said
the action was to ``awaken the people to the evils and godlessness
of communism.''
</TEXT>
