<HEAD>River Pollution Kills Thousands of Fish</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chemical wastes in the Szamos River
that flows into Hungary from Romania have moved into the Tisza
River, killing thousands of fish, the Magyar Nemzet newspaper
reported Saturday.
   It quoted Lajos Szlavik, a water conservation director, as
saying Romanian officials said they were not aware of any pollution
in the Szamos River on their side of the border but they agreed to
participate in tests.
   Szlavik told the newspaper a net had been placed to keep the
dead fish from flowing downstream and about 3,300 pounds of fish
have been collected.
   Hungarian tests determined that the water was polluted with
chemicals and oxygen in the river had fallen below critical levels,
according to Szlavik.
