<DOCNO> AP880723-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 2055EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ContraArms     07-23 0597</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contra Arms,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Gives Mercenary For Contras One-Day Sentence, $50 Fine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American mercenary received one
day's probation and a $50 fine after pleading guilty to violating
the federal Neutrality Act by plotting to send civilian fighters to
help the Contras.
   U.S. District Judge Norman Roettger refused to comment on the
sentence he gave on Friday to Joe Sam Adams, one of seven men
indicted earlier this month for activities aiding the Nicaraguan
rebels, known as Contras.
   ``If Roettger gave a sentence like that, what does it tell
you?'' said Rick Goldman, one of Adams' attorneys. ``Obviously, the
sentence reflects the judge's feelings about the indictment.''
   The Neutrality Act prohibits American citizens from trying to
overthrow a nation ``at peace'' with the United States.
   But attorneys for the defendants scoffed at the notion that the
United States is at peace with the Sandinista regime in Nicaragua.
   The original federal inquiry that started about two years ago in
Florida helped expose the Iran-Contra affair, but the seven
indicted this month were not major players in the underground
Contra aid network.
   Attorneys for the defendants have said their clients were
singled out to silence those in the network who had become critics
of the administration, while those who gave the orders were not
prosecuted.
   A spokesman for the Christic Institute _ which is appealing a
$24 million civil lawsuit relating to Contra aid efforts, alleged
guns-for-drugs deals and other covert activities _ said the light
punishment for Adams was no big surprise.
   ``This conforms with our experience that one can violate the law
to aid the Contras in the southern district of Florida without fear
of punishment,'' Christic spokesman Peter Dykstra said Saturday.
``We are upset but our anger lies more with the impunity that's
apparently afforded to those in Washington who gave the orders to
violate the law. That's why we intend to bring our case back
through the appeals process.''
   Adams pleaded guilty to the main charge of the indictment _ that
the defendants conspired to overthrow a foreign government while on
U.S. soil. Adams could have faced three years in prison.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Jeffrey Feldman said, ``I indicated to
the judge that I thought the sentence was fair.''
   Before appearing in Roettger's court, Adams pleaded innocent
before U.S. Magistrate Lurana Snow. He was released on $25,000 bond.
   Minutes later, Adams changed his plea to guilty and he and his
lawyers stood before Roettger for sentencing.
   Adams, 38, of St. Louis, is a marksman and professional weight
lifter as well as a former bodyguard for Adolfo Calero, a Contra
leader. He has said that he fought with the Contras in Nicaragua to
overthrow the country's leftist Sandinista government.
   ``I think certainly the judge sees this case for what it is, and
I think he recognizes how inappropriate the charges are,'' said
John Mattes, an assistant federal public defender who has
criticized the July 13 indictment for going after the ``foot
soldiers rather than the generals.''
   Five men named in the indictment have pleaded innocent.
   ``The sentence is absolutely phenomenal,'' said Doug Jones, the
lawyer for Tom Posey, an Alabama businessman named in the
indictment. ``I am sure that Mr. Adams and his attorneys are very
pleased.''
   One of the accused, mercenary-turned-whistle-blower Jack
Terrell, is expected to plead on Monday.
   Others indicted were Mario Calero, brother of Adolfo Calero;
Jose Coutin, a Miami Cuban and former Civilian Materiel Assistance
liaison here; Alex Martinez, a Cuban-American stockbroker; and Maco
Stewart, a former assistant state attorney general and state
representative in Texas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
