<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Gulf-Ball 1stLd-Writethru   07-23 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Ball, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0556,0615</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Secretary Visits Gulf, Letter To Vincennes Found</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4 grafs for grafs 6-8 pvs to UPDATE with letter to
Vincennes found, spokesman saying it would be delivered to ship
Sunday; pickup 9th pvs, The Vincennes ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The secretary of the U.S. Navy, William
Ball III, met Saturday with local defense officials as he wrapped
up a two-day visit to the Persian Gulf that was conducted under
extraordinarily tight security.
   An aide to Ball said his visit was a general overseas tour to
``see the troops.'' It was Ball's first trip to the area since
becoming Navy secretary this year, and it was not announced by the
Pentagon in advance.
   During the visit, Ball boarded the flagship Coronado, the
destroyer John Hancock and the mine sweeper Conquest _ three of the
approximately 16 American warships now in the gulf.
   The security included a bulletproof car.
   All Americans in the region have been cautioned about possible
terrorist acts in the aftermath of the July 3 downing of an Iranian
jetliner by the U.S. missile cruiser Vincennes. All 290 aboard the
plane were killed.
   U.S. officials meanwhile said they recovered a letter, bearing
10,000 signatures and expressing support for the Vincennes' captain
and crew, that was supposed to have been delivered to the warship
two days ago.
   The signature campaign was organized last weekend in San Diego,
the Vincennes' home port, by Rep. Bill Lowrey, R-Calif.
   The letter, which reportedly weighs about 50 pounds and is 1,000
feet long, had been mishandled on its way to the gulf through an
express delivery service, said Karl Higgins, a Lowrey aide.
Higgins, in a telephone interview from his home in San Diego, said
the letter was found in a London cargo terminal Saturday and was
shipped to Bahrain.
   Higgins said the letter would be delivered to the ship Sunday.
   The Vincennes sailed out of the gulf three days ago and is in
the Arabian Sea, according to a spokesman at U.S. Central Command
headquarters in Tampa, Fla.
   Although there has been speculation that the 9,600-ton cruiser
might be withdrawn from the region as a gesture toward reducing
tensions, military sources, who asked not to be identified, said
they had seen nothing to indicate the ship would leave before its
scheduled departure in late August.
   Ball's visit had been planned before Iran's announced acceptance
last week of a U.N. cease-fire plan for ending the 8-year-old war
with Iraq, according to U.S. officials, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Ball, accompanied by U.S. Ambassador Sam H. Zakhem and Rear Adm.
Anthony Less, commander of the Joint Task Force Middle East, met
with Bahrain's defense minister, Sheik Khalifa Bin Ahmed al Khalifa.
   In keeping with the strict security, officials refused to
disclose the Navy secretary's destination after the gulf, other
than to say it was ``not in this area.''
   The United States is expected to reduce its naval force in the
Persian Gulf if the cease-fire is implemented. However, U.S.
officials here and at the Pentagon say it is too soon to speculate
on a timetable for a cutback.
   Naval sources, asking not to be further identified, said that
neither Ball's visit nor the departure on Saturday of two U.S.
warships was related to any reduction in force.
   The destroyer O'Brien and the missile frigate John H. Sides left
the port of Manama and headed toward the Strait of Hormuz toward
home after completing their three-month duty tours.
   The sources said both will be replaced by other warships now en
route.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
