<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pakistan-India     07-23 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan-India,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zia Accuses India of Provoking Ethnic Disturbances</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Zia ul-Haq on Saturday
accused India of provoking ethnic violence in Pakistan's southern
province of Sind.
   ``We have fundamental proof, evidence to show to our friends in
India, that they have been interferring in Sind by trying to
isolate Sind from the rest of Pakistan,'' Zia said in a statement.
He did not elaborate.
   More than 40 people have been killed in ethnic fighting in Sind
during the past two months.
   In the latest incident, on July 17, the mayor of Hyderabad was
wounded in an assassination attempt and a Hyderabad city councilman
was killed in the attack. The shootings were followed by riots in
which seven people were killed.
   Much of the violence has involved Moslem immigrants who fled to
Pakistan from predominantly Hindu India in 1947 after the Indian
subcontinent received independence from Britain and was partitioned
into India and Pakistan.
   The immigrants are demanding recognition as a fifth ethnic group.
   Pakistan is ethnically divided into four major groups: Pathans
in the northwest, Punjabis in the eastern province of Punjab,
Baluchis in the western province of Baluchistan and Sindhis in Sind.
   Zia noted the immigrants have been in Pakistan more than 40
years and said: ``Why is it that now they have come all of a sudden
as a group demanding its rights? Because it has been provoked as
such, as a parochial element in order to advance political
reasons.''
   Zia denied Indian allegations that Pakistan is adding to the
violence in India's northern Punjab province. India claims Pakistan
is aiding militant Sikhs who are demanding an independent homeland
in that province bordering Pakistan.
   Sikhism is an offshoot of the Hindu religion. Pakistan is mainly
Moslem and Zia in mid-June invoked Islamic law, saying it took
precedence over existing legislation, and that Pakistan must become
an Islamic nation.
   He said Saturday, ``Anyone who considers that this is going to
be a secular state, or a state in which you can have Islam as a
religion between man and God only, is wrong.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
