<DOCNO> AP880723-0165 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 2110EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0603 07-23 0723</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0603,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis and Bentsen Push Ethnic Themes In Tandem Campaigning</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 5 grafs new with Dukakis appearance in Minot, SUBS 2nd
graf pvs, ``Here I, for transition; SUBS 7th graf pvs, In his, to
correct spelling of Portuguese; SUBS 13th graf pvs, On Friday, to
delete reference to Minot stop</NOTE>
<HEAD>Precede MODESTO, Calif.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINOT, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential candidate Michael
Dukakis took his campaign to the nation's agricultural heartland on
Saturday, emphasizing his support for the farm family he called
``the backbone of this country.''
   Dukakis, with running mate Lloyd Bentsen at his side, appeared
before a huge crowd at the North Dakota State Fair and promised
that as president he would invest in rural development.
   ``If there's one thing I believe in it's the farm family because
it's the backbone of this country ... and our economy,'' Dukakis
said.
   The stop in Minot, in a state with the fewest electoral votes,
followed a morning rally in the central valley of California for an
early strike in the biggest battleground for electoral votes.
   ``Here I am the son of immigrants, running with the grandson of
immigrants,'' Dukakis told the cheering crowd of more than 5,000
overflowing from a park amphitheater in Modesto, Calif.
   ``This was a trip I wanted very much to make right after
Atlanta. To come out here, to the heartland of the country.'' he
said. ``To be in a valley which is America, because you are
America, all of you.''
   Even the music was designed to rouse local immigrant pride. As
the candidates entered and departed, the loudspeakers blared singer
Neil Diamond's song, ``America,'' about immigrants coming to
America and being proud of their new country, from the movie ``The
Jazz Singer.''
   The Massachusetts governor accepted gifts from children
representing local communities, including those from his own Greek
background. Wife Kitty put a Scottish cap on her husband, which he
showed off and then waved to the crowd.
   Kept off to the side was a noisy group of several dozen
anti-abortion protesters.
   In his speech, Dukakis threw in Greek, Spanish and Portuguese
phrases and got cheers from those groups. But his main pitch was to
economic issues and to what he called ``progressive values'' of
thrift and hard work, combined with help from the government
including expanded health insurance programs.
   He promised to find new uses for agricultural products and to
fight what he said was 12 percent unemployment in the Modesto area.
   The economic expansion of the Reagan administration was built on
a ``fiscal house of cards'' standing on the huge federal debt that
more than doubled during the past eight years, he said.
   Reagan, in his weekly radio address on Saturday, said the
Democrats ``don't want to level'' with the American people, trying
to hide their liberal politics.
   ``To hear them talk, you would never have guessed we are in the
biggest peacetime expansion in history,'' he said. When the
Democrats last controlled the White House, he said, ``America did a
heck of a lot worse.''
   The Democratic candidates were in the second day of a three-day
post convention swing across the country, with a strong
middle-America theme.
   On Friday, they campaigned in Bentsen's home state of Texas.
Sunday's plans included events in St. Louis and Erie, Pa., before
returning to Dukakis' native Boston.
   The rally was in the congressional district of Rep. Tony Coelho,
the third-ranking Democrat in the House, who said the ticket of
Dukakis and Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen could wrest from the
Republicans two central valley voting groups which had strayed to
the Republican side in presidential elections.
   Dukakis appealed to the families of ethnic immigrants. Running
mate Bentsen, himself from a Rio Grande valley farm family,
appealed to those who moved to the rich agricultural valley from
Texas, Oklahoma and other states hit by the dust bowl of the
1930's, he said.
   ``If we can win the central San Joaquin valley, we can win the
state,'' said Coelho. California, with 47 electoral votes, has more
than any other state. The Democrats have not won it since 1964.
   Coelho, former chairman of the Democrats' national congressional
campaign committee, said Bush would probably neutralize the appeal
of the Democratic ticket in California if he chose Gov. George
Deukmejian as his running mate.
</TEXT>
