<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Scandal     07-23 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Scandal,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Ministry to Look Into Stock Scandal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's Finance Ministry will investigate a real
estate firm at the hub of a stock scandal involving several of the
nation's top leaders, including Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita,
news reports said Saturday.
   The scandal touches more than a dozen prominent political,
communications and other business leaders. They are suspected of
earning huge profits by obtaining unlisted shares of the company
and selling them after they were released on the market.
   ``We will investigate the case to disclose the whole picture,''
a senior Finance Ministry official was quoted as saying by the
nationally circulated Asahi Shimbun. The official was not
identified.
   Takeshita, former Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone, and former
Foreign Minister Shintaro Abe, a senior governing party official,
have acknowledged that their aides earned such profits. In Japan,
aides often act in such matters on behalf of their bosses.
   The Finance Ministry called on the real estate firm,
Recruit-Cosmos Co., to reveal the names of everyone who obtained
the company's unlisted stocks.
   Another leading daily, the Sankei Shimbun, said the Finance
Ministry will investigate to determine whether the dealings
violated the nation's Security and Exchange Law.
</TEXT>
