<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SAfrica-Violence     07-23 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Violence,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Dead in Natal Violence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police killed two black men after
they came under fire in a crowd in Natal province, according to a
police report Saturday.
   The daily police unrest report for Friday said 14 men were
arrested at Neamalala after the shooting ended.
   The report said the police had been investigating the deaths of
two men who had been stabbed to death in Zululand township.
   In two other incidents in Natal, at Kwandegezi, near Pinetown,
police said a gunman wounded a member of the security force, and
police found the body of a black man stabbed to death at Mbimbali.
   A group of blacks set a house afire in Mpumalanga, also in
Natal, and a black woman suffered slight burns, police said.
   No further details on any of the events were given. Fighting
between different black political factions in the Natal townships
has been going on for more than a year, with an estimated 500
people killed.
   State-of-emergency regulations restrict reporting about unrest,
security force action, treatment of detainees, some forms of
protest and a range of statements classified as subversive.
</TEXT>
