<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Vatican-Israel     07-23 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vatican-Israel,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Patriarch Calls on Israelis to Halt `Repressive Measures'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Roman Catholic patriarch of Jerusalem
called on Israeli authorities Saturday to ``renounce repressive
measures'' in dealing with the Palestinian uprising.
   Michel Sabbah, a Palestinian, told Vatican Radio: ``Violent
measures used by the Israeli authorities, repressive measures, will
never lead to calm and even less to peace, because violence
encourages violence and an ever stronger resistance.''
   ``What should be done is to try to understand the desires of
these people calling for their rights, to talk with them and above
all to treat them like human beings.''
   The patriarch is the spiritual leader of the 65,000 Latin-rite
Catholics in Israel, the Israeli-occupied territories, Jordan and
Cyprus. Sabbah was the first Arab named to the post.
   The Jerusalem-born priest became patriarch in January, a month
after the Palestinian uprising in the West Bank and Gaza Strip
began. More than 230 Palestinians and four Israelis have died in
the violence.
   ``What can the church do?'' Sabbah asked. ``I don't think the
authorities listen, I don't think many others will listen. I
address myself to the Israeli leaders and call on them to renounce
repressive measures.''
   He also said he feared the violence connected with the uprising
would grow worse since ``it seems that until the elections this
November, authority will rest in the hands of the military and no
politician wants to take any responsibility.''
</TEXT>
