<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ireland-Kirov     07-23 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ireland-Kirov,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets' Kirov Ballet Gets Rave Reviews In First Irish Tour</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kirov Ballet received rave reviews on
its first visit to Ireland as part of the celebration of Dublin's
1,000th birthday.
   The Soviet company's six-day tour, which ended Saturday,
featured the European premiere of a new production of ``Swan Lake''
by Kirov director Oleg Vinogradov.
   Under the headline ``A Production of Perfection,'' the Irish
Independent newspaper's dance critic Mary MacGoris wrote, ``The
magic of `Swan Lake' cast a sustained spell ... the dancing was
magnificent.''
   Reviewer Carolyn Swift of The Irish Times called the production
``the closest to perfect I have ever seen.''
   The 3,500-seat Simmonscourt exhibition hall at the Royal Dublin
Society was sold out for the Kirov's seven performances.
   Top price for tickets was 50 Irish pounds ($75). A jarring note
was the heat in the building, which does not have air conditioning.
   Many of the 200 members of the Kirov Ballet attended a
performance at Dublin's Gaiety theater and went to see the movie
``Crocodile Dundee'' during breaks from rehearsals before Monday's
opening performance. They also went shopping.
   The company goes to London Monday.
</TEXT>
