<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Baby'sFingers 1stLd_Writethru a0647 07-23 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baby's Fingers, 1st Ld _ Writethru, a0647,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newborn Baby's Fingers Reattached</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd-3rd grafs to UPDATE with hospital official's
elaboration it was an accident and that instrument appears not to
have been malfunctioning. Picks up 4th graf `Kristen Meckle ... '</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ROBBINSDALE, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newborn baby was in fair condition
Saturday after doctors in Minnesota reattached two fingers severed
during a Caesarean section at a North Dakota hospital, officials
said.
   A surgeon at Trinity Medical Center in Minot, N.D., was making
an incision with a disposable surgical stapler when he accidentally
cut off the tips of the baby's index and middle fingers, hospital
President Terry Hoff said Saturday.
   About a quarter-inch of each of the two fingers was cut off
during the Friday surgery but the joints were unaffected, he said.
Surgical staplers cut and staple at the same time, Hoff said. The
North Dakota hospital's president said the instrument appears not
to have malfunctioned.
   Kristen Meckle, daughter of Ted and Diane Meckle, was flown to
North Memorial Medical Center in Robbinsdale for reattachment
surgery later Friday, said North Memorial spokeswoman Karen
Knepper. The medical center has been the site of previous
successful reattachments.
   Knepper said the baby was in ``very critical'' condition when
she arrived Friday night, but her condition improved after the
surgery.
   ``The prognosis for keeping her fingers is good,'' Knepper said.
   Hoff would not release the name of the surgeon who performed the
Caesarean section.
   He said no formal investigation will be made, but hospital staff
members and doctors who handle what he called quality assurance
will look into the incident.
   Knepper said the baby will remain at North Memorial eight to 10
days.
</TEXT>
