<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 2239EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Deaths     07-23 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths,0410</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Lee LeBlanc</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>IRON RIVER, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lee LeBlanc, who became a leading
wildlife artist and a winner of the prestigious federal duck stamp
competition after retiring from a career at several Hollywood
studios, died Thursday at 74.
   LeBlanc, who lived in Iron County, Mich., since his retirement
in 1962, died at a hospital in Marshfield, Wis.
   From 1972 on, he designed stamps for wildlife and fishing
licenses in several states and Canada. He won the prestigious
federal duck stamp competition for 1973-74 with his painting of a
pair of Stellar's eiders.
   He also drew illustrations for such things as greeting cards and
children's books on wildlife.
   Born Oct. 5, 1913, in Powers, LeBlanc attended art schools in
Los Angeles, Philadelphia and New York before joining the staff of
Walt Disney.
   He later held administrative positions at 20th Century Fox and
MGM studios until his retirement.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>John Burchard</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE COMPTON, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John C. Burchard, who made headlines
for trying to fly an airplane with no experience in 1930, died in a
car crash Monday. He was 89.
   The electronics engineer tried his hand at flying in a small
plane in Chicago in June 1930, even though he had never been in one
before.
   After takeoff, he found himself in the air upside down with
gasoline dripping over his nose, hanging by his seat belt. He
managed to land in a pasture _ still upside down _ and walked away
with only a bump on his head.
   Burchard later took flying lessons, and received his pilot's
license in 1943. He continued flying until shortly before his
death.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Roy Rosenthal</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roy Gilbert Rosenthal, former publisher of
several community newspapers and former chairman of University
Printing Co., died Thursday at Swedish Hospital. He was 92.
   Rosenthal joined the University District Herald's editorial
staff while a college student, and returned to the Herald and his
studies after serving in World War I.
   In 1922, Rosenthal bought the Montesano Vidette, and in 1927 he
bought the Herald and its parent, University Printing Co.
   From 1932 to 1937, Rosenthal was the University of Washington
director of publicity.
   He founded the Northgate-North Seattle Journal in 1950 and was
its publisher until he sold the Journal and Herald in 1961.
Rosenthal also published the Jewish Transcript and the Masonic
Tribune.
</TEXT>
