<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BusAccident 1stLd_Writethru a0651 07-23 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Accident, 1st Ld _ Writethru, a0651,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Driver Charged After Bus Runs off N.J. Highway, Injures At Least
42</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with arrest of driver, details of bus'
destination, traffic tie-ups.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BASS RIVER, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bus driver was charged with possession
of drug paraphernalia Saturday night after the bus she was driving
went off the Garden State Parkway, injuring all 42 passengers, two
of them seriously, and tying up traffic for hours, state police
said.
   The Gray Lines tour bus, transporting a church group from New
York City to Atlantic City, went off the road and into some trees
Saturday afternoon, said state police Sgt. Stacy Cranmer.
   State police did not know the name of the church.
   The driver, Annette Smalls, 29, of Newark, N.J., was questioned
after she underwent blood and urine tests at Shore Memorial
Hospital in Somers Point, N.J., said state Trooper Michael Kaiser.
Test results will not be known for several days, he said.
   Kaiser said additional charges against Ms. Smalls, who was being
held at the Bass River state police station late Saturday night,
were pending. He declined to specify the paraphernalia involved. No
other arrests were made.
   An investigation was continuing into the accident's cause, which
occurred after rain had dampened the road, Kaiser said.
   Helene Kennedy, a nursing supervisor at the mainland division of
the Atlantic City Medical Center, said 21 passengers were brought
to the hospital.
   One person was in critical condition and another in serious
condition Saturday night, Ms. Kennedy said, adding their names were
being withheld until after notification of their families.
   The remaining passengers were treated and released, she said.
   Twelve passengers were taken to the Atlantic City Medical
Center's city division and were treated and released with minor
cuts and bruises, another nursing supervisor said.
   A nursing supervisor at Shore Memorial said nine people were
brought to the hospital. They also were treated and released with
minor injuries.
   The accident caused traffic back-ups of up to five miles in the
southbound lanes for several hours as vehicles were restricted to
one lane, Cranmer said.
</TEXT>
