<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 2313EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WritersStrike     07-23 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Writers Strike,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Striking Scriptwriters Meet With Producers, Agree On News Blackout</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Networks-Writers, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Producers and striking scriptwriters resumed
talks Saturday for the first time in more than a month, and both
sides immediately agreed to a news blackout.
   A federal mediator ordered negotiators for the Writers Guild of
America and the Alliance of Motion Picture and Television Producers
back to the bargaining table. The 5-month-old walkout has crippled
TV and movie production.
   Mediator Leonard Farrell can convene meetings but lacks the
authority to arbitrate the dispute. He asked for the news blackout
at the start of Saturday's meeting at alliance headquarters in
Sherman Oaks, said Martin Waldman, spokesman for the 9,000-member
guild. The news blackout extends for the duration of the resumed
negotiating sessions, Waldman said.
   ``Something historic is happening upstairs. I think there is
finally the opportunity to make a deal,'' George Kirgo, head of the
union's West Coast branch, said before Saturday's meeting. ``I have
true high hopes for the first time in a long time that we can make
some sense at this table and that it can come to an end this
weekend.''
   But alliance spokesman Herb Steinberg said the producers had
nothing new to offer.
   ``All of the ingredients for a deal are on the table and they
have been for several weeks,'' said Steinberg. ``We are going to
sit and listen. That is our posture for this meeting.''
   Previous talks ended in June with scriptwriters overwhelmingly
rejecting an offer from producers.
   The strike began March 7 over the issue of payments for reruns
of one-hour domestic shows and a bigger share in the increased
foreign market.
</TEXT>
