<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 2324EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MinisterSlain     07-23 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Minister Slain,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suspect Denied Bond In Slaying Of Civil Rights Figure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AURORA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond was denied Saturday to a man charged
with the beating death of a minister who had just returned from the
Democratic National Convention, authorities said.
   The Rev. Robert Wesby, a prominent civil rights activist in this
community, had gone to Atlanta to support Jesse Jackson, the
unsuccessful presidential candidate.
   Wesby, 61, was a ``good friend down through the years, an
honorable man,'' Jackson said Saturday.
   ``We regret so much that this good man was killed and we hope
that those who were involved will face swift justice,'' Jackson
said.
   Wesby was beaten to death Friday near the altar of his
Progressive Baptist Church, about 35 miles west of Chicago. Acting
on a tip, police arrested Calvin Green, 28, of Aurora and charged
him with first-degree murder.
   Kane County Circuit Judge Peter Grometer ordered Green held
without bond, said police Sgt. Ron Martin.
   Martin would not comment on whether police knew of a possible
motive for the slaying. Church members said Green was a street
preacher in the area.
   County Coroner Mary Lou Kearns said Wesby was killed with a
``very sharp, heavy instrument.'' No murder weapon was found at the
scene, police said.
   Kearns said wounds on Wesby's left arm indicated he tried to
defend himself.
   Wesby founded his church 25 years ago. Since 1972, he also led
the Aurora branch of Operation PUSH, the Chicago-based civil rights
organization founded by Jackson.
   He was a follower of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. and
participated in the famous 1965 march from Selma, Ala., to
Montgomery, Ala.
</TEXT>
