<1ST_LINE>u i AM-India-Disease     07-23 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Disease,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delhi's Death Toll From Cholera Rises To 118</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers with spades, wheelbarrows and
trucks began removing heaps of garbage from New Delhi's slum areas
Saturday as officials reported 14 more deaths from cholera and
intestinal infections.
   The death toll from this month's outbreak is now at least 118,
and a city health spokesman said Saturday hospitals had admitted 70
more patients with cholera and other intestinal diseases.
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi, who visited the affected districts
Friday, has given the municipal sanitation department a deadline of
three days to clean clogged drains and garbage dumps and spray
pesticides over stagnant water.
   He accused city administrators and health officers of not doing
enough to combat the epidemic.
   The health department spokesman, who spoke with the condition he
not be identified, said 103,684 people have been inoculated in the
disease-stricken zones.
   Trucks were collecting garbage and crews cleared the overworked
drainage system.
   The onset of the monsoon rains in early July resulted in clogged
drains in districts with inadequate sanitation facilities.
   Health officials blame the cholera outbreak on the contamination
of wells by rainwater flowing through garbage and sewage.
   More than 9,140 people have sought treatment at hospitals this
month for cholera and gastroenteritis, according to official
figures. That is more than four times the number of such cases
registered in all of July last year.
   Outbreaks of cholera and gastroenteritis also have occurred in
northern Uttar Pradesh and Punjab states claiming 62 lives,
according to news reports.
</TEXT>
