<2ND_LINE>AM-Cambodia-Talks,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cambodian Leader Says Peace Talks Depend on Rebels</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One name cq for Suharto and Moerdiono</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GHAFUR FADYL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodian leader Hun Sen thanked
Vietnam and Indonesia Saturday for their efforts to find a peace
formula for his country and said success also depends on rebels
fighting his government.
   He made the remarks as he joined delegates from Vietnam and the
Cambodian resistance alliance for the first such talks since
Vietnam invaded Cambodia nearly 10 years ago. The talks are
scheduled to begin Monday.
   Hun Sen described the first informal meeting Saturday as a
result of the initiative of Indonesia and Vietnam.
   ``We appreciate the efforts to solve the Cambodian problem. We
will endeavor to make the `cocktail party' a success. But it also
depends on the other side,'' he said.
   Delegates were calling Saturday's meeting a cocktail party.
   Meanwhile, former Cambodian leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk
arrived for a six-day visit as guest of Indonesian President
Suharto.
   The prince was not scheduled to attend talks between the three
guerrilla factions and government scheduled to be held at the
presidential palace in Bogor. The mountain retreat is about 40
miles south of Jakarta.
   Sihanouk resigned as president of the guerrilla coalition, which
includes his followers, anti-communists and the radical Khmer
Rouge, on July 11. He has said he will be represented at the talks
by his son, Prince Norodom Ranariddh.
   Other delegates arriving Saturday included Vietnamese Foreign
Minister Nguyen Co Thach and Laotian acting Foreign Minister
Thongsavath Khaikham-Phithoune.
   The Vietnamese official told reporters, ``I express my firm
belief that the `cocktail party' will be successful because of the
courage and wisdom of Indonesia.''
   In the meeting with Suharto, Sihanouk expressed hope for the
success of the talks, presidential spokesman Moerdiono said.
</TEXT>
