<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 0000EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Brazil-USSanctions     07-23 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-US Sanctions,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brazilian President Calls U.S. Trade Sanctions `Unfair'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Brazil Trade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Sarney on Friday
criticized as unfair a U.S. decision to impose economic sanctions
on Brazil for refusing to recognize patents for foreign
pharmaceutical products.
   President Reagan started a process Friday that will lead to
sanctions on $200 million worth of yet unspecified Brazilian goods.
The United States is the No. 1 market for Brazilian exports.
   Sarney issued a communique calling the decision ``unfair and
discriminatory.'' He said it ``violates the most elementary
principles of international law and the GATT,'' referring to the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, the Geneva-based body that
promotes fair trade practices.
   Sarney said the U.S. government was caving in to the special
interests of the American pharmaceutical industry and warned the
action ``tends to undermine bilateral trade relations.''
   The United States claims American drug companies lose about $36
million a year because Brazil permits unauthorized copies of
pharmaceutical products and formulas.
   Sarney denied that U.S. companies were being jeopardized. He
said 85 percent of the Brazilian drug industry is foreign-owned and
that American companies were the market leaders with a 35 percent
share.
   He added that Brazil may demand reparations under GATT
provisions for damages caused by the sanctions.
   The sale of medical drugs in Brazil totaled $1.1 billion in
1987, according to the Brazilian Pharmaceutical Industry
Association. About 73 percent of that total was by foreign-owned
multinationals.
   Of the 500 pharmaceutical companies in Brazil, 69 are
foreign-owned, the association said.
   The U.S. decision had been expected by the drug industry in
Brazil, said Jorge Raimundo, president of the Anglo-American
Pharmaceutical Industry Chamber.
   ``Only the government didn't see it coming. Brazil has not shown
any willingness to negotiate,'' Raimundo said in a telephone
interview.
   Raimundo, who also is an executive of the Brazilian subsidiary
of the British-owned Glaxo drug company, said the sanctions would
immediately hurt Brazilian exports.
   ``It already is having an effect. The American importer and the
Brazilian exporter don't know what products will be on the list, so
trade stalls,'' he said.
   The United States came close to slapping $105 million in trade
sanctions on Brazil earlier this year, but backed away in March
when that country responded to complaints about its policies
regarding importation of software products.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
