<HEAD>Three Bodies Recovered From Canal Where Plane Crashed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities Friday pulled three bodies from
the drainage canal where a DC-6 cargo plane crashed Wednesday
night, and investigators continued their inspection of the crash
site.
   The plane went down near the Golden Meadow community in
Lafourche Parish, about 40 miles south of New Orleans. The
Lafourche Parish Sheriff's Office withheld the identities of the
three crash victims Friday, saying only that they were from the
Miami area.
   The four-engine, propeller driven aircraft belonged to Universal
Air Equipment Leasing Inc. of Miami and was operated by Fiorelli
Crews of Miami, according to a news release from TACA Airlines,
which had chartered the flight to carry 22,000 pounds of
handicrafts, seafood and other cargo.
   Federal Aviation Administration investigators have not
determined the cause of the crash, but an FAA controller who asked
not to be identified has said the plane's pilot reported he was
short of fuel and would be unable to reach New Orleans.
   There were believed to be only three crewmen aboard the plane.
