<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Sikhs,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>19 People Killed in Sikh Violence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New attacks blamed on Sikh militants
killed 19 people in northern Punjab state, a news agency reported
Friday.
   The violence followed a bombing Tuesday near the holiest Sikh
shrine, the Golden Temple in Amritsar, that killed at least 29
people and injured more than 40. Sikh radicals were also blamed for
that attack.
   The latest killings raised to at least 1,552 the toll in Punjab
this year blamed on Sikh militants fighting for an independent
homeland.
   In one attack, five Nihangs, members of a Sikh fundamentalist
sect, were shot to death on a highway about 20 miles from Amritsar,
the United News of India agency said.
   In a nearby village, three Sikhs, including two women, were
killed.
   UNI did not say when the attacks occurred and gave no details.
   Militant Sikhs are often blamed for slaying moderates who oppose
their calls for independence.
   Sikhs form 2 percent of India's 800 million people but
constitute a majority in Punjab.
   Radical Sikhs have been campaigning for a separate homeland
since 1982. They claim they are discriminated against by Hindus,
who make up 80 percent of the population.
   The Sikh religion was created 500 years ago as an alternative to
Hinduism and Islam.
