<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cuba-USVisas     07-23 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuba-US Visas,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuba Says U.S. Visa Cancellation Reflects Displeasure</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mica-Cuba</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuba canceled visas of a U.S. congressional
delegation to express its objections to a meeting between American
diplomats and Cuban dissidents, the Cuban news agency Prensa Latina
reported Friday from Havana.
   It said the Foreign Ministry issued a statement charging, ``The
July 15 meeting was organized to make it possible for American
diplomats to instruct their counterrevolutionary servants and was
not a normal diplomatic activity.'' Rep. Dan Mica, D-Fla., chairman
of a House foreign affairs subcommittee, was to travel to Cuba with
several aides to inspect U.S. diplomatic facilities. The United
States maintains no formal diplomatic ties with the communist
Caribbean nation, but has a Special Interest Section in Havana.
   Cuba revoked the visas Tuesday night.
   Mica wrote to President Fidel Castro expressing ``shock'' and
``astonishment'' over Cuba's decision. Mica's letter was dated
Thursday and released Friday.
   The Havana government statement said the July 15 meeting
represented interference in Cuba's internal affairs and called the
gathering ``a gross provocation.''
   Prensa Latina, monitored in Mexico City, quoted the ministry as
saying the meeting was held at the home of an American diplomat in
Cuba ``with a score of former counterrevolutionary prisoners and
other enemies of our process.''
   It said the Cubans were advised how to act during a visit to
Cuba by a delegation of the U.N. Human Rights Commission, planned
later this summer.
   Mica wrote, ``If the mere fact that members of the Cuban
Committee on Human Rights attended a party results in punitive
action against the United States, one can hardly imagine that the
Cuban people would feel free to meet and provide information to
representatives of the U.N. Human Rights Commission.''
   He called on Castro to make it clear to the people of Cuba that
they are free to speak openly to the commission members.
</TEXT>
