<2ND_LINE>AM-Man of Steel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0748,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minor Injuries When 1,000 Pounds Of Steel Falls On Man</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one graf after 8th graf ``I'm just...' to UPDATE with
company president's comment. Edits throughout to reflect that man
was helped by outside crew sted co-workers.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WAUSAU, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sheet of steel estimated to weigh 1,000
pounds fell on a construction worker and pinned him, but other
workers got him out of the tight squeeze and he suffered only minor
injuries.
   ``I couldn't breathe under there,'' Thomas Bittner of Wausau
said Friday. ``I'm lucky I had enough guys there to get me out.''
   ``I was squashed. All I wanted was to get this thing off of
me,'' he said.
   Bittner, 35, was working on a fence being erected Thursday at
Wausau Steel Corp. when a hook connecting a section of fence to a
crane came loose and the section fell on him, the Marathon County
Sheriff's Department reported.
   The sheet of quarter-inch thick steel, roughly seven feet wide
and 30 feet long piece, pinned Bittner on top of scrap metal, said
David Pagel, safety director in the Marathon County Sheriff's
Department.
   Workers freed him before firefighters arrived, the fire
department said.
   ``I was working with about four or five other guys. They lifted
the corner of the plate and got me out,'' Bittner said.
   ``I'm just glad people were there to help,'' he said.
   Peter Wallach, president of Wausau Steel, said Bittner was
helping an outside crew putting up the fence when the accident
happened. ``I just figured we were all ... lucky that he didn't
even have a broken bone,'' Wallach said.
   Bittner, who was wearing a welding helmet when the fence section
fell, was treated for minor injuries to his head, chest and elbow
at Wausau Hospital Center and released, officials said. He also
needed stitches for a cut behind one ear.
   Bittner and the other workers estimated the sheet of metal
weighed about 1,000 pounds.
   ``I guess anything over 100 pounds doesn't feel so great,''
Bittner said.
</TEXT>
