<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola-Rebels,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angolan Rebels Report Killing 37 Soldiers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angola's rebels said Friday they killed
more than 37 soldiers in four attacks this week. Their claim came
two days after Marxist Angola formally accepted a pact calling for
removal of foreign troops.
   Rebels of UNITA, the National Union for the Total Independence
of Angola, also said they also captured two soldiers.
   They gave rebel casualties as four killed and nine wounded.
   The rebels gave no details, and there was no independent
confirmation of their claims, made in a statement distributed in
this Portuguese capital.
   South Africa, Angola and Cuba formally accepted a U.S.-brokered
agreement Wednesday aimed at getting foreign troops out of Angola
and granting independence to bordering South-West Africa, also
known as Namibia.
   Cuban troops in Angola help the government fight the rebels,
while South African troops are in southern Angola to bolster UNITA
forces.
   South Africa controls South-West Africa and joins Washington in
backing the Angolan rebels.
   The rebels were not a party to the agreement, which gave no
specific timetable for withdrawal.
   Angola's guerrillas have been fighting since 1975 to force the
government to share power.
</TEXT>
