<DOCNO> AP880723-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 0021EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DefenseProbe     07-23 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Probe,0613</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Delays Decision on Defense Probe Documents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge listened to more than two
hours of legal arguments Friday, then delayed ruling on a news
media request to unseal documents in a major investigation of
suspected fraud in military contracts.
   ``It seems to me there is just no way to properly render a
decision from the bench,'' U.S. District Court Judge David Kenyon
said.
   He said he had not received complete copies of the documents
sought until Friday and wanted to study them before ruling and
added: ``I'm not at all sure what decision will be rendered.''
   The request pending in Los Angeles is one of a number of similar
efforts by news organizations to see affidavits related to the
coast-to-coast probe of the relationship between defense industry
consultants, Pentagon officials and weapons manufacturers.
   Before leaving the bench, Kenyon asked government prosecutors
how long they planned to keep the material sealed if he ruled in
their favor. Prosecutors had asked Kenyon to overturn a decision by
U.S. Magistrate Joseph Reichmann, who ruled last week that the
public has a right to see the documents now.
   ``I can't give you a date, but I hope it would be reasonably
soon,'' responded U.S. Attorney Robert Bonner. He said it would be
released when the government no longer feared harm to its
investigation.
   But attorney Rex Heincke, representing the Los Angeles Times,
argued the government failed to show that any harm could come from
documents in an investigation that is already in headlines.
   ``Anyone who is going to destroy evidence has done it by now,''
he said.
   Attorneys for the Los Angeles Times, Copley Newspapers, NBC and
CBS sought release of the documents detailing searches at the
offices of Litton Industries, Teledyne Electronics and Northrop
Corp., and the Los Angeles home of consultant Fred Lackner.
   The most vehement opposition to unsealing the documents came
from a battery of attorneys representing unnamed employees of
companies mentioned as targets of the probe. They argued that the
reputations of these clients, referred to as ``Mr. X,'' would be
harmed by a mention in the documents, even if they are never
charged with a crime.
   ``It would be totally destructive of these individuals to unseal
the affidavits,'' said attorney George O'Connell.
   Among the newspapers seek release of similar documents are The
Washington Times; The Washington Post; St. Louis Post-Dispatch;
Newsday, published in Long Island, N.Y., and New York City; the St.
Paul (Minn.) Pioneer Press Dispatch; the Star Tribune of
Minneapolis; and The Hartford (Conn.) Courant.
   In Minneapolis on Friday, a federal magistrate took under
advisement a request to see documents allowing a search of Unisys
Corp. offices in Minnesota.
   Patrick Schiltz, lawyer for the Star Tribune, told U.S.
Magistrate Earl Cudd that keeping the search warrants and
affidavits sealed is pointless because ``any reasonably informed
observer'' could make a good guess as to what is involved in the
investigation, simply by reading newspapers.
   But Assistant U.S. Attorney Thor Anderson told the magistrate
the fact the information was printed in newspapers ``doesn't make
it accurate.''
   On Thursday, The Hartford Courant filed a motion seeking
documents related to the search of Pratt & Whitney offices in
Washington, D.C. Earlier in the week, the newspaper had asked a
federal judge to unseal affidavits related to the search of three
Connecticut offices of Norden Systems and the home of a Norden vice
president.
   Both Pratt & Whitney and Norden Systems are divisions of
Hartford-based United Technologies Corp., Connecticut's largest
private employer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880723-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 0040EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada-Abortion     07-23 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Abortion,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Woman Can Have Abortion Though Boyfriend Objects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian provincial court in a landmark ruling
on Friday rejected an Edmonton man's bid to prevent his former
girlfriend from having an abortion.
   But Justice Joanne Viet of Alberta Court of Queen's Bench
acknowledged the rights of a father of an unborn child by ruling
that Randy Mock, 25, could sue 18-year-old Michelle Brandanburg for
damages.
   Mock obtained a temporary injunction to prevent Ms. Brandanburg
from proceeding with the abortion, but that injunction expired on
Thursday.
   When it did, Ms. Brandanburg's lawyer told reporters, her client
went to the United States and got an abortion.
   ``It's devastating,'' said Mock, who had claimed father's rights
and wanted to raise the child on his own.
   He said he would pursue the case for damages. ``I've come this
far ... I've just lost my child and it's not going to die in vain.''
   The decision came as Parliament wrestled with the abortion issue
following a controversial Supreme Court decision last January,
striking down Canada's restrictive abortion law.
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney's Conservative government said
debate will begin next week on compromise legislation that would
permit easy access to abortions early in a pregnancy but impose
restrictions in later stages.
   Anti-abortion and pro-choice groups had used the Edmonton case
to back their arguments, and both sides claimed victory.
   ``Every step along the way in cases like this are important for
women,'' said defense attorney Donna Oliver Dyck, who represented
Ms. Brandanburg and argued that a woman should have control of her
own body.
   Mock's lawyer, Rosanna Saccomani, said the judge acknowledged
the merits of her client's case by saying he had the right to sue
for damages.
   Ms. Saccomani told the court the couple lived together 18 months
and had a verbal agreement as a common-law couple last February to
stop using contraceptives so they could have a child.
   ``There was an intention to create a child ... that was what the
parties wanted. She should continue with her obligations.''
   She said the relationship broke up in June because of opposition
from Ms. Brandanburg's family. By then, Ms. Brandanburg was
pregnant. Her lawyer argued that Mock's request for a permanent
injunction to prevent the abortion was ``ludicrous'' since he had
no rights as the father of an unborn child.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
