<DOCNO> AP880723-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 0010EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-IrelandPilgrimage     07-23 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ireland Pilgrimage,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>O'Connor and Koch Offer Prayer and Politics In Ireland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KNOCK, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal John O'Connor offered prayers and
New York Mayor Edward Koch talked politics Friday as 1,000
Americans gathered in this land of fog and bog on a pilgrimage for
peace in Northern Ireland.
   ``I hope to do nothing but be a pilgrim. I hope to do nothing
but pray,'' O'Connor said at an airport ceremony, explaining why he
would not delve into political specifics.
   The cardinal, the Roman Catholic archbishop of New York, said he
was visiting Ireland in ``a totally non-political,
non-ambassadorial position. ... The only contact we want to make is
with God.''
   The allusion was to his lack of meetings over the issue of
Northern Ireland.
   Koch, a self-described ``Jewish soldier in the cardinal's
army,'' was less reticent.
   He repeated his belief that the British should eventually leave
Northern Ireland and said the British should release a government
report on police violence against nationalists in the province.
   The mayor said that by not releasing the report, compiled by
veteran investigator John Stalker, the British government ``loses
any credibility for the future ... and that means that there's even
more bitterness.''
   At Knock, Koch joined the pilgrims and embraced O'Connor, who
kidded him, ``You're all over the papers'' _ a reference to a
photograph of Koch pouring a pint of ale in a Dublin pub.
   The pilgrims gathered at the Shrine of Our Lady of Knock, which
commemorates the evening of Aug. 21, 1879, when 15 people said they
saw a vision of Mary, mother of Jesus.
   The apparition was a rare sign of hope in a region that had been
devastated by famine and emigration. The shrine's success as a
tourist destination was ensured when Pope John Paul II visited it
in 1979.
   Knock is still a village of less than 400 people, but now it
boasts three hotels and as many policemen, more than a dozen pubs,
and an airport with an 8,000-foot-long runway.
   Despite a turnout that was lower than expected _ the basilica in
Knock was only half filled for his first Mass in Ireland _ O'Connor
said he was not concerned.
   ``Not only am I not disappointed, I am overjoyed by the number
that did come,'' O'Connor said.
   In a conclusion to his sermon, O'Connor said: ``This is the
beginning of a series of pilgrimages that will captivate the world.
... All hearts, all minds will turn toward the sufferings in
Northern Ireland.''
   The mainly Catholic Irish Republican Army is fighting to push
the British out of Protestant-dominated Northern Ireland, join it
with the Republic of Ireland and set up an all-Ireland socialist
state. The IRA is outlawed on both sides of the border. Its legal
political wing is Sinn Fein.
   The Protestant-Catholic ratio in Northern Ireland is 3-2,
according to its Fair Employment Agency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
