<DOCNO> AP880723-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 0044EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Japan     07-23 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Japan,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Tells Japan It Can't Have Islands</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev told former Prime Minister
Yasuhiro Nakasone of Japan on Friday that Japan's alliance with the
West blocks return of four disputed islands, a Japanese official
said.
   The Soviet leader reiterated the Kremlin's long-standing
position on the islands, under Soviet control since World War II.
His stance allowed no progress on what Tokyo considers the main
obstacle to improved relations with Moscow, the Japanese official
said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The Soviet Union occupied four islands off northern Japan at the
end of World War II. The dispute over ownership of the territory
has prevented the two nations from concluding a peace treaty for 43
years.
   Nakasone told Gorbachev some of the area was occupied illegally
by former dictator Josef V. Stalin. Nakasone argued that, as part
of the current Soviet drive to acknowledge and correct past wrongs
committed by Stalin, the territory should be returned to Japan, the
Japanese official said.
   In a 1956 joint declaration between the two nations, the Soviet
government announced its willingness to return two of the islands
upon conclusion of a peace treaty to officially note the end of
World War II.
   However, Gorbachev reminded Nakasone that the Kremlin amended
that position in 1960 ``because Japan decided to conclude a new
security arrangement with the United States,'' the official said,
paraphrasing Gorbachev.
   He reported that despite the impasse on the issue, Nakasone was
pleased with the visit that began here Wednesday. Nakasone was due
to leave Monday and return directly to Moscow.
   ``We didn't find anything particularly new in the messages sent
by the Soviet side,'' said the government official, who was present
at the meeting between Gorbachev and Nakasone. ``But what was more
interesting was the extent to which we were able to get our message
across to the Soviet side.''
   Nakasone left the office of prime minister late last year but
has been considered during the Soviet visit as an envoy of his
successor, Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita. Japan officially
considers Nakasone's visit private, though he belongs to the Diet,
or Parliament.
   The Japanese official contrasted what he described as a new
Soviet receptiveness with conditions four years ago, when all
mention of the disputed islands was censored from Japanese speeches
carried by Soviet media.
   The official said Nakasone and Gorbachev expressed mutual
interest in improving relations between their countries but that no
specific agreements were concluded during the visit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
