<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Drought     07-23 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Drought,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought Drying Rivers In Hubei Province; Could Cut Water To
Shanghai</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China-Weather</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A heat wave and a drought that is ravaging much
of central China is drying rivers, destroying crops and threatening
the water supply of China's biggest city, Shanghai, newspapers
reported Friday.
   The Liberation Daily (Jiefang Ribao) said water consumption in
Shanghai has been near an all-time high since the beginning of July.
   Temperatures have hovered around 100 degrees and little rain has
fallen.
   Nearly 500 heat-related deaths have been reported during the
last month in central China. Most of the deaths have been
concentrated around the Yangtze River basin.
   Vice Mayor Ni Tianzeng was quoted as saying that chemicals used
in purifying water would last only five days and that he sent an
emergency request to other provinces for such chemicals.
   In Hubei province, the People's Daily (Renmin Ribao) reported
that 90 percent of middle-sized and smaller rivers had ceased to
flow.
   It said that in the province's northern Yunyang district 90
percent of the corn crop died.
   The China Youth News (Zhongguo Qingnian Bao) reported that in
Wuhan, the capital of Hubei, one third of the city's 3 million
people were not certain of getting their daily minimum of water.
   ``There is no water in many buildings higher than four stories.
In some buildings built on high ground, there is no water in the
daytime and many people get up at midnight to store water for
daytime use,'' the paper said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
