<DOCNO> AP880723-0200 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 0047EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Liner     07-23 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Liner,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Shipworkers Blow Stacks Over QE2's Foreign Repairs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British union leaders fumed Friday as the famed
luxury liner Queen Elizabeth II was shipped back abroad to be made
shipshape.
   ``This could have been avoided if the work had gone to a British
shipyard in the first place,'' said Alex Ferry, general secretary
of the Confederation of Shipbuilding and Engineering Unions.
   The ocean liner, also known as the QE2, will get a new propeller
system in West Germany, where it underwent a costly refitting last
year.
   Cunard Steam-Ship Co. PLC, the liner's owner, faced protests
last year when it gave the $190 million refit contract to the Lloyd
Werft shipyard in Bremerhaven, West Germany. The shipping firm said
no British shipyard would accept the six-month deadline with
penalties reported at $1.7 million a day.
   A Cunard official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Friday the work performed by Lloyd Werft, primarily to install new
diesel engines, had been excellent.
   However, he said problems arose involving a fuel-saving type of
propeller installed at the company's request. He said the device
had never been tried before on a passenger ship.
   The propeller will be replaced with a traditional type at a cost
of $3.4 million, under a guarantee by Lloyd Werft, the spokesman
said.
   However, Ferry laid the problems to cost-cutting wars.
   ``Countries are undercutting each other because of the market,
and this has led directly to work being done to time and price at
the expense of good quality workmanship,'' he said.
   Passengers paying up to $5,950 for the first post-refit cruise
raised a host of complaints, including flooding in cabins and
bathrooms, sweltering rooms and faulty water taps, showers,
telephones and television sets. Some of these problems were linked
to vibration by the propeller shaft.
   The 19-year-old vessel was used as a troop ship during Britain's
1982 war with Argentina over the Falkland Islands.
   It was due back in its home port of Southampton Aug. 1 to take
passengers on a trans-Atlantic trip.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
