<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 0048EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Slovenia     07-23 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Slovenia,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>8,000 Protest Military Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LJUBLJANA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 8,000 people rallied Friday
to support four Slovenians on trial for allegedly disclosing a
military secret, the state Tanjug news agency reported.
   The meeting was organized in a park near Ljubljana, the
Slovenian capital, by an unofficial committee formed to defend
journalists Janez Jansa, David Tasic and Franci Zavrl, along with
Ivan Borstner, a non-commissioned army officer.
   The four were charged by the military court in Ljubljana with
possessing a classified document allegedly dealing with the
deployment of army units in Slovenia, Yugoslavia's most developed
republic.
   Protesters said the closed-door trial, which started Monday, was
seen as an attempt to crack down on democratic tendencies in
Slovenia.
   Several speakers, including intellectuals and war veterans,
criticized the military and Yugoslav federal authorities for
wanting to ``usurp the sovereign rights of the Slovenian people,''
Tanjug said.
   Zavrl, the only defendent not in custody, also addressed the
meeting, describing the trial a ``shameful, humiliating court
proceeding,'' the report said.
   All three journalists have in the past sharply criticized the
army and particularly former Defense Minister Branko Mamula,
accusing him of promoting sales of Yugoslav arms to Third World
countries and of misappropriating public funds.
   Earlier Friday, Yugoslavia's presidency rejected an appeal by
the Slovenian leadership that the trial be conducted in the
Slovenian language instead of Serbo-Croatian.
   The republic's leadership has earlier demanded that the trial be
conducted openly, that the accused be defended by civilian lawyers
and that they be released from custody.
   The army rejected the requests, citing what they called the
sensitive nature of the classified documents.
</TEXT>
