<DOCNO> AP880723-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 0047EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Soviet     07-23 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Soviet,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Says It Is `Consulting' On Cambodia Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China said Saturday the idea of a meeting with
the Soviet Union to discuss how to bring peace to Cambodia is still
under discussion.
   China's Foreign Ministry was replying to reports out of
Washington that Deputy Foreign Minister Zhu Qizhen and his Soviet
counterpart, Igor Rogachev, would meet in Beijing in August to work
out a peace settlement on Cambodia.
   A U.S. official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said U.S.
Secretary of State George P. Shultz was informed of the planned
meeting during a visit to China a week ago.
   The Cambodian question has been taken up in recent sessions of
Chinese-Soviet political normalization talks held twice a year, but
the August meeting would be the first devoted solely to the
subject. The Foreign Ministry called such a meeting ``still under
consultation.''
   It did not elaborate.
   China has said Cambodia is the main obstacle to normalizing
relations with Moscow. Relations have been strained since the two
Communist giants split over ideological and strategic differences
in the early 1960s.
   China, which backs the Khmer Rouge and other forces fighting
Vietnamese troops in Cambodia, says the Soviet Union, financial
supporter for the Hanoi government, must use its influence to end
Vietnam's nine-year occupation of Cambodia.
   The main factions in the Cambodian conflict _ the three-party
resistance coalition, the Vietnam-backed Hun Sen government in
Phnom Penh and Vietnam _ are scheduled to gather in Jakarta next
week to set an agenda for peace negotiations.
   Vietnam, battered by economic crisis and natural disasters at
home, has pledged to withdraw 50,000 troops this year and remove
its total force of about 120,000 by 1990.
   But prospects for peace are clouded by squabbling within the
resistance coalition, the resignation of coalition leader Prince
Norodom Sihanouk and the future role of the Khmer Rouge, which
ruled Cambodia from 1975 to 1978. Under Khmer Rouge rule, hundreds
of thousands of Cambodians were killed.
   Soviet and Chinese involvement is considered crucial if peace is
to last in the Southeast Asian nation.
   A settlement to the Cambodian question would also set the stage
for the first Chinese-Soviet summit in 30 years.
   Chinese senior leader Deng Xiaoping and Soviet Communist Party
chief Mikhail Gorbachev have expressed interest in a summit, but
Deng has stressed that the Kremlin must first remove what China
calls the ``three obstacles,'' particularly the problem of Cambodia.
   The Soviet Union has moved to remove the other two obstacles by
beginning a withdrawal of its troops from Afghanistan and easing
tensions along the Chinese border by reducing its troop strength in
Mongolia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
