<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Aug. 5-7, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bill Kirchenbauer Went From Class Clown to Standup Comic</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With his name and a birthplace like Salzburg,
Austria, you might expect comedian Bill Kirchenbauer to talk like
Arnold Schwarzenegger.
   On request, Kirchenbauer does a pretty fair Schwarzenegger, but
his otherwise unaccented speech reflects his peripatetic upbringing
as an Army brat.
   ``I went to 13 schools in 12 years,'' he said. ``In just one
year I went to four schools. I was always the new kid. I was also
the class clown. They can't get mad at you if you're funny.''
   Kirchenbauer is still funny, both as a standup comedian and as
the star of the ABC comedy show ``Just the 10 of Us.'' The show, a
spinoff of ``Growing Pains,'' made its debut in the spring and will
return in the fall. He had originally auditioned for another role
on ``Growing Pains,'' which he didn't get. But they liked him so
much they offered him the role of Coach.
   He plays Coach Lubbock, who loses his job at Dewey High School
on ``Growing Pains'' and is forced to uproot his large family and
take a new job at an all-boys prep school in a small town. He and
his wife, played by Deborah Harmon, have five daughters, two sons,
and one child on the way.
   ``Coach Lubbock was probably named after the city in Texas,''
said Kirchenbauer. ``I lived there, too, when Dad was in the Army.
I was born in Salzburg, then I lived just about everywhere, from
Alaska to Florida. I think that had a lot to do with my becoming a
standup comedian. I moved so much I became the class clown to get
along. I began to look at each class as an audience. I said if you
squint it does look like an audience.
   ``My father was a sergeant-major, although he's now retired. The
first place I can remember was Fort Benning, Ga. We lived on
Ingersol Loop. My mother called me Billiker Boop from Ingersol
Loop. I've never been in the Army myself. I don't take orders very
well, except from a director.''
   He said he had been an entertainer for as long as he could
remember. ``When I was 5 I began working with puppets,'' he said.
``I always put on a show before Christmas. I had a Jerry Mahoney
puppet my parents gave me. Then around 12 they started looking like
dolls so I quit.
   ``In my teens I started doing impressions. I did shows at the
American Legion and places like that. But doing impressions is very
limited. All you can do is take people out of context. And so many
people did impressions better than me. Then I began to do
impressions of things. Like garbage trucks and typewriters and
roller deodorant.''
   He had a job selling video editing equipment, but about 10 years
ago he quit and worked full-time as a comedian.
   Kirchenbauer had previously worked with Alan Thicke when he
produced ``Fernwood 2-Night'' and ``America 2-Night.'' Kirchenbauer
played egotistical singer Tony Roletti.
   He said he sees Coach as a man who's idealistic about the way he
raises his family. ``He just wants the American dream for them,''
he said. ``My wife says he's like me: a bossy know-it-all, but a
sweet kind of guy who would return a wallet if he found it.''
   Kirchenbauer said the thing he likes most about the show is that
he doesn't have to travel as much. ``I enjoy doing the standup, but
the travel gets you down,'' he said. ``Some people get rowdy in the
clubs. I had to knock out a guy in St. Louis. I was using a big
flashlight in my act and I hit him over the head with it. People
think it's a game. You yell at the comedian and he yells back at
you.''
   Kirchenbauer has been appearing on NBC's ``Tonight Show'' for
eight years. The first time he was asked to be on the show he
turned it down. He'd won a competition in San Francisco for standup
comics and he got the call after his picture ran in the Los Angeles
Times. His manager told him he shouldn't go on ``The Tonight Show''
on a gimmick.
   ``I played the coach for six weeks on `Just the 10 of Us' and
now people think that's all I can do,'' he said. ``I've been doing
comedy for more than 10 years.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend, Aug. 5-7</NOTE>
