<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Commodities, Adv 23-24-1st Add,0240</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 23</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 24</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions July 23-24</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some commodity price trends for the past week.
   Grain and soybean futures retreated on the Chicago Board of
Trade.
   Wheat for delivery in September settled Friday at $3.84{ a
bushel compared with $3.93{ a week earlier; September corn fell to
$3.12{ a bushel from $3.43; September oats skidded to $2.60 a
bushel from $3.17{; and August soybeans plunged to $8.30{ a bushel
from $9.91{.
   Livestock and meat futures rose on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   August live cattle advanced to 66.12 cents a pound from 64.27
cents; August feeder cattle rose to 77.37 cents a pound from 74.75
cents; August hogs finished at 46.12 cents a pound compared with
44.37 cents; and July frozen pork bellies expired Friday at 39.75
cents a pound compared with 37.30 cents a week earlier.
   Precious metals moved higher on New York's Commodity Exchange.
   August gold advanced to $442.90 a troy ounce from $441.30; July
silver moved to $7.606 a troy ounce from $7.310.
   Energy futures leaped higher on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil for September delivery settled
at $16.38 a barrel, up from $14.97; August heating oil surged to
44.95 cents a gallon from 41.12 cents; unleaded gasoline improved
to 52.07 cents a gallon from 49.73 cents.
</TEXT>
