<HEAD>Oil Prices Little Changed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices were little changed after
falling in early trading and then recovering on technical factors.
   The September contract for the benchmark U.S. crude oil, West
Texas Intermediate, fell 1 cent to $16.38 a 42-gallon barrel Friday
on the New York Mercantile Exchange. On Thursday, the contract rose
34 cents.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, the contract for
August delivery of unleaded gasoline slipped 0.03 cent to 52.07
cents a gallon, while August home heating oil fell 0.58 cent to
44.95 cents a gallon.
   ``It was a mixed-bag session,'' said John Azarow, a trader with
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Early trading was dominated by events in the Persian Gulf,
Azarow said.
   Traders became pessimistic about the impact the proposed
cease-fire between Iran and Iraq could have on already abundant
world oil supplies, Azarow said. Both countries could step up oil
production, adding to the glut, as they try to repair their
economies following the war, he said.
   Traders were thinking, ``Maybe the outbreak of peace is not that
good for prices after all,'' Azarow said.
   Contracts then fell to their lows _ with the September West
Texas Intermediate contract sinking to $16.12 _ after reports of an
Iraqi attack on Iran, Azarow said.
   But when prices did not fall further, the session turned around
on technical factors, Azarow said.
   ``New buyers felt confident because the market showed some
support,'' he said.
</TEXT>
